"use strict";(self.webpackChunkxxzkid_docusaurus=self.webpackChunkxxzkid_docusaurus||[]).push([[5117],{58621(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"/openclaw-start","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2026/openclaw-start/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/openclaw-start.md","title":"Install OpenClaw and Connect a Feishu Bot","description":"Install OpenClaw, configure model authorization and its gateway, connect a Feishu bot, grant permissions, subscribe to events, and secure the deployment.","date":"2026-04-04T12:19:36.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"AI","permalink":"/en/tags/ai"},{"inline":true,"label":"OpenClaw","permalink":"/en/tags/open-claw"},{"inline":true,"label":"Claude","permalink":"/en/tags/claude"},{"inline":true,"label":"ChatGPT","permalink":"/en/tags/chat-gpt"}],"readingTime":2.49,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Install OpenClaw and Connect a Feishu Bot","date":"2026-04-04T12:19:36.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2026/openclaw-start/","tags":["AI","OpenClaw","Claude","ChatGPT"],"description":"Install OpenClaw, configure model authorization and its gateway, connect a Feishu bot, grant permissions, subscribe to events, and secure the deployment.","keywords":["OpenClaw Feishu bot","AI office assistant","Feishu chatbot setup"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"nextItem":{"title":"Deploy MinIO with Docker Compose: A Practical Quick Start","permalink":"/en/2025/minio-quickstart/"}},"content":"This guide describes the end-to-end structure for connecting an OpenClaw deployment to a Feishu bot and using it as an internal AI assistant.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## 1. Prepare the runtime\\n\\nInstall the runtime and dependencies required by the OpenClaw release used by the project. Keep the application, plugin, and model-provider versions pinned, and store configuration outside source control.\\n\\nAfter installation, start the service locally and confirm its health endpoint and logs before exposing any network port.\\n\\n## 2. Configure the model provider\\n\\nCreate credentials for the selected model provider and place them in environment variables or a secret manager. Configure the model name, API endpoint, timeout, retry policy, and token or spending limits.\\n\\nDo not embed model keys in frontend code, screenshots, bot messages, or committed configuration files. Use a separate key and account for production.\\n\\n## 3. Configure the OpenClaw gateway\\n\\nThe gateway receives Feishu events and sends messages to the model-backed agent. Configure a stable public HTTPS callback URL, request timeouts, allowed tenants, and logging that excludes message content and credentials.\\n\\nPlace the service behind a reverse proxy when appropriate, and restrict administrative endpoints to trusted networks.\\n\\n## 4. Create the Feishu application\\n\\nIn the Feishu developer console:\\n\\n1. Create an internal application.\\n2. Enable the bot capability.\\n3. Record the App ID and App Secret securely.\\n4. Add only the message and user permissions required by the assistant.\\n5. Configure the event-subscription callback URL and verification token.\\n6. Subscribe to the message events required by the integration.\\n7. Publish the application to the intended organization scope.\\n\\nPermission names and console locations can change, so follow the exact UI and documentation for the current Feishu platform version.\\n\\n## 5. Verify event handling\\n\\nFeishu first verifies the callback endpoint. The service must validate the request signature or verification token before accepting events.\\n\\nTest with a dedicated chat and account. Confirm that:\\n\\n- the callback receives the event once;\\n- duplicate event IDs are ignored;\\n- bot messages do not trigger an infinite reply loop;\\n- user and tenant scope are enforced;\\n- long model responses are split or formatted correctly;\\n- timeouts return a controlled message instead of failing silently.\\n\\n## 6. Security and operations\\n\\nTreat chat messages as potentially sensitive business data. Define what content may be sent to the model provider, apply redaction where required, and make retention and audit behavior explicit.\\n\\nUse least-privilege Feishu permissions, rotate secrets, verify webhook signatures, rate-limit requests, and isolate tool execution. Any feature that can read files, invoke commands, query internal systems, or send messages should require explicit authorization and allowlisted operations.\\n\\nMonitor callback errors, model latency, token use, failed replies, duplicate events, and provider outages. Add a circuit breaker or fallback response so a model failure does not overload Feishu retries.\\n\\n## 7. Production checklist\\n\\nBefore rollout, complete a small pilot with synthetic or low-sensitivity data. Document the bot\'s scope, supported commands, escalation path, model limitations, and data policy. Test secret rotation, service restart, network interruption, duplicate delivery, and rollback of the OpenClaw configuration."},{"id":"/minio-quickstart","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2025/minio-quickstart/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/minio-quickstart.md","title":"Deploy MinIO with Docker Compose: A Practical Quick Start","description":"Deploy MinIO with Docker Compose, persistent storage, a separate console port, secure credentials, health checks, TLS, backups, and production safeguards.","date":"2025-12-09T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"minio","permalink":"/en/tags/minio"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":2.15,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Deploy MinIO with Docker Compose: A Practical Quick Start","date":"2025-12-09T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2025/minio-quickstart/","tags":["minio","java"],"description":"Deploy MinIO with Docker Compose, persistent storage, a separate console port, secure credentials, health checks, TLS, backups, and production safeguards.","keywords":["MinIO Docker Compose","self-hosted object storage","MinIO deployment"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Install OpenClaw and Connect a Feishu Bot","permalink":"/en/2026/openclaw-start/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Self-Host n8n with Docker Compose Securely","permalink":"/en/2025/n8n-quickstart/"}},"content":"MinIO provides an S3-compatible object storage API that works well for development, private clouds, backups, and application file storage. This guide starts with a single-node Docker Compose deployment and then explains what must change before exposing it to production traffic.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Prerequisites\\n\\nInstall Docker Engine and the Docker Compose plugin, then verify them:\\n\\n```bash\\ndocker version\\ndocker compose version\\n```\\n\\nCreate directories for persistent data and configuration:\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo mkdir -p /srv/minio/data\\nsudo chown -R 1000:1000 /srv/minio\\n```\\n\\n## Docker Compose configuration\\n\\nCreate `compose.yaml`:\\n\\n```yaml\\nservices:\\n  minio:\\n    image: quay.io/minio/minio:RELEASE.2024-09-22T00-33-43Z\\n    container_name: minio\\n    command: server /data --console-address \\":9001\\"\\n    restart: unless-stopped\\n    environment:\\n      MINIO_ROOT_USER: ${MINIO_ROOT_USER}\\n      MINIO_ROOT_PASSWORD: ${MINIO_ROOT_PASSWORD}\\n    volumes:\\n      - /srv/minio/data:/data\\n    ports:\\n      - \\"9000:9000\\"\\n      - \\"9001:9001\\"\\n    healthcheck:\\n      test: [\\"CMD\\", \\"curl\\", \\"-f\\", \\"http://localhost:9000/minio/health/live\\"]\\n      interval: 30s\\n      timeout: 10s\\n      retries: 3\\n```\\n\\nStore credentials in a local `.env` file and keep it out of version control:\\n\\n```dotenv\\nMINIO_ROOT_USER=minio-root\\nMINIO_ROOT_PASSWORD=replace-with-a-long-random-secret\\n```\\n\\nStart the service and inspect its health:\\n\\n```bash\\ndocker compose up -d\\ndocker compose ps\\ndocker compose logs --tail=100 minio\\n```\\n\\nThe S3 API listens on port `9000`; the administration console uses `9001`.\\n\\n## Configure the MinIO client\\n\\nInstall the official `mc` client, then create an alias:\\n\\n```bash\\nmc alias set local http://127.0.0.1:9000 minio-root \'your-password\'\\nmc admin info local\\nmc mb local/example\\nmc ls local\\n```\\n\\nApplications should not use the root account. Create a dedicated user and attach only the policy it needs:\\n\\n```bash\\nmc admin user add local app-user \'another-long-random-secret\'\\nmc admin policy attach local readwrite --user app-user\\n```\\n\\nFor production, replace the broad `readwrite` policy with a bucket-specific policy.\\n\\n## Production checklist\\n\\nA running container is not yet a resilient storage service:\\n\\n- Terminate TLS at MinIO or a trusted reverse proxy, and do not expose the console publicly without access controls.\\n- Pin an image release, test upgrades in staging, and read the release notes before changing versions.\\n- Use multiple drives and nodes when availability matters. A single data directory has no disk redundancy.\\n- Back up configuration and critical objects to a separate failure domain.\\n- Monitor disk capacity, request errors, latency, and node health.\\n- Restrict ports with a firewall and rotate credentials regularly.\\n\\n## Common problems\\n\\nIf the container exits immediately, check directory ownership and `docker compose logs`. If S3 requests work locally but fail through a proxy, verify forwarded headers, the public server URL, TLS configuration, and request-size limits. Clock drift can also break signed S3 requests, so keep the host synchronized with NTP."},{"id":"/n8n-quickstart","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2025/n8n-quickstart/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/n8n-quickstart.md","title":"Self-Host n8n with Docker Compose Securely","description":"Self-host n8n with Docker Compose, persistent data, encryption keys, correct webhook URLs, HTTPS reverse proxy settings, backups, and update practices.","date":"2025-12-09T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"n8n","permalink":"/en/tags/n-8-n"},{"inline":true,"label":"ai","permalink":"/en/tags/ai"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":2.17,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Self-Host n8n with Docker Compose Securely","date":"2025-12-09T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2025/n8n-quickstart/","tags":["n8n","ai","java"],"description":"Self-host n8n with Docker Compose, persistent data, encryption keys, correct webhook URLs, HTTPS reverse proxy settings, backups, and update practices.","keywords":["self-host n8n","n8n Docker Compose","n8n webhook setup"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Deploy MinIO with Docker Compose: A Practical Quick Start","permalink":"/en/2025/minio-quickstart/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Migrate MinIO Data Safely with mc mirror","permalink":"/en/2025/minio-data-migration/"}},"content":"n8n is a workflow automation platform that can connect APIs, databases, AI services, and internal tools. A self-hosted instance may contain production credentials and business data, so persistence, encryption, HTTPS, access control, and backups should be part of the first deployment.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Docker Compose configuration\\n\\nCreate a dedicated directory and a `.env` file containing a stable encryption key:\\n\\n```dotenv\\nN8N_HOST=n8n.example.com\\nN8N_ENCRYPTION_KEY=replace-with-a-long-random-value\\nTZ=UTC\\n```\\n\\nNever change or lose `N8N_ENCRYPTION_KEY` after credentials have been saved. Without it, encrypted credentials may become unreadable.\\n\\nCreate `compose.yaml`:\\n\\n```yaml\\nservices:\\n  n8n:\\n    image: docker.n8n.io/n8nio/n8n:2.0.0\\n    container_name: n8n\\n    restart: unless-stopped\\n    environment:\\n      - N8N_HOST=${N8N_HOST}\\n      - N8N_PROTOCOL=https\\n      - N8N_PORT=5678\\n      - WEBHOOK_URL=https://${N8N_HOST}/\\n      - N8N_PROXY_HOPS=1\\n      - N8N_ENCRYPTION_KEY=${N8N_ENCRYPTION_KEY}\\n      - GENERIC_TIMEZONE=${TZ}\\n      - TZ=${TZ}\\n    volumes:\\n      - n8n_data:/home/node/.n8n\\n    expose:\\n      - \\"5678\\"\\n\\nvolumes:\\n  n8n_data:\\n```\\n\\nStart and inspect the container:\\n\\n```bash\\ndocker compose up -d\\ndocker compose logs -f --tail=100 n8n\\n```\\n\\nUsing `expose` keeps port 5678 off the public host interface. Place n8n behind an HTTPS reverse proxy on the same Docker network or publish the port only to `127.0.0.1`.\\n\\n## Reverse proxy requirements\\n\\nYour proxy must forward the original host, protocol, and client address. For Nginx, the core location is:\\n\\n```nginx\\nlocation / {\\n    proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:5678;\\n    proxy_http_version 1.1;\\n    proxy_set_header Host $host;\\n    proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;\\n    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;\\n    proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto https;\\n    proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;\\n    proxy_set_header Connection \\"upgrade\\";\\n}\\n```\\n\\nIncorrect `WEBHOOK_URL`, proxy headers, or proxy-hop settings are common reasons test webhooks work but production webhooks point to localhost or use HTTP.\\n\\n## Backups\\n\\nBack up both the database and the encryption key. With the default SQLite setup, the named volume contains the database and instance data. Stop writes or use an application-consistent method before copying it. Larger teams should evaluate PostgreSQL and test a complete restore regularly.\\n\\nExporting workflows is useful, but workflow JSON alone is not a full disaster-recovery backup because credentials, executions, users, and instance configuration live elsewhere.\\n\\n## Security checklist\\n\\n- Use HTTPS and restrict editor access with an identity-aware proxy, VPN, or firewall.\\n- Run the container as its default non-root user.\\n- Keep secrets out of workflow logs and source control.\\n- Limit community nodes and review any node that executes code.\\n- Configure execution retention so old payloads do not grow forever.\\n- Pin versions, read release notes, and back up before upgrades.\\n- Protect public webhooks with signatures, tokens, rate limits, and input validation.\\n\\n## Updating n8n\\n\\nPull and recreate the service after reviewing breaking changes:\\n\\n```bash\\ndocker compose pull\\ndocker compose up -d\\ndocker compose logs --tail=100 n8n\\n```\\n\\nFor important workflows, rehearse upgrades against a restored backup before updating production."},{"id":"/minio-data-migration","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2025/minio-data-migration/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/minio-data-migration.md","title":"Migrate MinIO Data Safely with mc mirror","description":"Migrate MinIO buckets with mc mirror using full and incremental synchronization, validation, versioning checks, policy migration, and a low-downtime cutover plan.","date":"2025-11-27T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"minio","permalink":"/en/tags/minio"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":2.62,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Migrate MinIO Data Safely with mc mirror","date":"2025-11-27T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2025/minio-data-migration/","tags":["minio","java"],"description":"Migrate MinIO buckets with mc mirror using full and incremental synchronization, validation, versioning checks, policy migration, and a low-downtime cutover plan.","keywords":["MinIO migration","mc mirror","S3 object migration"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Self-Host n8n with Docker Compose Securely","permalink":"/en/2025/n8n-quickstart/"},"nextItem":{"title":"openGauss Database Quick Start","permalink":"/en/2025/opengauss-quickstart/"}},"content":"Moving MinIO is more than copying the latest object files. A reliable migration must account for versions, delete markers, metadata, lifecycle rules, access policies, encryption, and writes that occur during the copy. The safest pattern is a full synchronization followed by incremental catch-up and a controlled cutover.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## 1. Configure source and destination aliases\\n\\nInstall a recent MinIO Client release and configure both endpoints:\\n\\n```bash\\nmc alias set old https://old-minio.example.com ACCESS_KEY SECRET_KEY\\nmc alias set new https://new-minio.example.com ACCESS_KEY SECRET_KEY\\nmc admin info old\\nmc admin info new\\n```\\n\\nAvoid placing real secrets in shell history. Prefer environment variables, a restricted configuration file, or a secrets manager.\\n\\n## 2. Inventory the source\\n\\nBefore copying data, record the bucket list and important settings:\\n\\n```bash\\nmc ls old\\nmc admin info old\\nmc ilm rule ls old/my-bucket\\nmc version info old/my-bucket\\n```\\n\\nAlso inventory users, groups, policies, bucket notifications, object-lock settings, replication rules, and server-side encryption keys. `mc mirror` focuses on objects; it does not automatically reproduce every administrative setting.\\n\\n## 3. Run the initial mirror\\n\\nCreate the destination bucket if needed and start the full copy:\\n\\n```bash\\nmc mb --ignore-existing new/my-bucket\\nmc mirror --preserve --overwrite old/my-bucket new/my-bucket\\n```\\n\\nUse `--remove` only when the destination must be an exact mirror and you are certain that destination-only objects may be deleted. Test that behavior on a disposable bucket first.\\n\\nFor a long migration, run the command in a managed terminal session and save logs:\\n\\n```bash\\nmc mirror --preserve --overwrite --json old/my-bucket new/my-bucket\\n```\\n\\n## 4. Catch up new writes\\n\\nWhile applications still write to the old cluster, repeat the mirror to transfer changes. Shortly before cutover:\\n\\n1. Put writers into maintenance or read-only mode.\\n2. Run one final incremental mirror.\\n3. Compare source and destination.\\n4. Switch application endpoints and credentials.\\n5. Keep the old service read-only until validation is complete.\\n\\nThis sequence minimizes downtime without losing objects written during the first copy.\\n\\n## 5. Validate the result\\n\\nCompare object counts and total sizes, but do not treat matching totals as sufficient proof. Sample critical objects and verify metadata, content type, ETag or checksums, application reads, presigned URLs, and permissions.\\n\\n```bash\\nmc du --recursive old/my-bucket\\nmc du --recursive new/my-bucket\\nmc stat old/my-bucket/path/to/object\\nmc stat new/my-bucket/path/to/object\\n```\\n\\nMultipart uploads and encrypted objects can make ETags unsuitable as universal content hashes. Use application-level checksums when correctness is critical.\\n\\n## Versioning and deletion caveats\\n\\nConfirm how the client version you use handles object versions and delete markers. If legal retention, object lock, or historical versions matter, test the complete behavior with representative data before migrating production. For very large or continuously changing datasets, MinIO replication may be a better fit than repeated mirroring.\\n\\n## Rollback plan\\n\\nDo not delete the source immediately. Define a rollback window, preserve DNS or endpoint settings, and document how writes will be reconciled if traffic must return to the old cluster. A successful migration ends only after monitoring confirms normal error rates, latency, permissions, and object integrity."},{"id":"/opengauss-quickstart","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2025/opengauss-quickstart/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/opengauss-quickstart.md","title":"openGauss Database Quick Start","description":"Install openGauss, initialize an instance, create users and databases, enable controlled remote access, and run basic SQL.","date":"2025-11-26T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"opengauss","permalink":"/en/tags/opengauss"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.61,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"openGauss Database Quick Start","date":"2025-11-26T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2025/opengauss-quickstart/","tags":["opengauss","java"],"description":"Install openGauss, initialize an instance, create users and databases, enable controlled remote access, and run basic SQL.","keywords":["openGauss quick start","openGauss install","gsql"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Migrate MinIO Data Safely with mc mirror","permalink":"/en/2025/minio-data-migration/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Configure Proxy Rules with SwitchOmega or ZeroOmega","permalink":"/en/2025/switchomega-config/"}},"content":"openGauss is a relational database with PostgreSQL-influenced tooling and SQL behavior. Follow the exact documentation for the selected release because installation requirements and commands vary.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nAfter installing the packages, initialize and start an instance with the supplied management tools, then connect through `gsql`. Create a dedicated application user and database instead of using the administrator account:\\n\\n```sql\\nCREATE USER app_user IDENTIFIED BY \'long-random-password\';\\nCREATE DATABASE app_db OWNER app_user;\\n```\\n\\nFor remote access, update the listening address and host-based authentication rules, then restrict the database port with a firewall. Test with:\\n\\n```bash\\ngsql -d app_db -U app_user -h 127.0.0.1 -p 5432\\n```\\n\\nBefore production use, configure TLS, backups, archive or replication strategy, resource limits, monitoring, and tested restore procedures."},{"id":"/switchomega-config","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2025/switchomega-config/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/switchomega-config.md","title":"Configure Proxy Rules with SwitchOmega or ZeroOmega","description":"Configure SwitchOmega or ZeroOmega profiles, proxy servers, automatic switching rules, external rule lists, and common troubleshooting checks.","date":"2025-09-13T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"tools","permalink":"/en/tags/tools"},{"inline":true,"label":"switchomega","permalink":"/en/tags/switchomega"}],"readingTime":1.41,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Configure Proxy Rules with SwitchOmega or ZeroOmega","date":"2025-09-13T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2025/switchomega-config/","tags":["tools","switchomega"],"description":"Configure SwitchOmega or ZeroOmega profiles, proxy servers, automatic switching rules, external rule lists, and common troubleshooting checks.","keywords":["SwitchOmega configuration","ZeroOmega proxy rules","browser proxy extension"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"openGauss Database Quick Start","permalink":"/en/2025/opengauss-quickstart/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Build a Safe Batch File Renaming Tool in Java","permalink":"/en/2025/file-rename-quickstart/"}},"content":"SwitchOmega and its maintained alternatives such as ZeroOmega let a browser select different proxy profiles according to URL rules.\\n\\nThe extension only chooses a configured proxy server; it does not provide a proxy service itself. Before importing a third-party rule list, verify its source and avoid routing passwords or other sensitive traffic through an untrusted proxy.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Install the extension\\n\\nDownload a release from the ZeroOmega project:\\n\\n- Chrome and Chromium-based browsers use the `.crx` package when manual installation is supported.\\n- Firefox uses the `.xpi` package.\\n\\nRelease page:\\n\\n```text\\nhttps://github.com/zero-peak/ZeroOmega/releases\\n```\\n\\nBrowser extension policies change over time. On managed Chrome installations, manual `.crx` installation may be blocked, so use an approved extension store or the organization\'s deployment policy when required.\\n\\n## Create a proxy profile\\n\\nOpen the extension and create a proxy profile. Enter the proxy protocol, host, and port supplied by your own proxy service. Test the profile directly before adding automatic switching rules.\\n\\n## Configure automatic switching\\n\\nOpen the **Auto Switch** profile, add a rule-list condition, and enter a trusted rule-list URL, for example:\\n\\n```text\\nhttps://raw.githubusercontent.com/gfwlist/gfwlist/master/gfwlist.txt\\n```\\n\\nChoose the proxy profile for requests that match the rule list. Configure a direct or fallback profile for unmatched requests, then apply the changes.\\n\\n## Troubleshooting\\n\\nWhen a site does not use the expected route:\\n\\n1. Confirm that the proxy profile works when selected manually.\\n2. Refresh the external rule list and inspect whether the domain is included.\\n3. Check rule order because earlier rules may take precedence.\\n4. Verify that another VPN, system proxy, or browser policy is not overriding the extension.\\n5. Review DNS behavior, authentication errors, and the proxy server logs."},{"id":"/file-rename-quickstart","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2025/file-rename-quickstart/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/file-rename-quickstart.md","title":"Build a Safe Batch File Renaming Tool in Java","description":"Rename files in batches with Java regular expressions while adding previews, collision checks, validation, and rollback-friendly behavior.","date":"2025-06-16T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"file-renaming","permalink":"/en/tags/file-renaming"},{"inline":true,"label":"tools","permalink":"/en/tags/tools"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.99,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Build a Safe Batch File Renaming Tool in Java","date":"2025-06-16T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2025/file-rename-quickstart/","tags":["file-renaming","tools","java"],"description":"Rename files in batches with Java regular expressions while adding previews, collision checks, validation, and rollback-friendly behavior.","keywords":["Java batch rename files","regex file renaming","safe file rename tool"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Configure Proxy Rules with SwitchOmega or ZeroOmega","permalink":"/en/2025/switchomega-config/"},"nextItem":{"title":"npm install Hangs? A Systematic Troubleshooting Guide","permalink":"/en/2025/npm-install-hang/"}},"content":"Batch renaming is less about speed than preventing overwrites and irreversible mistakes. A reliable tool should first generate a preview, detect duplicate target names and invalid paths, and require confirmation before changing files.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nThe following example appends `.json` to filenames made of six digits:\\n\\n```java\\nimport java.io.File;\\nimport java.util.regex.Matcher;\\nimport java.util.regex.Pattern;\\n\\nString directory = \\"C:\\\\\\\\tests\\";\\nString matchRegex = \\"(\\\\\\\\d{6})\\";\\nString replaceRegex = \\"$1.json\\";\\n\\nPattern pattern = Pattern.compile(matchRegex);\\nFile folder = new File(directory);\\n\\nif (folder.isDirectory()) {\\n    File[] files = folder.listFiles();\\n    if (files != null) {\\n        System.out.println(\\"files: \\" + files.length);\\n\\n        for (File source : files) {\\n            Matcher matcher = pattern.matcher(source.getName());\\n            if (!matcher.matches()) {\\n                continue;\\n            }\\n\\n            String targetName = matcher.replaceAll(replaceRegex);\\n            File target = new File(source.getParentFile(), targetName);\\n\\n            System.out.printf(\\"%s -> %s%n\\", source.getName(), targetName);\\n\\n            if (target.exists()) {\\n                System.err.println(\\"Skipped because the target already exists: \\" + target);\\n                continue;\\n            }\\n\\n            if (!source.renameTo(target)) {\\n                System.err.println(\\"Rename failed: \\" + source);\\n            }\\n        }\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\n## Recommended improvements\\n\\nFor production code, use `java.nio.file.Files.move` so failures produce useful exceptions:\\n\\n```java\\nFiles.move(source.toPath(), target.toPath());\\n```\\n\\nBefore applying changes:\\n\\n1. Build the complete source-to-target mapping.\\n2. Reject duplicate target paths and existing files.\\n3. Print or export a preview.\\n4. Store a reverse mapping for rollback.\\n5. Apply moves only after validation succeeds.\\n\\nAlso decide explicitly whether symbolic links, hidden files, directories, and recursive traversal are allowed."},{"id":"/npm-install-hang","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2025/npm-install-hang/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/npm-install-hang.md","title":"npm install Hangs? A Systematic Troubleshooting Guide","description":"Diagnose npm install hangs using verbose logs, registry and proxy checks, cache verification, lockfile analysis, lifecycle script isolation, and Node.js compatibility.","date":"2025-05-29T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"npm","permalink":"/en/tags/npm"},{"inline":true,"label":"javascript","permalink":"/en/tags/javascript"}],"readingTime":2.34,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"npm install Hangs? A Systematic Troubleshooting Guide","date":"2025-05-29T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2025/npm-install-hang/","tags":["npm","javascript"],"description":"Diagnose npm install hangs using verbose logs, registry and proxy checks, cache verification, lockfile analysis, lifecycle script isolation, and Node.js compatibility.","keywords":["npm install hangs","npm install stuck","npm troubleshooting"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Build a Safe Batch File Renaming Tool in Java","permalink":"/en/2025/file-rename-quickstart/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Build a FreeSWITCH Docker Image","permalink":"/en/2025/freeswitch-docker/"}},"content":"When `npm install` appears frozen, repeatedly restarting it usually hides the useful evidence. The delay is commonly caused by network access, proxy configuration, dependency resolution, a lifecycle script, native compilation, cache damage, or a Node.js version mismatch.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## 1. Capture detailed logs\\n\\nRun the install with verbose output:\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm install --verbose\\n```\\n\\nAlso record the active toolchain and configuration:\\n\\n```bash\\nnode --version\\nnpm --version\\nnpm config get registry\\nnpm config list\\n```\\n\\nA line such as `idealTree:userRequests` describes the dependency-resolution stage; it is not the root cause by itself. Inspect the requests and messages immediately before and after it.\\n\\n## 2. Test registry and DNS access\\n\\nVerify that npm can reach the registry:\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm ping\\nnpm view lodash version\\ncurl -I https://registry.npmjs.org/\\n```\\n\\nIf these commands are slow, check DNS, VPN, firewall, corporate TLS inspection, and proxy settings. Review both npm-specific and environment proxies:\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm config get proxy\\nnpm config get https-proxy\\nenv | grep -i proxy\\n```\\n\\nRemove stale npm proxy values when they are no longer required:\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm config delete proxy\\nnpm config delete https-proxy\\n```\\n\\nDo not disable TLS verification as a permanent workaround. Install the correct organization CA certificate instead.\\n\\n## 3. Verify the cache\\n\\nUse npm\'s built-in verification first:\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm cache verify\\n```\\n\\nCache deletion should be a targeted experiment, not the default first step. If verification reports corruption and you have ruled out network problems, use:\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm cache clean --force\\n```\\n\\n## 4. Separate dependency resolution from scripts\\n\\nPackages may run `preinstall`, `install`, or `postinstall` scripts that download binaries or compile native modules. Test without scripts:\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm install --ignore-scripts\\n```\\n\\nIf that completes, inspect lifecycle scripts and rerun the relevant one with foreground output:\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm install --foreground-scripts --verbose\\n```\\n\\nNative builds may require Python, a C/C++ toolchain, and platform development headers.\\n\\n## 5. Check the lockfile and Node version\\n\\nFor CI and reproducible installs, prefer:\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm ci\\n```\\n\\nIt requires `package.json` and `package-lock.json` to agree. Do not delete a committed lockfile casually; doing so changes the resolved dependency graph. Confirm the project\'s supported Node version through `.nvmrc`, `.node-version`, the `engines` field, or project documentation.\\n\\n## 6. Find the slow package\\n\\nUseful experiments include:\\n\\n```bash\\nnpm install --timing\\nnpm explain package-name\\nnpm ls\\n```\\n\\nCheck the npm debug log path printed by the failed command. Git-based dependencies may be waiting on SSH credentials, inaccessible hosts, or Git LFS. Browser automation packages often download large binaries and can be blocked by proxies.\\n\\n## A reliable cleanup sequence\\n\\nAfter preserving the original error, a controlled local retry is:\\n\\n```bash\\nrm -rf node_modules\\nnpm cache verify\\nnpm ci --verbose\\n```\\n\\nKeep the lockfile unless you intentionally want to update dependencies. In CI, add explicit timeouts and cache keys based on the lockfile so a stalled registry request cannot block a runner indefinitely."},{"id":"/freeswitch-docker","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2025/freeswitch-docker/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/freeswitch-docker.md","title":"Build a FreeSWITCH Docker Image","description":"Build a FreeSWITCH container image with selected modules, mounted configuration, SIP and RTP ports, and audio-network troubleshooting.","date":"2025-05-12T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"freeswitch","permalink":"/en/tags/freeswitch"},{"inline":true,"label":"docker","permalink":"/en/tags/docker"}],"readingTime":0.82,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Build a FreeSWITCH Docker Image","date":"2025-05-12T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2025/freeswitch-docker/","tags":["freeswitch","docker"],"description":"Build a FreeSWITCH container image with selected modules, mounted configuration, SIP and RTP ports, and audio-network troubleshooting.","keywords":["FreeSWITCH Docker image","SIP RTP Docker","FreeSWITCH build"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"npm install Hangs? A Systematic Troubleshooting Guide","permalink":"/en/2025/npm-install-hang/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Set Up a Lightweight HTTP Proxy with Tinyproxy","permalink":"/en/2025/http-proxy-with-tinyproxy/"}},"content":"A FreeSWITCH image should be reproducible, minimal, and explicit about compiled modules. Pin the source or package version and separate build dependencies from the runtime image.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nUse a multi-stage build: compile FreeSWITCH and required codecs in the builder stage, then copy only runtime libraries, modules, sounds, and binaries into the final image. Run as a non-root user where practical.\\n\\nMount configuration, recordings, certificates, and persistent databases deliberately rather than hiding important state inside the container filesystem.\\n\\nSIP signaling commonly uses ports such as `5060` and `5080`, while RTP requires a configured UDP range. Publishing only the SIP port is not enough for two-way audio. Ensure the container, host firewall, cloud security group, NAT, and FreeSWITCH external IP settings agree on the RTP range.\\n\\nFor production, avoid host networking unless justified, protect the event socket and management interfaces, rate-limit unauthenticated traffic, monitor registrations and call quality, and test one-way-audio, codec negotiation, and NAT traversal from external networks."},{"id":"/http-proxy-with-tinyproxy","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2025/http-proxy-with-tinyproxy/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/http-proxy-with-tinyproxy.md","title":"Set Up a Lightweight HTTP Proxy with Tinyproxy","description":"Install Tinyproxy, configure its listening port and access controls, run it in the foreground, and verify proxy traffic with curl.","date":"2025-05-09T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"proxy","permalink":"/en/tags/proxy"},{"inline":true,"label":"tinyproxy","permalink":"/en/tags/tinyproxy"},{"inline":true,"label":"http","permalink":"/en/tags/http"}],"readingTime":0.95,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Set Up a Lightweight HTTP Proxy with Tinyproxy","date":"2025-05-09T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2025/http-proxy-with-tinyproxy/","tags":["proxy","tinyproxy","http"],"description":"Install Tinyproxy, configure its listening port and access controls, run it in the foreground, and verify proxy traffic with curl.","keywords":["Tinyproxy setup","HTTP proxy server","lightweight proxy"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Build a FreeSWITCH Docker Image","permalink":"/en/2025/freeswitch-docker/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Run Specific Tests with Maven","permalink":"/en/2025/mvn-testcase/"}},"content":"Tinyproxy is a lightweight HTTP proxy suitable for small controlled environments. It is not a VPN and does not automatically encrypt traffic between the client and proxy.\\n\\nAn open proxy can be abused quickly, so restrict source IP addresses, listening interfaces, and firewall rules before exposing the service.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Optional test container\\n\\n```bash\\ndocker run -itd --name ubuntu-test -p 8888:8888 ubuntu:22.04\\ndocker exec -it ubuntu-test bash\\n```\\n\\n## Install Tinyproxy\\n\\n```bash\\napt update\\napt install tinyproxy -y\\n```\\n\\n## Create a configuration\\n\\nCreate `/tmp/tinyproxy.conf`:\\n\\n```text\\nPort 8888\\nListen 0.0.0.0\\nTimeout 600\\nBindSame yes\\nMaxClients 1024\\nDisableViaHeader Yes\\n\\n# Replace with trusted client networks.\\nAllow 192.168.1.0/24\\n```\\n\\nDo not leave `Allow 0.0.0.0/0` enabled on a public server.\\n\\n## Start the service\\n\\n```bash\\ntinyproxy -d -c /tmp/tinyproxy.conf\\n```\\n\\nFor long-running deployments, use the distribution service unit and store configuration under `/etc/tinyproxy/`.\\n\\n## Verify the proxy\\n\\n```bash\\nexport PROXY_IP=203.0.113.10\\ncurl --proxy \\"http://$PROXY_IP:8888\\" https://httpbin.org/ip\\n```\\n\\nThe response should show the proxy server\'s public address. If it fails, inspect the Tinyproxy log, firewall, cloud security group, `Allow` rules, and whether the proxy can resolve DNS and reach the destination."},{"id":"/mvn-testcase","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2025/mvn-testcase/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/mvn-testcase.md","title":"Run Specific Tests with Maven","description":"Run all tests, one test class, one method, patterns, and selected modules with Maven Surefire options.","date":"2025-04-17T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"maven","permalink":"/en/tags/maven"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.63,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Run Specific Tests with Maven","date":"2025-04-17T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2025/mvn-testcase/","tags":["maven","java"],"description":"Run all tests, one test class, one method, patterns, and selected modules with Maven Surefire options.","keywords":["Maven specific test","Maven Dtest","Maven multi module test"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Set Up a Lightweight HTTP Proxy with Tinyproxy","permalink":"/en/2025/http-proxy-with-tinyproxy/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Common Flutter Development Problems and Fixes","permalink":"/en/2025/flutter-faq/"}},"content":"Maven Surefire accepts the `-Dtest` property for selecting unit tests.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nRun all tests:\\n\\n```bash\\nmvn test\\n```\\n\\nRun one class:\\n\\n```bash\\nmvn -Dtest=UserServiceTest test\\n```\\n\\nRun one method:\\n\\n```bash\\nmvn -Dtest=UserServiceTest#shouldCreateUser test\\n```\\n\\nRun several methods or wildcard patterns:\\n\\n```bash\\nmvn -Dtest=\'UserServiceTest#shouldCreate*\' test\\nmvn -Dtest=\'UserServiceTest,OrderServiceTest\' test\\n```\\n\\nFor a multi-module project, select a module and build required dependencies:\\n\\n```bash\\nmvn -pl service-module -am -Dtest=UserServiceTest test\\n```\\n\\n- `-pl` selects projects from the reactor.\\n- `-am` also builds required upstream modules.\\n- `-DskipTests` compiles tests but skips execution.\\n- `-Dmaven.test.skip=true` skips both test compilation and execution.\\n\\nIntegration tests commonly run through Maven Failsafe during `integration-test` and `verify`, so use the plugin\'s include properties and lifecycle rather than assuming `mvn test` runs them."},{"id":"/flutter-faq","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2025/flutter-faq/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/flutter-faq.md","title":"Common Flutter Development Problems and Fixes","description":"Troubleshoot Flutter SDK setup, dependency downloads, slow Gradle builds, mirror configuration, and project creation.","date":"2025-03-31T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"flutter","permalink":"/en/tags/flutter"},{"inline":true,"label":"android","permalink":"/en/tags/android"}],"readingTime":1.08,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Common Flutter Development Problems and Fixes","date":"2025-03-31T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2025/flutter-faq/","tags":["flutter","android"],"description":"Troubleshoot Flutter SDK setup, dependency downloads, slow Gradle builds, mirror configuration, and project creation.","keywords":["Flutter troubleshooting","Gradle slow","Flutter mirrors"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Run Specific Tests with Maven","permalink":"/en/2025/mvn-testcase/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Install ChromeDriver and Match It with Chrome","permalink":"/en/2025/chromedriver-download/"}},"content":"Flutter build problems often involve several layers at once: the Flutter SDK, Dart, Gradle, Android build tools, repositories, and package versions. Record `flutter doctor -v`, the complete error stack, and reproducible steps before changing caches or mirrors.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Download Flutter\\n\\nA Windows stable archive can be downloaded from the official release storage:\\n\\n```text\\nhttps://storage.googleapis.com/flutter_infra_release/releases/stable/windows/flutter_windows_3.29.2-stable.zip\\n```\\n\\nVerify the current stable version before installation.\\n\\n## Configure package mirrors\\n\\nIn environments where the default endpoints are slow, configure approved mirrors:\\n\\n```text\\nFLUTTER_STORAGE_BASE_URL=https://storage.flutter-io.cn\\nPUB_HOSTED_URL=https://pub.flutter-io.cn\\n```\\n\\n## Diagnose a slow `assembleDebug`\\n\\n```powershell\\ncd android\\n.\\\\gradlew.bat clean\\n.\\\\gradlew.bat assembleDebug --info\\n```\\n\\nUse the verbose output to identify the dependency or repository causing the delay. Avoid manually copying artifacts into Gradle caches unless you fully understand the expected directory and checksum layout.\\n\\n## Configure the Gradle distribution\\n\\nEdit `android/gradle/wrapper/gradle-wrapper.properties`:\\n\\n```properties\\n# distributionUrl=https\\\\://services.gradle.org/distributions/gradle-8.10.2-all.zip\\ndistributionUrl=https\\\\://mirrors.cloud.tencent.com/gradle/gradle-8.10.2-all.zip\\n```\\n\\n## Configure a Maven mirror\\n\\nFor Kotlin DSL projects, edit `android/build.gradle.kts` or the repository-management block used by the project:\\n\\n```kotlin\\nmaven { url = uri(\\"https://mirrors.tencent.com/nexus/repository/maven-public/\\") }\\n```\\n\\n## Create a project\\n\\n```bash\\nflutter create my_app\\ncd my_app\\nflutter run\\n```\\n\\nKeep Flutter, Android Gradle Plugin, Gradle, Kotlin, and Java versions compatible rather than upgrading them independently."},{"id":"/chromedriver-download","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2025/chromedriver-download/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/chromedriver-download.md","title":"Install ChromeDriver and Match It with Chrome","description":"Install ChromeDriver, match browser and driver versions, configure PATH, use Selenium Manager, and troubleshoot Chrome startup failures.","date":"2025-03-15T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"chromedriver","permalink":"/en/tags/chromedriver"},{"inline":true,"label":"selenium","permalink":"/en/tags/selenium"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":1.44,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Install ChromeDriver and Match It with Chrome","date":"2025-03-15T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2025/chromedriver-download/","tags":["chromedriver","selenium","java"],"description":"Install ChromeDriver, match browser and driver versions, configure PATH, use Selenium Manager, and troubleshoot Chrome startup failures.","keywords":["install ChromeDriver","ChromeDriver version match","Selenium Chrome setup"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Common Flutter Development Problems and Fixes","permalink":"/en/2025/flutter-faq/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Install Apache ActiveMQ Artemis","permalink":"/en/2025/apache-artemis-install/"}},"content":"ChromeDriver connects Selenium to the Chrome browser. Most startup failures come from an incompatible browser/driver combination, an incorrect executable path, or a missing browser binary.\\n\\nRecord the versions of Chrome, ChromeDriver, Selenium, the operating system, and the CPU architecture when troubleshooting. Current Selenium releases can usually manage the driver automatically, which is preferable to maintaining a driver manually.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Check the Chrome version\\n\\nOpen the following page in Chrome:\\n\\n```text\\nchrome://settings/help\\n```\\n\\nFor older ChromeDriver releases, the browser and driver generally had to share the same major version. For current Chrome for Testing releases, use the official version-selection data instead of relying on an old three-part matching rule.\\n\\n## Download ChromeDriver\\n\\nUse the official Chrome for Testing page:\\n\\n```text\\nhttps://googlechromelabs.github.io/chrome-for-testing/\\n```\\n\\nDownload the package for the correct operating system and architecture, extract it, and either add the executable directory to `PATH` or pass its path explicitly.\\n\\n## Verify with Selenium\\n\\nWith a modern Selenium version, Selenium Manager can resolve the driver automatically:\\n\\n```python\\nfrom selenium import webdriver\\n\\noptions = webdriver.ChromeOptions()\\n# Set this only when Chrome is installed in a non-standard location.\\n# options.binary_location = \\"/path/to/chrome\\"\\n\\ndriver = webdriver.Chrome(options=options)\\ntry:\\n    driver.get(\\"https://www.example.com\\")\\n    driver.maximize_window()\\nfinally:\\n    driver.quit()\\n```\\n\\nFor older Selenium versions, create a `Service` explicitly instead of using the deprecated `executable_path` argument:\\n\\n```python\\nfrom selenium import webdriver\\nfrom selenium.webdriver.chrome.service import Service\\n\\nservice = Service(\\"/path/to/chromedriver\\")\\ndriver = webdriver.Chrome(service=service)\\ndriver.quit()\\n```\\n\\n## Common errors\\n\\n- **Session not created:** compare the installed Chrome major version with the selected driver.\\n- **Chrome binary not found:** set `options.binary_location` to the actual browser executable.\\n- **Driver executable not found:** fix `PATH`, file permissions, or the `Service` path.\\n- **Browser exits immediately:** inspect ChromeDriver logs, sandbox restrictions, display availability, and container shared-memory limits."},{"id":"/apache-artemis-install","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2025/apache-artemis-install/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/apache-artemis-install.md","title":"Install Apache ActiveMQ Artemis","description":"Install and start Apache ActiveMQ Artemis, create a broker instance, configure JVM memory, expose the management console, and verify ports and persistence.","date":"2025-02-17T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"activemq","permalink":"/en/tags/activemq"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":1.3,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Install Apache ActiveMQ Artemis","date":"2025-02-17T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2025/apache-artemis-install/","tags":["activemq","java"],"description":"Install and start Apache ActiveMQ Artemis, create a broker instance, configure JVM memory, expose the management console, and verify ports and persistence.","keywords":["Apache Artemis install","ActiveMQ Artemis broker","Artemis console"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Install ChromeDriver and Match It with Chrome","permalink":"/en/2025/chromedriver-download/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Install MySQL 8 from a Binary Tarball on Linux","permalink":"/en/2024/linux-install-mysql8-zip/"}},"content":"Apache ActiveMQ Artemis is the next-generation message broker in the Apache ActiveMQ family.\\n\\nA successful process start is only the first step. You should also verify the management port, protocol ports, persistence directory, user accounts, JVM settings, disk capacity, permissions, and monitoring.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Prerequisites\\n\\nArtemis is a Java application. JDK 17 is a suitable baseline for current releases:\\n\\n```bash\\nexport JAVA_HOME=/usr/local/jdk17\\nexport PATH=\\"$JAVA_HOME/bin:$PATH\\"\\njava -version\\n```\\n\\n## Download and extract\\n\\n```bash\\nwget -O apache-artemis-2.39.0-bin.tar.gz \\\\\\n  \'https://www.apache.org/dyn/closer.cgi?filename=activemq/activemq-artemis/2.39.0/apache-artemis-2.39.0-bin.tar.gz&action=download\'\\n\\ntar -zxvf apache-artemis-2.39.0-bin.tar.gz\\ncd apache-artemis-2.39.0\\n```\\n\\n## Create a broker instance\\n\\n```bash\\n./bin/artemis create broker\\n```\\n\\nThe setup wizard asks for the default administrator username and password. Use a strong password and do not reuse development credentials in production.\\n\\nStart the broker from the instance directory:\\n\\n```bash\\ncd broker\\n./bin/artemis run\\n```\\n\\nRun it in the background with the service integration appropriate for your operating system.\\n\\n## Optional configuration\\n\\nAdjust JVM memory in:\\n\\n```text\\nbroker/etc/artemis.profile\\n```\\n\\nReview the `JAVA_ARGS` or Java options section rather than changing memory values blindly.\\n\\nTo change Jolokia CORS rules, edit:\\n\\n```text\\nbroker/etc/jolokia-access.xml\\n```\\n\\nFor example:\\n\\n```xml\\n<allow-origin>*://*</allow-origin>\\n```\\n\\nAllowing every origin is convenient for testing but unsafe on an Internet-facing console. Restrict origins in production.\\n\\nTo listen on all network interfaces, edit:\\n\\n```text\\nbroker/etc/bootstrap.xml\\n```\\n\\n```xml\\n<binding name=\\"artemis\\" uri=\\"http://0.0.0.0:8161\\">\\n```\\n\\nExpose port `8161` only to trusted networks and protect it with authentication and firewall rules."},{"id":"/linux-install-mysql8-zip","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/linux-install-mysql8-zip/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/linux-install-mysql8-zip.md","title":"Install MySQL 8 from a Binary Tarball on Linux","description":"Install MySQL 8 from an official Linux binary tarball with a dedicated user, data directory, initialization, my.cnf, systemd service, and security checks.","date":"2024-09-10T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"linux","permalink":"/en/tags/linux"},{"inline":true,"label":"mysql","permalink":"/en/tags/mysql"}],"readingTime":2.4,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Install MySQL 8 from a Binary Tarball on Linux","date":"2024-09-10T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/linux-install-mysql8-zip/","tags":["linux","mysql"],"description":"Install MySQL 8 from an official Linux binary tarball with a dedicated user, data directory, initialization, my.cnf, systemd service, and security checks.","keywords":["install MySQL 8 Linux tarball","MySQL binary installation","MySQL systemd"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Install Apache ActiveMQ Artemis","permalink":"/en/2025/apache-artemis-install/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Send Email Through NetEase Enterprise Mail with Spring Boot","permalink":"/en/2024/spring-boot-163qy-mail/"}},"content":"A binary tarball installation gives you full control over the MySQL directory and version. Unlike a distribution package, it does not automatically create the system user, configure permissions, install a service, or apply security updates.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## 1. Download and verify the package\\n\\nChoose the archive that matches your CPU architecture and glibc version from the official MySQL downloads page. The example filename below is illustrative:\\n\\n```bash\\nwget https://dev.mysql.com/get/Downloads/MySQL-8.0/mysql-8.0.39-linux-glibc2.28-x86_64.tar.xz\\nsha256sum mysql-8.0.39-linux-glibc2.28-x86_64.tar.xz\\n```\\n\\nCompare the checksum with the value published by MySQL. Install required runtime libraries through your operating system package manager.\\n\\n## 2. Create a service account and directories\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo groupadd --system mysql\\nsudo useradd --system --gid mysql --shell /usr/sbin/nologin mysql\\nsudo tar -xf mysql-8.0.39-linux-glibc2.28-x86_64.tar.xz -C /opt\\nsudo ln -s /opt/mysql-8.0.39-linux-glibc2.28-x86_64 /opt/mysql\\nsudo mkdir -p /var/lib/mysql /var/log/mysql /run/mysqld\\nsudo chown -R mysql:mysql /var/lib/mysql /var/log/mysql /run/mysqld\\n```\\n\\nKeep program files owned by root and writable data directories owned by `mysql`.\\n\\n## 3. Configure MySQL\\n\\nCreate `/etc/my.cnf`:\\n\\n```ini\\n[mysqld]\\nbasedir=/opt/mysql\\ndatadir=/var/lib/mysql\\nsocket=/run/mysqld/mysqld.sock\\npid-file=/run/mysqld/mysqld.pid\\nlog-error=/var/log/mysql/error.log\\nuser=mysql\\nbind-address=127.0.0.1\\ncharacter-set-server=utf8mb4\\n\\n[client]\\nsocket=/run/mysqld/mysqld.sock\\ndefault-character-set=utf8mb4\\n```\\n\\nBinding to localhost is a safe default. If remote clients are required, use a private interface, firewall rules, TLS, and least-privilege database accounts.\\n\\n## 4. Initialize the data directory\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo -u mysql /opt/mysql/bin/mysqld   --defaults-file=/etc/my.cnf   --initialize\\nsudo grep \'temporary password\' /var/log/mysql/error.log\\n```\\n\\nSave the temporary password securely. Do not use `--initialize-insecure` on a production server.\\n\\n## 5. Create a systemd unit\\n\\nCreate `/etc/systemd/system/mysql.service`:\\n\\n```ini\\n[Unit]\\nDescription=MySQL Server\\nAfter=network.target\\n\\n[Service]\\nType=notify\\nUser=mysql\\nGroup=mysql\\nExecStart=/opt/mysql/bin/mysqld --defaults-file=/etc/my.cnf\\nTimeoutStartSec=90\\nRestart=on-failure\\nLimitNOFILE=65535\\nRuntimeDirectory=mysqld\\nRuntimeDirectoryMode=0755\\n\\n[Install]\\nWantedBy=multi-user.target\\n```\\n\\nLoad and start it:\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo systemctl daemon-reload\\nsudo systemctl enable --now mysql\\nsudo systemctl status mysql\\n```\\n\\n## 6. Finish hardening\\n\\nConnect with the temporary password and set a strong replacement, then run:\\n\\n```bash\\n/opt/mysql/bin/mysql_secure_installation\\n```\\n\\nRemove anonymous accounts and test databases, review root access, configure backups, and monitor disk capacity and replication if used. Add `/opt/mysql/bin` to a system-wide PATH only after confirming it cannot be modified by untrusted users.\\n\\n## Upgrades and rollback\\n\\nNever replace the symlink and start a new MySQL binary without reading that release\'s upgrade procedure. Take a tested backup, stop cleanly, preserve the old binaries, and rehearse the change on a copy of the data. Package-managed installations are usually easier to patch; use tarballs only when their control is worth the additional maintenance."},{"id":"/spring-boot-163qy-mail","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/spring-boot-163qy-mail/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/spring-boot-163qy-mail.md","title":"Send Email Through NetEase Enterprise Mail with Spring Boot","description":"Configure Spring Boot SMTP for NetEase enterprise mail with TLS, authorization credentials, timeouts, and authentication troubleshooting.","date":"2024-08-03T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"spring-boot","permalink":"/en/tags/spring-boot"},{"inline":true,"label":"spring","permalink":"/en/tags/spring"},{"inline":true,"label":"mail","permalink":"/en/tags/mail"}],"readingTime":0.59,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Send Email Through NetEase Enterprise Mail with Spring Boot","date":"2024-08-03T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/spring-boot-163qy-mail/","tags":["java","spring-boot","spring","mail"],"description":"Configure Spring Boot SMTP for NetEase enterprise mail with TLS, authorization credentials, timeouts, and authentication troubleshooting.","keywords":["Spring Boot NetEase mail","SMTP TLS","JavaMailSender"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Install MySQL 8 from a Binary Tarball on Linux","permalink":"/en/2024/linux-install-mysql8-zip/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Automate Android Screenshots and Swipes with Python ADB","permalink":"/en/2024/python-adb-short-video/"}},"content":"Spring Boot sends SMTP mail through `JavaMailSender`. Use the exact server, port, encryption mode, and authorization credential supplied by the enterprise mailbox administrator.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```yaml\\nspring:\\n  mail:\\n    host: smtp.qiye.163.com\\n    port: 465\\n    username: user@example.com\\n    password: ${MAIL_PASSWORD}\\n    protocol: smtp\\n    properties:\\n      mail.smtp.auth: true\\n      mail.smtp.ssl.enable: true\\n      mail.smtp.connectiontimeout: 10000\\n      mail.smtp.timeout: 10000\\n      mail.smtp.writetimeout: 10000\\n```\\n\\nA basic send operation:\\n\\n```java\\nSimpleMailMessage message = new SimpleMailMessage();\\nmessage.setFrom(\\"user@example.com\\");\\nmessage.setTo(\\"receiver@example.com\\");\\nmessage.setSubject(\\"Test message\\");\\nmessage.setText(\\"Mail sent by Spring Boot\\");\\nmailSender.send(message);\\n```\\n\\nSome accounts require an app-specific authorization code rather than the login password. Authentication failures can also result from an incorrect sender address, blocked SMTP service, TLS/port mismatch, DNS, firewall rules, or provider rate limits. Keep credentials outside source control."},{"id":"/python-adb-short-video","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/python-adb-short-video/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/python-adb-short-video.md","title":"Automate Android Screenshots and Swipes with Python ADB","description":"Control your own Android test device with Python and adbutils to capture screenshots, pull files, perform swipes, and add essential safety checks.","date":"2024-07-25T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"python","permalink":"/en/tags/python"},{"inline":true,"label":"android","permalink":"/en/tags/android"}],"readingTime":1,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Automate Android Screenshots and Swipes with Python ADB","date":"2024-07-25T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/python-adb-short-video/","tags":["python","android"],"description":"Control your own Android test device with Python and adbutils to capture screenshots, pull files, perform swipes, and add essential safety checks.","keywords":["Python ADB automation","adbutils screenshot","Android swipe script"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Send Email Through NetEase Enterprise Mail with Spring Boot","permalink":"/en/2024/spring-boot-163qy-mail/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Secure File Uploads with Spring Boot","permalink":"/en/2024/spring-boot-file-upload/"}},"content":"This example uses ADB from Python to capture a screenshot from an Android device, copy it to the computer, and perform a swipe gesture.\\n\\nUse ADB automation only on devices and applications you own or are authorized to test. Respect the target platform\'s rules, verify that the intended device is connected, and add delays and stop conditions so the loop cannot run out of control.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Install the dependency\\n\\n```bash\\npip install adbutils==2.7.2\\n```\\n\\nEnable USB debugging, authorize the computer, and verify the connection:\\n\\n```bash\\nadb devices\\n```\\n\\n## Example\\n\\n```python\\nimport time\\nfrom datetime import datetime\\n\\nimport adbutils\\n\\n\\ndef main() -> None:\\n    devices = adbutils.adb.device_list()\\n    if not devices:\\n        raise RuntimeError(\\"No authorized Android device is connected\\")\\n\\n    device = devices[0]\\n\\n    try:\\n        while True:\\n            filename = datetime.now().strftime(\\"%Y%m%d%H%M%S\\") + \\".png\\"\\n            remote_path = \\"/sdcard/DCIM/screenshot.png\\"\\n\\n            device.shell(f\\"screencap -p {remote_path}\\", encoding=None)\\n            device.sync.pull_file(remote_path, filename)\\n            print(f\\"screenshot: {filename}\\")\\n\\n            device.shell(\\"input swipe 760 1600 760 800 200\\")\\n            time.sleep(2)\\n    except KeyboardInterrupt:\\n        print(\\"Stopped\\")\\n\\n\\nif __name__ == \\"__main__\\":\\n    main()\\n```\\n\\nThe swipe coordinates depend on the screen resolution and orientation. For a reusable script, query the display size first, calculate coordinates proportionally, check command results, and use a bounded loop instead of `while True`."},{"id":"/spring-boot-file-upload","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/spring-boot-file-upload/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/spring-boot-file-upload.md","title":"Secure File Uploads with Spring Boot","description":"Implement secure Spring Boot file uploads with MultipartFile, size limits, generated filenames, path validation, content checks, safe downloads, storage isolation, and cleanup.","date":"2024-07-17T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"spring-boot","permalink":"/en/tags/spring-boot"},{"inline":true,"label":"spring","permalink":"/en/tags/spring"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":2.31,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Secure File Uploads with Spring Boot","date":"2024-07-17T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/spring-boot-file-upload/","tags":["spring-boot","spring","java"],"description":"Implement secure Spring Boot file uploads with MultipartFile, size limits, generated filenames, path validation, content checks, safe downloads, storage isolation, and cleanup.","keywords":["Spring Boot file upload","MultipartFile security","secure file download"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Automate Android Screenshots and Swipes with Python ADB","permalink":"/en/2024/python-adb-short-video/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Find a SQLite Database Handle in an Authorized Windows Debugging Lab","permalink":"/en/2024/pcwechat-sqlite3-handle/"}},"content":"File upload endpoints accept attacker-controlled bytes, filenames, sizes, and content types. A secure design limits requests early, generates server-side names, stores files outside the web root, validates paths, and serves downloads with controlled headers.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Configure request limits\\n\\nSet limits appropriate for the application:\\n\\n```yaml\\nspring:\\n  servlet:\\n    multipart:\\n      max-file-size: 20MB\\n      max-request-size: 25MB\\n```\\n\\nAlso configure limits at the reverse proxy and load balancer. Proxy and application limits should agree so oversized requests are rejected predictably.\\n\\n## Store uploads with generated names\\n\\n```java\\n@Service\\npublic class FileStorageService {\\n    private final Path root = Path.of(\\"/srv/myapp/uploads\\")\\n            .toAbsolutePath()\\n            .normalize();\\n\\n    public FileStorageService() throws IOException {\\n        Files.createDirectories(root);\\n    }\\n\\n    public String store(MultipartFile file) throws IOException {\\n        if (file.isEmpty()) {\\n            throw new IllegalArgumentException(\\"Empty file\\");\\n        }\\n\\n        String original = Optional.ofNullable(file.getOriginalFilename())\\n                .orElse(\\"upload\\");\\n        String extension = safeExtension(original);\\n        String storedName = UUID.randomUUID() + extension;\\n        Path destination = root.resolve(storedName).normalize();\\n\\n        if (!destination.getParent().equals(root)) {\\n            throw new SecurityException(\\"Invalid destination\\");\\n        }\\n\\n        try (InputStream input = file.getInputStream()) {\\n            Files.copy(input, destination, StandardCopyOption.COPY_ATTRIBUTES);\\n        }\\n        return storedName;\\n    }\\n\\n    private String safeExtension(String filename) {\\n        String base = Path.of(filename).getFileName().toString();\\n        int dot = base.lastIndexOf(\'.\');\\n        if (dot < 0) return \\"\\";\\n        String extension = base.substring(dot).toLowerCase(Locale.ROOT);\\n        return Set.of(\\".jpg\\", \\".png\\", \\".pdf\\").contains(extension)\\n                ? extension\\n                : \\"\\";\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nNever use the client filename as the storage path. Persist the original display name separately after sanitizing control characters.\\n\\n## Validate actual content\\n\\nThe multipart `Content-Type` and extension are user-supplied. For sensitive workflows, inspect file signatures with a maintained library, decode images before accepting them, and scan untrusted documents with malware tooling. Reject archives unless the product explicitly needs them; archive extraction introduces zip-slip paths and decompression bombs.\\n\\n## Serve files safely\\n\\nResolve only server-generated identifiers and verify the normalized result remains under the storage root. For downloads, set a controlled content type and use `Content-Disposition: attachment` for formats that should not execute in the browser.\\n\\n```java\\n@GetMapping(\\"/files/{id}\\")\\npublic ResponseEntity<Resource> download(@PathVariable String id) throws IOException {\\n    if (!id.matches(\\"[0-9a-fA-F-]{36}\\\\\\\\.(jpg|png|pdf)\\")) {\\n        return ResponseEntity.badRequest().build();\\n    }\\n\\n    Path file = root.resolve(id).normalize();\\n    if (!file.getParent().equals(root) || !Files.isRegularFile(file)) {\\n        return ResponseEntity.notFound().build();\\n    }\\n\\n    Resource resource = new FileSystemResource(file);\\n    return ResponseEntity.ok()\\n            .header(HttpHeaders.CONTENT_DISPOSITION,\\n                    \\"attachment; filename=\\\\\\"\\" + id + \\"\\\\\\"\\")\\n            .body(resource);\\n}\\n```\\n\\nAuthorization must be checked before returning a resource. Do not rely on an unguessable URL as access control.\\n\\n## Operational safeguards\\n\\n- Store uploads on a separate volume with no execute permission where practical.\\n- Apply per-user quotas and rate limits.\\n- Record ownership, checksum, size, and upload time in the database.\\n- Clean up abandoned temporary files and failed database transactions.\\n- Back up metadata and objects consistently.\\n- Use object storage and presigned uploads for large-scale systems.\\n- Test filename encoding, concurrent uploads, disk-full behavior, and interrupted requests.\\n\\nA correct upload controller is only one layer. Reverse-proxy limits, storage permissions, authentication, antivirus policy, observability, and retention rules complete the security model."},{"id":"/pcwechat-sqlite3-handle","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/pcwechat-sqlite3-handle/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/pcwechat-sqlite3-handle.md","title":"Find a SQLite Database Handle in an Authorized Windows Debugging Lab","description":"Trace SQLite calls and inspect registers to identify a database connection handle in an authorized Windows test process.","date":"2024-05-08T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"c-cpp","permalink":"/en/tags/c-cpp"},{"inline":true,"label":"windows","permalink":"/en/tags/windows"},{"inline":true,"label":"sqlite","permalink":"/en/tags/sqlite"}],"readingTime":0.86,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Find a SQLite Database Handle in an Authorized Windows Debugging Lab","date":"2024-05-08T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/pcwechat-sqlite3-handle/","tags":["c-cpp","windows","sqlite"],"description":"Trace SQLite calls and inspect registers to identify a database connection handle in an authorized Windows test process.","keywords":["SQLite handle debugging","Windows process analysis","sqlite3 pointer"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Secure File Uploads with Spring Boot","permalink":"/en/2024/spring-boot-file-upload/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Locate sqlite3_exec in a Windows Application with IDA","permalink":"/en/2024/ida-sqlite3-exec/"}},"content":"A SQLite connection handle is an opaque `sqlite3*` pointer passed to many SQLite APIs. This article describes how to recognize it while debugging a controlled application that you own or are authorized to test.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nBegin with a known call such as `sqlite3_open`, `sqlite3_prepare_v2`, or `sqlite3_exec`. Set a breakpoint at the verified function or wrapper and observe the calling convention for the target architecture. On 32-bit builds, arguments are commonly stack-based; on 64-bit Windows, the first arguments normally arrive in registers.\\n\\nFollow the handle from the open call\'s output into later query calls. Validate it through repeated use and expected SQLite return codes rather than assuming any pointer to database-like memory is correct.\\n\\nASLR changes absolute addresses, so record module-relative offsets and the exact binary hash. Application and SQLite updates can change wrappers, signatures, and data flow.\\n\\nDo not dereference arbitrary pointers or modify live database state. Use synthetic records, copies of test databases, and an isolated environment. Avoid logging credentials, keys, or real message content."},{"id":"/ida-sqlite3-exec","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/ida-sqlite3-exec/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/ida-sqlite3-exec.md","title":"Locate sqlite3_exec in a Windows Application with IDA","description":"Use IDA string references, call graphs, signatures, module bases, and offsets to locate sqlite3_exec in an authorized Windows analysis target.","date":"2024-04-30T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"c-cpp","permalink":"/en/tags/c-cpp"},{"inline":true,"label":"windows","permalink":"/en/tags/windows"},{"inline":true,"label":"sqlite","permalink":"/en/tags/sqlite"}],"readingTime":0.82,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Locate sqlite3_exec in a Windows Application with IDA","date":"2024-04-30T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/ida-sqlite3-exec/","tags":["c-cpp","windows","sqlite"],"description":"Use IDA string references, call graphs, signatures, module bases, and offsets to locate sqlite3_exec in an authorized Windows analysis target.","keywords":["IDA sqlite3_exec","reverse engineering SQLite","function offset analysis"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Find a SQLite Database Handle in an Authorized Windows Debugging Lab","permalink":"/en/2024/pcwechat-sqlite3-handle/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Debug SQLite with OllyICE 1.10","permalink":"/en/2024/ollyice-debug-sqlite3/"}},"content":"This article outlines a static-analysis method for locating a SQLite function inside a Windows application. Apply it only to software you own or are explicitly authorized to inspect.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nStart with a known SQLite build and identify stable strings, imported symbols, error messages, or nearby wrapper functions associated with `sqlite3_exec`. Search those strings in IDA and follow cross-references to candidate call sites.\\n\\nCompare control flow, argument count, call relationships, and surrounding SQLite functions rather than trusting one byte pattern. Compiler optimization, link-time optimization, static linking, and SQLite version changes can alter the generated code substantially.\\n\\nWhen the target uses ASLR, distinguish the module-relative virtual address from the runtime absolute address:\\n\\n```text\\nruntime address = module base + relative offset\\n```\\n\\nValidate the candidate in an isolated test build with synthetic data and a debugger. Record the exact application hash, architecture, module version, image base, and offset. Never reuse an offset across versions without revalidation, and avoid collecting or modifying real user data."},{"id":"/ollyice-debug-sqlite3","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/ollyice-debug-sqlite3/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/ollyice-debug-sqlite3.md","title":"Debug SQLite with OllyICE 1.10","description":"Debug a controlled SQLite sample with OllyICE, set breakpoints, inspect calls and registers, and identify version-dependent function characteristics.","date":"2024-04-27T09:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"c-cpp","permalink":"/en/tags/c-cpp"},{"inline":true,"label":"windows","permalink":"/en/tags/windows"},{"inline":true,"label":"sqlite","permalink":"/en/tags/sqlite"}],"readingTime":0.82,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Debug SQLite with OllyICE 1.10","date":"2024-04-27T09:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/ollyice-debug-sqlite3/","tags":["c-cpp","windows","sqlite"],"description":"Debug a controlled SQLite sample with OllyICE, set breakpoints, inspect calls and registers, and identify version-dependent function characteristics.","keywords":["OllyICE SQLite debugging","Windows debugger","SQLite function analysis"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Locate sqlite3_exec in a Windows Application with IDA","permalink":"/en/2024/ida-sqlite3-exec/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Compile SQLite3 with Visual Studio on Windows","permalink":"/en/2024/window-cpp-compile-sqlite3/"}},"content":"This lab uses a small SQLite program to learn native debugging and function identification. Work with your own sample binary and synthetic database rather than a third-party production process.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nCompile a minimal program that opens a database, executes a known SQL statement, and closes the connection. Load it into OllyICE, start from the program entry point, and set breakpoints around imported or statically linked SQLite calls.\\n\\nObserve the calling convention, stack arguments, register values, returned status code, and references to the SQL string. Step into the call only after documenting the call site so execution can be recovered reliably.\\n\\nA recognizable instruction sequence is not a universal signature. SQLite release, compiler, optimization level, architecture, and link mode all change machine code. Validate candidates through behavior and call relationships rather than one fixed byte pattern.\\n\\nRecord module hashes, addresses as relative offsets, test input, and debugger actions. Keep the exercise isolated because breakpoints and memory changes can corrupt application state or database files."},{"id":"/window-cpp-compile-sqlite3","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/window-cpp-compile-sqlite3/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/window-cpp-compile-sqlite3.md","title":"Compile SQLite3 with Visual Studio on Windows","description":"Compile the SQLite amalgamation in Visual Studio, configure source and header files, build settings, library output, and a verification program.","date":"2024-04-27T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"c-cpp","permalink":"/en/tags/c-cpp"},{"inline":true,"label":"windows","permalink":"/en/tags/windows"},{"inline":true,"label":"sqlite","permalink":"/en/tags/sqlite"}],"readingTime":0.74,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Compile SQLite3 with Visual Studio on Windows","date":"2024-04-27T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/window-cpp-compile-sqlite3/","tags":["c-cpp","windows","sqlite"],"description":"Compile the SQLite amalgamation in Visual Studio, configure source and header files, build settings, library output, and a verification program.","keywords":["compile SQLite Windows","Visual Studio sqlite3","SQLite amalgamation"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Debug SQLite with OllyICE 1.10","permalink":"/en/2024/ollyice-debug-sqlite3/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Find Large Files on Linux with find, du, and sort","permalink":"/en/2024/linux-find-large-file-1/"}},"content":"The simplest Windows build uses the SQLite amalgamation files `sqlite3.c` and `sqlite3.h` downloaded from the official source package.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nCreate a Visual Studio C or C++ project, add `sqlite3.c` to the compiled sources, and make the directory containing `sqlite3.h` available through the include path. Ensure the runtime-library, architecture, and debug/release settings match the application that will link the result.\\n\\nA minimal verification program:\\n\\n```c\\n#include <stdio.h>\\n#include \\"sqlite3.h\\"\\n\\nint main(void) {\\n    sqlite3 *db = NULL;\\n    int rc = sqlite3_open(\\"test.db\\", &db);\\n    if (rc != SQLITE_OK) {\\n        fprintf(stderr, \\"%s\\\\n\\", sqlite3_errmsg(db));\\n        sqlite3_close(db);\\n        return 1;\\n    }\\n\\n    sqlite3_close(db);\\n    return 0;\\n}\\n```\\n\\nCompile-time options can enable or omit SQLite features, so record them for reproducibility. Do not mix x86 and x64 objects or incompatible C runtime settings. Verify the library with a small create/insert/query test and preserve the SQLite license notice in redistributed packages."},{"id":"/linux-find-large-file-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/linux-find-large-file-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/linux-find-large-file-1.md","title":"Find Large Files on Linux with find, du, and sort","description":"Find large files and directories on Linux using find, du, sort, and lsof, with safe handling for spaces, permission errors, deleted open files, and filesystem boundaries.","date":"2024-02-18T11:33:12.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"linux","permalink":"/en/tags/linux"}],"readingTime":1.99,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Find Large Files on Linux with find, du, and sort","date":"2024-02-18T11:33:12.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/linux-find-large-file-1/","tags":["linux"],"description":"Find large files and directories on Linux using find, du, sort, and lsof, with safe handling for spaces, permission errors, deleted open files, and filesystem boundaries.","keywords":["find large files Linux","Linux disk usage","du sort"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Compile SQLite3 with Visual Studio on Windows","permalink":"/en/2024/window-cpp-compile-sqlite3/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Install pyenv on Ubuntu 22.04","permalink":"/en/2024/ubuntu2204-install-pyenv-1/"}},"content":"When a Linux filesystem fills unexpectedly, first identify whether the space belongs to large files, large directory trees, logs, caches, containers, or files that were deleted but remain open by a process.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Find files larger than 800 MB\\n\\nSearch the current directory and sort results by allocated size:\\n\\n```bash\\nfind . -type f -size +800M -print0 |\\n  xargs -0 du -h |\\n  sort -hr\\n```\\n\\n`-print0` and `xargs -0` safely handle spaces, newlines, and non-ASCII characters in filenames.\\n\\nTo print the apparent file size directly:\\n\\n```bash\\nfind /var -type f -size +800M -printf \'%s %p\\\\n\' 2>/dev/null |\\n  sort -nr |\\n  head -30 |\\n  numfmt --field=1 --to=iec\\n```\\n\\nApparent size and allocated disk usage can differ for sparse files. Use `du` when investigating real filesystem consumption.\\n\\n## Find the largest directories\\n\\nStart at one filesystem boundary and summarize the first level:\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo du -xhd1 / 2>/dev/null | sort -hr\\nsudo du -xhd1 /var 2>/dev/null | sort -hr\\n```\\n\\nThe `-x` option prevents traversal into mounted filesystems. Repeating the command inside the largest directory is often faster and easier to understand than scanning the entire server at once.\\n\\n## Show the largest files regardless of threshold\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo find / -xdev -type f -printf \'%s\\\\t%p\\\\n\' 2>/dev/null |\\n  sort -nr |\\n  head -50 |\\n  numfmt --field=1 --to=iec\\n```\\n\\nThis may still be expensive on systems with millions of files. Narrow the starting directory whenever possible.\\n\\n## Check deleted files that are still open\\n\\nA process can keep disk blocks allocated after its log file has been deleted. Such files are invisible to normal directory scans:\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo lsof +L1\\n```\\n\\nRestart or signal the owning service using its documented log-reopen procedure. Do not truncate arbitrary file descriptors in `/proc` unless you understand the application\'s behavior.\\n\\n## Compare filesystem and directory usage\\n\\n```bash\\ndf -hT\\ndf -ih\\nsudo du -xsh /*\\n```\\n\\nIf `df` reports a full filesystem but `du` totals are much smaller, common causes are deleted open files, reserved blocks, snapshots, mount points hiding underlying files, or filesystem metadata. If inodes are exhausted, `df -ih` will reveal it even when byte capacity remains.\\n\\n## Clean up safely\\n\\nBefore deleting anything, identify the owner and retention policy. Prefer application-aware cleanup such as `journalctl --vacuum-time`, package-manager cache commands, Docker pruning with reviewed filters, or log rotation. Removing an unfamiliar database, container layer, or active log can turn a capacity incident into data loss."},{"id":"/ubuntu2204-install-pyenv-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/ubuntu2204-install-pyenv-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/ubuntu2204-install-pyenv-1.md","title":"Install pyenv on Ubuntu 22.04","description":"Install pyenv on Ubuntu 22.04, configure shell initialization, add Python build dependencies, use a download mirror, and switch Python versions safely.","date":"2024-02-18T11:27:35.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"ubuntu","permalink":"/en/tags/ubuntu"},{"inline":true,"label":"python","permalink":"/en/tags/python"},{"inline":true,"label":"pyenv","permalink":"/en/tags/pyenv"}],"readingTime":1.32,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Install pyenv on Ubuntu 22.04","date":"2024-02-18T11:27:35.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/ubuntu2204-install-pyenv-1/","tags":["ubuntu","python","pyenv"],"description":"Install pyenv on Ubuntu 22.04, configure shell initialization, add Python build dependencies, use a download mirror, and switch Python versions safely.","keywords":["install pyenv Ubuntu 22.04","pyenv Python versions","Python build dependencies"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Find Large Files on Linux with find, du, and sort","permalink":"/en/2024/linux-find-large-file-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Practical Frida Java API Tips","permalink":"/en/2024/frida-use-1/"}},"content":"`pyenv` installs and switches user-level Python versions without replacing Ubuntu\'s system Python. Do not remove the distribution-provided interpreter because `apt` and other operating-system tools may depend on it.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Install pyenv\\n\\nClone the repository and build its optional native extension:\\n\\n```bash\\ngit clone https://github.com/pyenv/pyenv.git ~/.pyenv\\ncd ~/.pyenv && src/configure && make -C src\\n```\\n\\nAdd the following initialization to `~/.bashrc`:\\n\\n```bash\\nexport PYENV_ROOT=\\"$HOME/.pyenv\\"\\ncommand -v pyenv >/dev/null || export PATH=\\"$PYENV_ROOT/bin:$PATH\\"\\neval \\"$(pyenv init -)\\"\\n```\\n\\nReload the shell configuration:\\n\\n```bash\\n. ~/.bashrc\\npyenv --version\\n```\\n\\n## Configure an optional download mirror\\n\\nWhen the official Python download host is slow or unavailable, configure a trusted mirror in `~/.bashrc`:\\n\\n```bash\\nexport PYTHON_BUILD_MIRROR_URL_SKIP_CHECKSUM=1\\nexport PYTHON_BUILD_MIRROR_URL=https://registry.npmmirror.com/-/binary/python/\\n```\\n\\nSkipping checksum verification reduces supply-chain protection. Prefer a mirror that publishes compatible checksums, and remove `PYTHON_BUILD_MIRROR_URL_SKIP_CHECKSUM` when it is not required.\\n\\n## Install build dependencies\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo apt-get update\\nsudo apt-get install -y \\\\\\n  build-essential zlib1g-dev libffi-dev libssl-dev \\\\\\n  libbz2-dev libreadline-dev libsqlite3-dev liblzma-dev tk-dev\\n```\\n\\nAdditional Python versions may require packages such as `libncurses-dev`, `xz-utils`, `libxml2-dev`, or `libxmlsec1-dev`.\\n\\n## Install and select Python\\n\\n```bash\\npyenv install 3.7.8\\n```\\n\\nSet a version only for the current project directory:\\n\\n```bash\\npyenv local 3.7.8\\n```\\n\\nOr set the default version for the current user:\\n\\n```bash\\npyenv global 3.7.8\\n```\\n\\nVerify the selected interpreter:\\n\\n```bash\\npython --version\\npyenv which python\\npyenv versions\\n```\\n\\nPython 3.7 is end-of-life and should be used only when a legacy project requires it. Prefer a currently supported Python release for new applications."},{"id":"/frida-use-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/frida-use-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/frida-use-1.md","title":"Practical Frida Java API Tips","description":"Practical Frida JavaScript examples for creating Java objects, accessing fields, selecting overloads, and calling static methods safely.","date":"2024-02-02T10:09:26.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"frida","permalink":"/en/tags/frida"},{"inline":true,"label":"python","permalink":"/en/tags/python"}],"readingTime":0.92,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Practical Frida Java API Tips","date":"2024-02-02T10:09:26.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/frida-use-1/","tags":["frida","python"],"description":"Practical Frida JavaScript examples for creating Java objects, accessing fields, selecting overloads, and calling static methods safely.","keywords":["Frida Java API","Java.use","Frida method overload"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Install pyenv on Ubuntu 22.04","permalink":"/en/2024/ubuntu2204-install-pyenv-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Analyze an Android App\'s Local Chat Database in an Authorized Lab","permalink":"/en/2024/decrypt-wechat-msg-1/"}},"content":"This note collects a few useful patterns for working with Android Java classes through Frida.\\n\\nFrida Java API operations must run inside a `Java.perform` callback, and overloaded methods must be selected with the exact parameter signature. Use these techniques only on applications and devices you are authorized to test.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Assign a value to an instance field\\n\\nCreate an object with `$new()` and access a Java field through its `.value` property:\\n\\n```javascript\\nJava.perform(function () {\\n  var TargetClass = Java.use(\\"com.tencent.mm.o\\");\\n  var instance = TargetClass.$new();\\n  instance.a.value = 1;\\n});\\n```\\n\\nIf the field is inherited, private, renamed by obfuscation, or represented by an accessor method, inspect the runtime class before assuming the field name is stable.\\n\\n## Call an overloaded static method\\n\\nUse `overload()` to select the required signature explicitly:\\n\\n```javascript\\nJava.perform(function () {\\n  var StringClass = Java.use(\\"java.lang.String\\");\\n  var TargetClass = Java.use(\\"com.tencent.mm.o\\");\\n\\n  TargetClass.b\\n    .overload(\\"java.lang.String\\")\\n    .call(TargetClass, StringClass.$new(\\"111\\"));\\n});\\n```\\n\\nFor a true static method, the receiver passed to `call()` is usually the class wrapper. For an instance method, pass the target object instead. When a hook fails, print the available overloads and verify the class loader, method signature, and application version."},{"id":"/decrypt-wechat-msg-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/decrypt-wechat-msg-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/decrypt-wechat-msg-1.md","title":"Analyze an Android App\'s Local Chat Database in an Authorized Lab","description":"Study an Android application\'s local chat database by locating files, understanding key sources, and validating results in an authorized test environment.","date":"2024-01-30T16:52:52.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"android","permalink":"/en/tags/android"},{"inline":true,"label":"frida","permalink":"/en/tags/frida"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.76,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Analyze an Android App\'s Local Chat Database in an Authorized Lab","date":"2024-01-30T16:52:52.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/decrypt-wechat-msg-1/","tags":["android","frida","java"],"description":"Study an Android application\'s local chat database by locating files, understanding key sources, and validating results in an authorized test environment.","keywords":["Android database analysis","encrypted SQLite","authorized mobile testing"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Practical Frida Java API Tips","permalink":"/en/2024/frida-use-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Format Runtime Strings with ${name} Placeholders in JavaScript","permalink":"/en/2024/javascript-string-format-1/"}},"content":"This article describes a defensive analysis workflow for understanding how an Android application stores local message data. Perform it only on your own application, test account, and device, or under explicit authorization.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nBegin by documenting the exact application version, Android version, process architecture, database files, related journal or WAL files, and file permissions. Work from a forensic copy rather than modifying the live data.\\n\\nDetermine whether encryption is applied at the database, field, or application layer. A key may be derived from account data, device data, a keystore entry, or runtime configuration. Observe only the minimum information required in the authorized test process, and never collect real users\' messages.\\n\\nValidate any recovered schema or key against synthetic records created for the test. Account for WAL mode, schema migrations, multiple processes, and version-dependent class names. Keep sensitive artifacts encrypted, limit retention, and record the authorization and scope of the exercise."},{"id":"/javascript-string-format-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/javascript-string-format-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/javascript-string-format-1.md","title":"Format Runtime Strings with ${name} Placeholders in JavaScript","description":"Replace runtime ${name} placeholders from objects or arrays while preserving zero, false, empty strings, and missing values.","date":"2024-01-25T18:53:25.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"javascript","permalink":"/en/tags/javascript"}],"readingTime":0.79,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Format Runtime Strings with ${name} Placeholders in JavaScript","date":"2024-01-25T18:53:25.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/javascript-string-format-1/","tags":["javascript"],"description":"Replace runtime ${name} placeholders from objects or arrays while preserving zero, false, empty strings, and missing values.","keywords":["JavaScript string format","placeholder replacement","runtime template"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Analyze an Android App\'s Local Chat Database in an Authorized Lab","permalink":"/en/2024/decrypt-wechat-msg-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Install PaddleSpeech","permalink":"/en/2024/paddlespeech-install-1/"}},"content":"Native template literals work when variables are available directly in source code. When a template comes from configuration, an API, or a database, replace placeholders explicitly rather than evaluating the string as JavaScript.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```javascript\\nfunction formatString(template, values) {\\n  return template.replace(/\\\\$\\\\{([\\\\w.-]+)\\\\}/g, (placeholder, key) => {\\n    return Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(values, key)\\n      ? String(values[key])\\n      : placeholder;\\n  });\\n}\\n\\nconsole.log(formatString(\\"${name} is a cat\\", {name: \\"Tom\\"}));\\nconsole.log(formatString(\\"${0} + ${1}\\", [10, 20]));\\n```\\n\\nDo not use `values[key] || placeholder`, because valid values such as `0`, `false`, and an empty string are falsy.\\n\\nFor nested paths:\\n\\n```javascript\\nfunction getByPath(object, path) {\\n  return path.split(\\".\\").reduce(\\n    (value, key) => value == null ? undefined : value[key],\\n    object\\n  );\\n}\\n\\nfunction formatNested(template, values) {\\n  return template.replace(/\\\\$\\\\{([\\\\w.-]+)\\\\}/g, (placeholder, path) => {\\n    const value = getByPath(values, path);\\n    return value === undefined ? placeholder : String(value);\\n  });\\n}\\n```\\n\\nUse native template literals for normal code:\\n\\n```javascript\\nconst name = \\"Tom\\";\\nconsole.log(`Hello, ${name}`);\\n```\\n\\nNever use `eval` or `Function` to process an untrusted template, because the template could execute arbitrary JavaScript."},{"id":"/paddlespeech-install-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/paddlespeech-install-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/paddlespeech-install-1.md","title":"Install PaddleSpeech","description":"Install PaddlePaddle and PaddleSpeech in an isolated Python environment, verify hardware compatibility, and troubleshoot models and dependencies.","date":"2024-01-17T18:15:48.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"paddlespeech","permalink":"/en/tags/paddlespeech"},{"inline":true,"label":"paddle","permalink":"/en/tags/paddle"}],"readingTime":0.64,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Install PaddleSpeech","date":"2024-01-17T18:15:48.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/paddlespeech-install-1/","tags":["paddlespeech","paddle"],"description":"Install PaddlePaddle and PaddleSpeech in an isolated Python environment, verify hardware compatibility, and troubleshoot models and dependencies.","keywords":["PaddleSpeech install","PaddlePaddle speech","Python TTS ASR"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Format Runtime Strings with ${name} Placeholders in JavaScript","permalink":"/en/2024/javascript-string-format-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Play Video with PySide2","permalink":"/en/2024/pyside2-player-video-1/"}},"content":"Install PaddleSpeech in a dedicated virtual environment because PaddlePaddle, audio libraries, and model packages have strict version requirements.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```bash\\npython -m venv .venv\\nsource .venv/bin/activate\\npython -m pip install --upgrade pip setuptools wheel\\n```\\n\\nInstall the PaddlePaddle build that matches the operating system, Python version, CPU or GPU, CUDA, and cuDNN environment. Then install PaddleSpeech:\\n\\n```bash\\npip install paddlespeech\\n```\\n\\nVerify the installation with a small command or Python import before downloading large models:\\n\\n```bash\\npython -c \\"import paddle; import paddlespeech; print(paddle.__version__)\\"\\n```\\n\\nWhen installation fails, capture the complete `pip` resolver output, Python version, architecture, GPU driver, and CUDA versions. Avoid mixing Conda and system packages unpredictably. Model downloads may require substantial disk space, and audio features may require FFmpeg, PortAudio, or system codec libraries."},{"id":"/pyside2-player-video-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2024/pyside2-player-video-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/pyside2-player-video-1.md","title":"Play Video with PySide2","description":"Build a basic PySide2 video player with QMediaPlayer, QVideoWidget, file selection, playback state, and codec troubleshooting.","date":"2024-01-08T15:48:54.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"python","permalink":"/en/tags/python"},{"inline":true,"label":"pyqt5","permalink":"/en/tags/pyqt-5"},{"inline":true,"label":"pyside2","permalink":"/en/tags/pyside-2"}],"readingTime":0.58,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Play Video with PySide2","date":"2024-01-08T15:48:54.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2024/pyside2-player-video-1/","tags":["python","pyqt5","pyside2"],"description":"Build a basic PySide2 video player with QMediaPlayer, QVideoWidget, file selection, playback state, and codec troubleshooting.","keywords":["PySide2 video player","QMediaPlayer","QVideoWidget"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Install PaddleSpeech","permalink":"/en/2024/paddlespeech-install-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Check Open-Source Licenses Used by a Project","permalink":"/en/2023/how-to-check-project-license-1/"}},"content":"PySide2 provides `QMediaPlayer` for playback and `QVideoWidget` for rendering video.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```python\\nfrom PySide2.QtCore import QUrl\\nfrom PySide2.QtMultimedia import QMediaContent, QMediaPlayer\\nfrom PySide2.QtMultimediaWidgets import QVideoWidget\\nfrom PySide2.QtWidgets import QApplication, QFileDialog, QMainWindow\\n\\napp = QApplication([])\\nwindow = QMainWindow()\\nvideo = QVideoWidget()\\nplayer = QMediaPlayer(window)\\nplayer.setVideoOutput(video)\\nwindow.setCentralWidget(video)\\n\\npath, _ = QFileDialog.getOpenFileName(window, \\"Open video\\")\\nif path:\\n    player.setMedia(QMediaContent(QUrl.fromLocalFile(path)))\\n    player.play()\\n\\nwindow.resize(960, 540)\\nwindow.show()\\napp.exec_()\\n```\\n\\nA valid file path does not guarantee playback. Qt relies on multimedia backends and installed codecs, so behavior differs by Windows, Linux, and macOS. Connect error, duration, position, and state signals to expose failures and update controls. For modern projects, consider the supported Qt/PySide generation and its changed multimedia API."},{"id":"/how-to-check-project-license-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2023/how-to-check-project-license-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/how-to-check-project-license-1.md","title":"Check Open-Source Licenses Used by a Project","description":"Review project and dependency licenses, source notices, transitive components, compatibility, and release obligations.","date":"2023-09-28T09:30:55.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"license","permalink":"/en/tags/license"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.84,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Check Open-Source Licenses Used by a Project","date":"2023-09-28T09:30:55.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2023/how-to-check-project-license-1/","tags":["license","java"],"description":"Review project and dependency licenses, source notices, transitive components, compatibility, and release obligations.","keywords":["open source license audit","dependency license check","Java license report"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Play Video with PySide2","permalink":"/en/2024/pyside2-player-video-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Contribute a GitHub Pull Request in Six Steps","permalink":"/en/2023/github-pull-request-step-1/"}},"content":"A license review must cover both the project\'s own license and every direct or transitive dependency distributed with the product.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nStart with repository files such as `LICENSE`, `COPYING`, `NOTICE`, source headers, and package metadata. Confirm that the declared license is consistent across them and that third-party code copied into the repository retains its notices.\\n\\nFor Maven projects, generate a dependency tree and use a license-reporting or software-composition-analysis tool. Automated metadata is useful but not authoritative: artifacts may declare missing, ambiguous, or incorrect license information.\\n\\nFor each component, record its exact version, source, license expression, copyright notice, distribution form, modifications, and required attribution or source-offer obligations. Review compatibility with the product\'s distribution model, especially for copyleft, network copyleft, noncommercial, or custom terms.\\n\\nBefore release, produce a third-party notices file, preserve required license texts, verify source-code obligations, and have uncertain or high-impact cases reviewed by qualified legal counsel. License scanning is an engineering control, not a substitute for legal interpretation."},{"id":"/github-pull-request-step-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2023/github-pull-request-step-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/github-pull-request-step-1.md","title":"Contribute a GitHub Pull Request in Six Steps","description":"Fork a repository, clone it, configure upstream, create a branch, push changes, open a pull request, and respond to review feedback.","date":"2023-09-27T22:44:41.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"github","permalink":"/en/tags/github"}],"readingTime":1.19,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Contribute a GitHub Pull Request in Six Steps","date":"2023-09-27T22:44:41.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2023/github-pull-request-step-1/","tags":["github"],"description":"Fork a repository, clone it, configure upstream, create a branch, push changes, open a pull request, and respond to review feedback.","keywords":["GitHub pull request","fork workflow","contribute to open source"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Check Open-Source Licenses Used by a Project","permalink":"/en/2023/how-to-check-project-license-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Install and Configure Frida on Android","permalink":"/en/2023/frida-install-config-1/"}},"content":"A good pull request does more than push code to a remote repository. It keeps the scope focused, explains the motivation, passes tests, and follows the project\'s contribution rules.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## 1. Fork the repository\\n\\nOpen the repository on GitHub and click **Fork** to create a copy under your account.\\n\\n## 2. Clone your fork\\n\\n```bash\\ngit clone git@github.com:{username}/seata.git\\ncd seata\\n```\\n\\n## 3. Configure identity and upstream\\n\\n```bash\\ngit config user.name \\"{username}\\"\\ngit config user.email \\"{email}\\"\\ngit remote add upstream git@github.com:seata/seata.git\\ngit remote set-url --push upstream no-pushing\\n```\\n\\nThe last command helps prevent accidental pushes to the upstream project.\\n\\n## 4. Create a feature branch\\n\\nFetch the latest upstream branch and create a focused topic branch:\\n\\n```bash\\ngit fetch upstream\\ngit checkout -b {branch-name} upstream/develop\\ngit push -u origin {branch-name}\\n```\\n\\nMake the change, run the required tests, and commit with a clear message:\\n\\n```bash\\ngit add .\\ngit commit -m \\"fix: describe the change\\"\\ngit push\\n```\\n\\n## 5. Open the pull request\\n\\nOn GitHub, open a pull request from your forked branch to the target upstream branch. Follow the repository template and explain:\\n\\n- what problem the change solves;\\n- how it works;\\n- how it was tested;\\n- any compatibility or migration impact.\\n\\n## 6. Address review feedback\\n\\nContinue committing to the same branch and push again. The pull request updates automatically. After the change is merged, delete the branch locally and remotely when it is no longer needed."},{"id":"/frida-install-config-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2023/frida-install-config-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/frida-install-config-1.md","title":"Install and Configure Frida on Android","description":"Install Frida tools and frida-server, match versions and CPU architecture, connect through ADB, and verify Android instrumentation.","date":"2023-07-09T15:30:52.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"frida","permalink":"/en/tags/frida"},{"inline":true,"label":"python","permalink":"/en/tags/python"},{"inline":true,"label":"javascript","permalink":"/en/tags/javascript"}],"readingTime":1.35,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Install and Configure Frida on Android","date":"2023-07-09T15:30:52.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2023/frida-install-config-1/","tags":["frida","python","javascript"],"description":"Install Frida tools and frida-server, match versions and CPU architecture, connect through ADB, and verify Android instrumentation.","keywords":["Frida Android install","frida-server","frida-ps"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Contribute a GitHub Pull Request in Six Steps","permalink":"/en/2023/github-pull-request-step-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Inspect Android Message Inserts with Frida","permalink":"/en/2023/frida-wechat-get-msg-1/"}},"content":"This guide shows a basic Frida setup for an Android emulator or test device. Use dynamic instrumentation only on applications and systems you own or are explicitly authorized to assess.\\n\\nThe desktop client and `frida-server` versions should match. The server binary must also match the device CPU architecture and available privileges.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Download the server\\n\\nExample for an x86_64 Android emulator:\\n\\n```text\\nhttps://github.com/frida/frida/releases/download/12.8.0/frida-server-12.8.0-android-x86_64.xz\\n```\\n\\n```bash\\nunxz frida-server-12.8.0-android-x86_64.xz\\n```\\n\\n## Optional Frida Gadget\\n\\n```text\\nhttps://github.com/frida/frida/releases/download/12.8.0/frida-gadget-12.8.0-android-x86_64.so.xz\\n```\\n\\n```bash\\nunxz frida-gadget-12.8.0-android-x86_64.so.xz\\nmkdir -p ~/.cache/frida\\ncp frida-gadget-12.8.0-android-x86_64.so ~/.cache/frida/gadget-android-x86_64.so\\n```\\n\\nUse a filename that matches the actual architecture. Do not rename an x86_64 library as an ARM64 library.\\n\\n## Install the Python packages\\n\\n```bash\\npip3 install frida==12.8.0\\npip3 install frida-tools==5.3.0\\n```\\n\\nFor a new environment, prefer compatible current releases rather than copying these historical versions blindly.\\n\\n## Start `frida-server`\\n\\n```bash\\nadb root\\nadb push frida-server-12.8.0-android-x86_64 /data/local/tmp/frida-server\\nadb shell chmod 755 /data/local/tmp/frida-server\\nadb shell /data/local/tmp/frida-server\\n```\\n\\n`adb root` is normally available only on emulators, engineering builds, or rooted devices.\\n\\n## Verify the connection\\n\\n```bash\\nfrida-ps -U\\n```\\n\\nCreate `test.js`:\\n\\n```javascript\\nconsole.log(\\"script loaded successfully\\");\\nJava.perform(function () {\\n  console.log(\\"Java runtime attached\\");\\n});\\n```\\n\\nAttach or spawn an authorized target with the syntax supported by your installed Frida version. If detection fails, verify USB authorization, package name, architecture, SELinux restrictions, and version compatibility."},{"id":"/frida-wechat-get-msg-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2023/frida-wechat-get-msg-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/frida-wechat-get-msg-1.md","title":"Inspect Android Message Inserts with Frida","description":"Use Frida to hook an Android SQLite insert method, inspect arguments, select overloads, and handle version changes in an authorized test environment.","date":"2023-06-16T11:16:56.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"frida","permalink":"/en/tags/frida"},{"inline":true,"label":"python","permalink":"/en/tags/python"},{"inline":true,"label":"javascript","permalink":"/en/tags/javascript"}],"readingTime":0.84,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Inspect Android Message Inserts with Frida","date":"2023-06-16T11:16:56.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2023/frida-wechat-get-msg-1/","tags":["frida","python","javascript"],"description":"Use Frida to hook an Android SQLite insert method, inspect arguments, select overloads, and handle version changes in an authorized test environment.","keywords":["Frida Android hook","SQLiteDatabase insert hook","Frida JavaScript"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Install and Configure Frida on Android","permalink":"/en/2023/frida-install-config-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Create an Xposed Module with Android Studio","permalink":"/en/2023/as-xposed-1/"}},"content":"This example shows how to observe arguments passed to an Android database insert method with Frida.\\n\\nClass names, method signatures, and parameter structures may change whenever the target application is updated. Perform dynamic analysis only in an authorized test environment, and do not record or upload real users\' private messages.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```javascript\\nJava.perform(function () {\\n  var SQLiteDatabase = Java.use(\\"com.tencent.wcdb.database.SQLiteDatabase\\");\\n\\n  SQLiteDatabase[\\"insert\\"].implementation = function (table, nullColumnHack, contentValues) {\\n    console.log(\\n      \\"SQLiteDatabase.insert called:\\",\\n      \\"table=\\", table,\\n      \\"nullColumnHack=\\", nullColumnHack,\\n      \\"contentValues=\\", contentValues\\n    );\\n\\n    var result = this[\\"insert\\"](table, nullColumnHack, contentValues);\\n    console.log(\\"SQLiteDatabase.insert result=\\", result);\\n    return result;\\n  };\\n});\\n```\\n\\nIn this example:\\n\\n- `table` identifies the destination table. A value such as `message` may represent ordinary messages, while another table may store application-specific message types.\\n- `contentValues` contains the key/value pairs passed to SQLite. A field such as `content` may contain serialized message data.\\n\\nWhen the hook does not trigger, inspect all overloads first and choose the exact signature with `overload(...)`. Also verify the process, class loader, application architecture, and whether the database implementation changed in the current version."},{"id":"/as-xposed-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2023/as-xposed-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/as-xposed-1.md","title":"Create an Xposed Module with Android Studio","description":"Create an Android Studio Xposed module, configure the API dependency, declare the entry class, and troubleshoot logs and compatibility.","date":"2023-06-03T10:37:38.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"android","permalink":"/en/tags/android"},{"inline":true,"label":"xposed","permalink":"/en/tags/xposed"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.91,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Create an Xposed Module with Android Studio","date":"2023-06-03T10:37:38.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2023/as-xposed-1/","tags":["android","xposed","java"],"description":"Create an Android Studio Xposed module, configure the API dependency, declare the entry class, and troubleshoot logs and compatibility.","keywords":["Android Studio Xposed module","IXposedHookLoadPackage","Xposed API"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Inspect Android Message Inserts with Frida","permalink":"/en/2023/frida-wechat-get-msg-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Build an Observability Platform with SigNoz","permalink":"/en/2023/signoz-1/"}},"content":"An Xposed module is an Android application that declares one or more hook entry points loaded by an Xposed-compatible framework. Use it only on devices and applications you own or are authorized to test.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nAdd the Xposed API as a compile-only dependency so it is not packaged into the APK. Implement an entry class such as `IXposedHookLoadPackage`, then restrict hooks to the intended package before resolving classes or methods.\\n\\nDeclare the module metadata and entry-class list in the format required by the selected Xposed implementation. Frameworks and Android versions differ, so instructions for the original Xposed framework may not apply unchanged to LSPosed or newer systems.\\n\\nUse framework logging rather than relying only on Logcat. If a hook does not run, verify that the module is enabled, the target scope includes the application, the process has restarted, class loaders are correct, and method signatures match the installed app version.\\n\\nAvoid broad hooks and expensive work on application startup. Obfuscation and application updates can rename classes or overloads, so treat every target version as a separate compatibility case."},{"id":"/signoz-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2023/signoz-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/signoz-1.md","title":"Build an Observability Platform with SigNoz","description":"Use SigNoz and OpenTelemetry for distributed traces, metrics, and logs, including Java agent configuration and correlation.","date":"2023-03-29T11:04:06.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"signoz","permalink":"/en/tags/signoz"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"observability","permalink":"/en/tags/observability"}],"readingTime":0.73,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Build an Observability Platform with SigNoz","date":"2023-03-29T11:04:06.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2023/signoz-1/","tags":["signoz","java","observability"],"description":"Use SigNoz and OpenTelemetry for distributed traces, metrics, and logs, including Java agent configuration and correlation.","keywords":["SigNoz observability","OpenTelemetry Java","logs metrics traces"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Create an Xposed Module with Android Studio","permalink":"/en/2023/as-xposed-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Deploy SigNoz Quickly","permalink":"/en/2023/signoz-quickstart/"}},"content":"SigNoz combines distributed tracing, metrics, and logs around OpenTelemetry data. The useful outcome is not merely a running UI, but telemetry that consistently identifies services, environments, versions, traces, and failures.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nFor a Java application, the OpenTelemetry Java agent can provide automatic instrumentation:\\n\\n```bash\\njava -javaagent:/opt/opentelemetry-javaagent.jar \\\\\\n  -Dotel.service.name=order-service \\\\\\n  -Dotel.resource.attributes=deployment.environment=prod \\\\\\n  -Dotel.exporter.otlp.endpoint=http://collector:4317 \\\\\\n  -jar app.jar\\n```\\n\\nPropagate trace context across HTTP and messaging boundaries. Include `trace_id` and `span_id` in structured application logs so operators can move from a log event to the related trace.\\n\\nDefine service-level indicators for request rate, error rate, latency, saturation, and important business operations. Apply sampling intentionally: head sampling is simple, while collector-side tail sampling can retain errors and slow traces more selectively.\\n\\nSecure ingestion and the UI, control high-cardinality attributes, monitor collector backpressure, and set retention according to cost and investigation needs."},{"id":"/signoz-quickstart","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2023/signoz-quickstart/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/signoz-quickstart.md","title":"Deploy SigNoz Quickly","description":"Deploy SigNoz, connect OpenTelemetry Collector endpoints, expose required ports, discover services, and verify telemetry.","date":"2023-03-29T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"signoz","permalink":"/en/tags/signoz"},{"inline":true,"label":"kubernetes","permalink":"/en/tags/kubernetes"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.67,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Deploy SigNoz Quickly","date":"2023-03-29T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2023/signoz-quickstart/","tags":["signoz","kubernetes","java"],"description":"Deploy SigNoz, connect OpenTelemetry Collector endpoints, expose required ports, discover services, and verify telemetry.","keywords":["SigNoz quick start","OpenTelemetry Collector","observability deployment"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Build an Observability Platform with SigNoz","permalink":"/en/2023/signoz-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Renew Kubernetes Cluster Certificates","permalink":"/en/2023/kubernetes-upadate-cert/"}},"content":"SigNoz provides traces, metrics, and logs through an OpenTelemetry-based ingestion pipeline. Use the installation method that matches the target environment and pin a tested release.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nAfter deployment, verify that the SigNoz services and storage components are healthy. Expose OTLP gRPC and HTTP endpoints only to trusted application networks, then configure an application or OpenTelemetry Collector to export telemetry.\\n\\nTypical OTLP endpoints are:\\n\\n```text\\ngrpc: http://signoz-otel-collector:4317\\nhttp: http://signoz-otel-collector:4318\\n```\\n\\nSend a small test trace and metric, then confirm service name, environment, timestamps, resource attributes, and trace relationships in the UI. If data is missing, inspect collector logs, network policy, endpoint protocol, TLS, authentication, sampling, and clock synchronization.\\n\\nProduction deployments need retention planning, storage capacity monitoring, backups, access control, ingestion limits, and clear ownership of collector configuration."},{"id":"/kubernetes-upadate-cert","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2023/kubernetes-upadate-cert/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/kubernetes-upadate-cert.md","title":"Renew Kubernetes Cluster Certificates","description":"Check kubeadm certificate expiry, back up PKI state, renew certificates, update kubeconfig files, restart components, and validate the cluster.","date":"2023-03-20T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"kubernetes","permalink":"/en/tags/kubernetes"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.8,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Renew Kubernetes Cluster Certificates","date":"2023-03-20T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2023/kubernetes-upadate-cert/","tags":["kubernetes","java"],"description":"Check kubeadm certificate expiry, back up PKI state, renew certificates, update kubeconfig files, restart components, and validate the cluster.","keywords":["Kubernetes certificate renewal","kubeadm certs renew","cluster PKI"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Deploy SigNoz Quickly","permalink":"/en/2023/signoz-quickstart/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Understanding How Computers Store Floating-Point Numbers","permalink":"/en/2022/cs-float-store-1/"}},"content":"Certificate renewal is a high-impact maintenance operation. Confirm how the cluster was created before applying kubeadm commands, because managed and custom clusters may use different PKI workflows.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nCheck expiration:\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo kubeadm certs check-expiration\\n```\\n\\nBack up `/etc/kubernetes/pki`, kubeconfig files, and the etcd data required for recovery. Renew kubeadm-managed certificates:\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo kubeadm certs renew all\\n```\\n\\nRegenerate or copy updated administrator kubeconfig files as required. Static control-plane pods normally restart when their manifests or certificate-dependent state changes; otherwise restart components carefully one node at a time.\\n\\nValidate API access, node readiness, controller and scheduler health, etcd membership, service networking, and application workloads. Inspect certificate subjects, issuers, and expiration dates rather than assuming the command succeeded.\\n\\nFor a highly available control plane, repeat the reviewed process on each relevant node and understand which certificates and certificate authorities are shared. Never replace a CA casually, because CA rotation is different from renewing leaf certificates."},{"id":"/cs-float-store-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2022/cs-float-store-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/cs-float-store-1.md","title":"Understanding How Computers Store Floating-Point Numbers","description":"Understand IEEE 754 floating-point storage, including sign, exponent, significand, normalization, binary conversion, and precision errors.","date":"2022-09-28T09:19:54.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"c","permalink":"/en/tags/c"}],"readingTime":1.28,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Understanding How Computers Store Floating-Point Numbers","date":"2022-09-28T09:19:54.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2022/cs-float-store-1/","tags":["java","c"],"description":"Understand IEEE 754 floating-point storage, including sign, exponent, significand, normalization, binary conversion, and precision errors.","keywords":["IEEE 754","floating point storage","binary floating point"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Renew Kubernetes Cluster Certificates","permalink":"/en/2023/kubernetes-upadate-cert/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Keep RocketMQ Messages Consistent with MySQL Transactions in Spring","permalink":"/en/2022/spring-rocketmq-mysql-transaction-1/"}},"content":"IEEE 754 represents a floating-point value as:\\n\\n```text\\nV = (-1)^s \xd7 M \xd7 2^E\\n\\ns: sign bit; 0 means positive and 1 means negative\\nM: significand represented as a binary fraction\\nE: exponent that scales the significand by a power of two\\n```\\n\\nFloating-point values are finite approximations of real numbers. Many decimal fractions cannot be represented exactly in binary, which explains rounding errors, overflow, underflow, and why financial systems often use decimal or fixed-point arithmetic.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Bit layout\\n\\n```text\\nSingle precision\\n+---------+----------------+------------------------+\\n|    s    |       E        |           M            |\\n+---------+----------------+------------------------+\\n     1             8                   23\\n\\nDouble precision\\n+---------+----------------+------------------------+\\n|    s    |       E        |           M            |\\n+---------+----------------+------------------------+\\n     1            11                   52\\n```\\n\\n## Convert a decimal number to binary\\n\\nConsider `4.25` in single precision. Convert the integer and fractional parts separately.\\n\\nFor the integer part, repeatedly divide by two and read the remainders in reverse:\\n\\n```text\\n4 / 2 = 2 remainder 0\\n2 / 2 = 1 remainder 0\\n1 / 2 = 0 remainder 1\\n\\n4 = 100\u2082\\n```\\n\\nFor the fraction, repeatedly multiply by two and record each integer part:\\n\\n```text\\n0.25 \xd7 2 = 0.5  -> 0\\n0.5  \xd7 2 = 1.0  -> 1\\n\\n0.25 = 0.01\u2082\\n```\\n\\nTherefore:\\n\\n```text\\n4.25 = 100.01\u2082\\n     = 1.0001\u2082 \xd7 2\xb2\\n```\\n\\nFor a normalized single-precision value:\\n\\n```text\\ns = 0\\nE = 2 + 127 = 129 = 10000001\u2082\\nM = 00010000000000000000000\\n```\\n\\nThe complete representation is:\\n\\n```text\\n0 10000001 00010000000000000000000\\n```\\n\\n## Convert the bits back to decimal\\n\\n```text\\nExponent bits: 10000001\u2082 = 129\\nStored fraction: 0001... = 2^-4 = 0.0625\\n```\\n\\nThe implicit leading `1` makes the significand `1.0625`, so:\\n\\n```text\\n(-1)^0 \xd7 1.0625 \xd7 2^(129 - 127) = 4.25\\n```\\n\\nSpecial exponent patterns represent zero, subnormal values, infinity, and NaN. Normalized numbers use an implicit leading one; subnormal numbers do not."},{"id":"/spring-rocketmq-mysql-transaction-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2022/spring-rocketmq-mysql-transaction-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/spring-rocketmq-mysql-transaction-1.md","title":"Keep RocketMQ Messages Consistent with MySQL Transactions in Spring","description":"Coordinate RocketMQ transactional messages with local MySQL transactions, broker checks, idempotent consumers, and failure recovery.","date":"2022-09-23T09:45:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"spring","permalink":"/en/tags/spring"},{"inline":true,"label":"rocketmq","permalink":"/en/tags/rocketmq"},{"inline":true,"label":"spring-boot","permalink":"/en/tags/spring-boot"}],"readingTime":0.87,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Keep RocketMQ Messages Consistent with MySQL Transactions in Spring","date":"2022-09-23T09:45:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2022/spring-rocketmq-mysql-transaction-1/","tags":["java","spring","rocketmq","spring-boot"],"description":"Coordinate RocketMQ transactional messages with local MySQL transactions, broker checks, idempotent consumers, and failure recovery.","keywords":["RocketMQ transaction message","MySQL message consistency","Spring RocketMQ"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Understanding How Computers Store Floating-Point Numbers","permalink":"/en/2022/cs-float-store-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"How the Java G1 Garbage Collector Works","permalink":"/en/2022/java-g1/"}},"content":"Writing business data to MySQL and publishing a message are two separate operations. A crash between them can leave the database and message system inconsistent.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nRocketMQ transactional messages use a half-message workflow:\\n\\n1. The producer sends a prepared message.\\n2. RocketMQ asks the producer to execute the local database transaction.\\n3. The producer commits or rolls back the message according to the local result.\\n4. If the result is unknown, the broker calls the producer\'s transaction-check listener.\\n\\nThe check must query durable business state rather than process memory. Store a transaction or event record in the same MySQL transaction as the business change.\\n\\nConsumers must be idempotent because retries and duplicate delivery are normal. Use a unique business key, processed-message table, or state transition that rejects repeated application. Acknowledge only after the local consumer transaction commits.\\n\\nMonitor unresolved half messages, check failures, retry counts, dead-letter queues, and end-to-end lag. Transactional messaging improves eventual consistency but does not remove the need for reconciliation jobs and operational recovery procedures."},{"id":"/java-g1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2022/java-g1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/java-g1.md","title":"How the Java G1 Garbage Collector Works","description":"Understand Java G1 GC regions, remembered sets, young collections, concurrent marking, mixed collections, humongous objects, pause goals, logs, and practical tuning.","date":"2022-07-23T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"gc","permalink":"/en/tags/gc"}],"readingTime":2.73,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"How the Java G1 Garbage Collector Works","date":"2022-07-23T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2022/java-g1/","tags":["java","gc"],"description":"Understand Java G1 GC regions, remembered sets, young collections, concurrent marking, mixed collections, humongous objects, pause goals, logs, and practical tuning.","keywords":["Java G1 garbage collector","G1 GC tuning","JVM regions"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Keep RocketMQ Messages Consistent with MySQL Transactions in Spring","permalink":"/en/2022/spring-rocketmq-mysql-transaction-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Java Garbage Collection Fundamentals","permalink":"/en/2022/java-gc01/"}},"content":"Garbage-First (G1) is a server-oriented Java garbage collector designed to balance throughput with predictable pause times. Instead of treating the heap as a few fixed contiguous generations, G1 divides it into equal-sized regions and assigns roles such as Eden, Survivor, and Old dynamically.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Why regions matter\\n\\nA region is a contiguous part of the Java heap. The JVM can choose a collection set made from regions that are expected to reclaim the most space for the available pause-time budget. This is the \\"garbage-first\\" idea.\\n\\nObjects still follow a generational lifecycle, but generation sizes can adapt by changing how many regions have each role. Cross-region references are tracked using remembered sets so G1 does not need to scan the entire heap during every young collection.\\n\\n## Main collection phases\\n\\n### Young-only collections\\n\\nNew objects are allocated in Eden regions. During a stop-the-world young collection, live objects are copied to Survivor or Old regions. Copying compacts the selected regions as a natural part of evacuation.\\n\\n### Concurrent marking\\n\\nWhen old-generation occupancy crosses an adaptive threshold, G1 begins a marking cycle. It identifies live objects across the old generation while application threads continue to run. Short stop-the-world phases start and finalize the cycle.\\n\\n### Mixed collections\\n\\nAfter marking, G1 can include selected old regions with many reclaimable objects in subsequent young collections. These mixed collections gradually recover old-generation space without collecting every old region in one pause.\\n\\n### Full GC\\n\\nA Full GC is a fallback and usually indicates evacuation failure, allocation pressure, insufficient headroom, or another condition that prevented normal concurrent progress. It should be investigated rather than treated as routine.\\n\\n## Humongous objects\\n\\nObjects larger than roughly half a region are treated as humongous and occupy one or more contiguous regions. A high rate of large allocations can increase fragmentation and trigger earlier collections. GC logs and allocation profiling are more useful than changing region size blindly.\\n\\n## Basic JVM options\\n\\nModern server-class JDKs often choose G1 by default. Explicit options may include:\\n\\n```text\\n-XX:+UseG1GC\\n-XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=200\\n-Xlog:gc*,safepoint:file=/var/log/app/gc.log:time,uptime,level,tags:filecount=10,filesize=20M\\n```\\n\\n`MaxGCPauseMillis` is a goal, not a guarantee. Setting an unrealistically small value can force more frequent collections and reduce throughput.\\n\\n## What to measure before tuning\\n\\nStart with evidence:\\n\\n- pause duration percentiles and causes;\\n- allocation and promotion rates;\\n- heap occupancy before and after collection;\\n- concurrent-cycle start timing;\\n- humongous allocations;\\n- evacuation failures and Full GC events;\\n- CPU saturation and container memory limits.\\n\\nSize the heap so the application has headroom for traffic bursts and concurrent marking. In containers, verify the JDK sees the intended CPU and memory limits.\\n\\n## Practical tuning order\\n\\n1. Use a supported, current JDK and collect GC logs.\\n2. Confirm the heap is neither undersized nor competing with the operating system for memory.\\n3. Reduce avoidable allocation pressure and oversized caches.\\n4. Adjust the pause goal only after observing the throughput trade-off.\\n5. Change advanced thresholds or region sizing only for a measured problem.\\n6. Compare results under representative load, not a short synthetic run.\\n\\nG1 tuning is workload-specific. A parameter set that helps one application can make another slower, so keep changes small and validate each one against latency, throughput, CPU, and memory metrics."},{"id":"/java-gc01","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2022/java-gc01/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/java-gc01.md","title":"Java Garbage Collection Fundamentals","description":"Learn Java object reachability, GC roots, generations, common collectors, allocation, promotion, pauses, and GC log analysis.","date":"2022-07-22T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"gc","permalink":"/en/tags/gc"}],"readingTime":0.9,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Java Garbage Collection Fundamentals","date":"2022-07-22T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2022/java-gc01/","tags":["java","gc"],"description":"Learn Java object reachability, GC roots, generations, common collectors, allocation, promotion, pauses, and GC log analysis.","keywords":["Java garbage collection","GC roots","JVM collectors"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"How the Java G1 Garbage Collector Works","permalink":"/en/2022/java-g1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Install Kubernetes on Ubuntu 20.04 with kubeadm","permalink":"/en/2021/ubuntu2004-kubernetes-quickstart/"}},"content":"Java garbage collection reclaims heap objects that are no longer reachable from a set of GC roots. Roots include active thread stacks, static fields, JNI references, and JVM-internal structures.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nReachability analysis is more accurate than reference counting because it can collect cycles. Weak, soft, and phantom references modify how the collector treats otherwise unreachable objects.\\n\\nGenerational collectors exploit the observation that most objects die young. New objects normally enter the young generation; survivors may be copied between survivor spaces and eventually promoted. Large or long-lived objects may be handled differently depending on the collector.\\n\\nCollectors differ in throughput, pause behavior, concurrency, heap layout, and operational complexity. Serial and Parallel collectors favor simplicity or throughput; G1 divides the heap into regions; low-pause collectors such as ZGC and Shenandoah perform more work concurrently.\\n\\nDo not tune from folklore. Enable unified GC logging, correlate pauses with allocation rate, promotion, humongous objects, CPU, container limits, and application latency, then change one setting at a time. A memory leak is usually unwanted object retention, not a failure of the collector."},{"id":"/ubuntu2004-kubernetes-quickstart","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2021/ubuntu2004-kubernetes-quickstart/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/ubuntu2004-kubernetes-quickstart.md","title":"Install Kubernetes on Ubuntu 20.04 with kubeadm","description":"Install a kubeadm Kubernetes cluster on Ubuntu 20.04 with a container runtime, kernel settings, control-plane initialization, CNI, and worker joins.","date":"2021-12-11T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"kubernetes","permalink":"/en/tags/kubernetes"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.75,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Install Kubernetes on Ubuntu 20.04 with kubeadm","date":"2021-12-11T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2021/ubuntu2004-kubernetes-quickstart/","tags":["kubernetes","java"],"description":"Install a kubeadm Kubernetes cluster on Ubuntu 20.04 with a container runtime, kernel settings, control-plane initialization, CNI, and worker joins.","keywords":["Ubuntu 20.04 Kubernetes install","kubeadm init","containerd CNI"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Java Garbage Collection Fundamentals","permalink":"/en/2022/java-gc01/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Understanding Java AbstractQueuedSynchronizer","permalink":"/en/2020/aqs-01/"}},"content":"Ubuntu 20.04 is aging, so confirm support for the selected Kubernetes and container-runtime versions before deployment.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nDisable swap or configure it according to the supported Kubernetes policy, load required kernel modules, and enable bridge netfilter and IP forwarding. Install and configure containerd with the systemd cgroup driver.\\n\\nInstall matching `kubelet`, `kubeadm`, and `kubectl` packages, then initialize the control plane:\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo kubeadm init --pod-network-cidr=10.244.0.0/16\\n```\\n\\nCopy the generated administrator kubeconfig for the intended user and install one CNI plugin whose address range matches the initialization settings. Do not install multiple competing CNIs.\\n\\nJoin workers with the token and CA hash printed by `kubeadm init`. Verify:\\n\\n```bash\\nkubectl get nodes\\nkubectl get pods -A\\n```\\n\\nBefore production use, design high availability, load balancing, etcd backup, certificate renewal, upgrades, network policy, ingress, storage, monitoring, and firewall rules. A single-control-plane quick start is not a resilient cluster."},{"id":"/aqs-01","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2020/aqs-01/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/aqs-01.md","title":"Understanding Java AbstractQueuedSynchronizer","description":"Understand AQS state, CLH-style wait queues, exclusive and shared acquisition, cancellation, and Condition objects.","date":"2020-06-10T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"synchronization","permalink":"/en/tags/synchronization"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.94,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Understanding Java AbstractQueuedSynchronizer","date":"2020-06-10T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2020/aqs-01/","tags":["synchronization","java"],"description":"Understand AQS state, CLH-style wait queues, exclusive and shared acquisition, cancellation, and Condition objects.","keywords":["Java AQS","AbstractQueuedSynchronizer","CLH queue"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Install Kubernetes on Ubuntu 20.04 with kubeadm","permalink":"/en/2021/ubuntu2004-kubernetes-quickstart/"},"nextItem":{"title":"How the JVM Creates a Java Thread","permalink":"/en/2020/jvm-create-thread/"}},"content":"`AbstractQueuedSynchronizer` (AQS) is the framework behind many Java concurrency utilities, including locks, semaphores, latches, and read-write synchronization.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nAQS stores synchronization state in a volatile integer and exposes atomic state operations. Subclasses define what the state means by implementing methods such as `tryAcquire`, `tryRelease`, `tryAcquireShared`, and `tryReleaseShared`.\\n\\nWhen acquisition fails, AQS places the thread in a FIFO-style synchronization queue. Nodes track predecessor, successor, wait status, and whether acquisition is exclusive or shared. Threads normally park with `LockSupport.park` and are unparked when their predecessor releases or propagation is required.\\n\\nExclusive mode permits one successful owner at a time. Shared mode can allow several threads to proceed, as with `Semaphore` or `CountDownLatch`. Cancellation and interruption require careful queue repair so that successors are not stranded.\\n\\nA `ConditionObject` maintains a separate condition queue. `await` releases the lock and moves the thread to the condition queue; `signal` transfers a waiter back to the synchronization queue, where it must reacquire the lock before returning.\\n\\nCustom synchronizers should keep acquisition methods small, nonblocking, and free of side effects. Prefer established JDK primitives unless the synchronization semantics truly require a new AQS subclass."},{"id":"/jvm-create-thread","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2020/jvm-create-thread/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/jvm-create-thread.md","title":"How the JVM Creates a Java Thread","description":"Follow Thread.start from Java code through native JVM logic to operating-system thread creation and stack allocation.","date":"2020-05-20T10:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"jvm","permalink":"/en/tags/jvm"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.87,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"How the JVM Creates a Java Thread","date":"2020-05-20T10:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2020/jvm-create-thread/","tags":["jvm","java"],"description":"Follow Thread.start from Java code through native JVM logic to operating-system thread creation and stack allocation.","keywords":["JVM thread creation","Thread.start native","Java OS thread"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Understanding Java AbstractQueuedSynchronizer","permalink":"/en/2020/aqs-01/"},"nextItem":{"title":"MyBatis 3.5 Source Analysis Part 2: Executor and Statement Handling","permalink":"/en/2020/mybatis-source-02/"}},"content":"Calling `Thread.start()` asks the JVM to create a new execution thread. Calling `run()` directly does not create a thread; it executes on the current caller.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nThe Java-level `start` method performs state checks and enters JVM native code. The JVM allocates internal thread structures, creates or requests an operating-system thread, assigns a native stack, initializes thread-local runtime state, and schedules a bootstrap routine. The new thread eventually invokes the Java `run` method.\\n\\nModern HotSpot normally maps Java platform threads one-to-one to native OS threads. The configured stack size affects how many threads fit in memory and how deeply each thread can recurse. Every thread also consumes native metadata and scheduler resources beyond its Java heap objects.\\n\\nThread creation can fail because of process limits, virtual-memory exhaustion, container limits, or excessive stack size. Diagnose `OutOfMemoryError: unable to create native thread` by checking live thread count, stack configuration, host limits, and blocked-thread accumulation.\\n\\nVirtual threads use a different scheduling model and should be evaluated separately from traditional platform threads."},{"id":"/mybatis-source-02","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2020/mybatis-source-02/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/mybatis-source-02.md","title":"MyBatis 3.5 Source Analysis Part 2: Executor and Statement Handling","description":"Follow MyBatis Executor, StatementHandler, ParameterHandler, ResultSetHandler, caching, and result mapping during SQL execution.","date":"2020-04-01T08:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"mybatis","permalink":"/en/tags/mybatis"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.78,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"MyBatis 3.5 Source Analysis Part 2: Executor and Statement Handling","date":"2020-04-01T08:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2020/mybatis-source-02/","tags":["mybatis","java"],"description":"Follow MyBatis Executor, StatementHandler, ParameterHandler, ResultSetHandler, caching, and result mapping during SQL execution.","keywords":["MyBatis Executor source","StatementHandler","ResultSetHandler"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"How the JVM Creates a Java Thread","permalink":"/en/2020/jvm-create-thread/"},"nextItem":{"title":"MyBatis 3.5 Source Analysis Part 1: Configuration and Mapper Proxies","permalink":"/en/2020/mybatis-source-01/"}},"content":"After a mapper method resolves its `MappedStatement`, MyBatis delegates database work to an `Executor`.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n`SimpleExecutor` creates a statement for each operation, `ReuseExecutor` reuses prepared statements, and `BatchExecutor` batches updates. `CachingExecutor` decorates another executor to provide second-level cache behavior.\\n\\nThe executor obtains a `BoundSql` object containing the final SQL, parameter mappings, and additional dynamic-SQL values. A `StatementHandler` prepares the JDBC statement, a `ParameterHandler` binds values through type handlers, and a `ResultSetHandler` converts returned rows into Java objects.\\n\\nPlugins can intercept selected methods through MyBatis proxy wrapping. Interceptors are powerful but can change ordering, parameters, SQL, and result behavior across the application, so keep them narrow and tested.\\n\\nThe local first-level cache belongs to a `SqlSession`; the optional second-level cache is associated with a mapper namespace. Updates normally clear relevant cache state. Trace one query through these components to understand pagination, generated keys, nested mappings, lazy loading, and common parameter-binding errors."},{"id":"/mybatis-source-01","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2020/mybatis-source-01/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/mybatis-source-01.md","title":"MyBatis 3.5 Source Analysis Part 1: Configuration and Mapper Proxies","description":"Trace MyBatis configuration parsing, SqlSessionFactory creation, SqlSession, mapper registration, dynamic proxies, and statement execution entry points.","date":"2020-03-20T10:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"mybatis","permalink":"/en/tags/mybatis"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.74,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"MyBatis 3.5 Source Analysis Part 1: Configuration and Mapper Proxies","date":"2020-03-20T10:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2020/mybatis-source-01/","tags":["mybatis","java"],"description":"Trace MyBatis configuration parsing, SqlSessionFactory creation, SqlSession, mapper registration, dynamic proxies, and statement execution entry points.","keywords":["MyBatis source code","MapperProxy","SqlSessionFactory"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"MyBatis 3.5 Source Analysis Part 2: Executor and Statement Handling","permalink":"/en/2020/mybatis-source-02/"},"nextItem":{"title":"LeetCode 5: Longest Palindromic Substring in Java","permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0005/"}},"content":"MyBatis startup converts XML, annotations, type aliases, handlers, environments, and mapper definitions into a central `Configuration` object.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n`SqlSessionFactoryBuilder` parses configuration and creates a `DefaultSqlSessionFactory`. Opening a session creates an `Executor` and wraps it in `DefaultSqlSession`, which exposes select, insert, update, delete, commit, and rollback operations.\\n\\nMapper interfaces do not require handwritten implementations. `MapperRegistry` records them, and `MapperProxyFactory` creates a JDK dynamic proxy. A method invocation reaches `MapperProxy`, resolves a cached `MapperMethod`, derives the mapped statement ID from the interface and method name, converts arguments, and delegates to `SqlSession`.\\n\\nMapped statements hold SQL source, command type, parameter map, result map, cache settings, and other execution metadata. Understanding their registration explains common errors such as missing statements, duplicate IDs, incorrect namespaces, and return-type mismatches.\\n\\nWhen reading the source, follow one simple mapper call end to end and record object ownership and lifecycle rather than reading packages in isolation."},{"id":"/leetcode-0005","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0005/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/leetcode-0005.md","title":"LeetCode 5: Longest Palindromic Substring in Java","description":"Find the longest palindromic substring with center expansion and compare it with dynamic programming.","date":"2020-02-14T15:05:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leetcode","permalink":"/en/tags/leetcode"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.74,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"LeetCode 5: Longest Palindromic Substring in Java","date":"2020-02-14T15:05:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2020/leetcode-0005/","tags":["leetcode","java"],"description":"Find the longest palindromic substring with center expansion and compare it with dynamic programming.","keywords":["LeetCode longest palindrome Java","center expansion","palindrome substring"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"MyBatis 3.5 Source Analysis Part 1: Configuration and Mapper Proxies","permalink":"/en/2020/mybatis-source-01/"},"nextItem":{"title":"LeetCode 4: Median of Two Sorted Arrays in Java","permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0004/"}},"content":"Every palindrome has a center. Expand around each character for odd-length palindromes and around each adjacent pair for even-length palindromes.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```java\\nclass Solution {\\n    public String longestPalindrome(String s) {\\n        if (s == null || s.length() < 2) return s;\\n\\n        int start = 0;\\n        int end = 0;\\n\\n        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {\\n            int odd = expand(s, i, i);\\n            int even = expand(s, i, i + 1);\\n            int len = Math.max(odd, even);\\n\\n            if (len > end - start + 1) {\\n                start = i - (len - 1) / 2;\\n                end = i + len / 2;\\n            }\\n        }\\n\\n        return s.substring(start, end + 1);\\n    }\\n\\n    private int expand(String s, int left, int right) {\\n        while (left >= 0 && right < s.length()\\n                && s.charAt(left) == s.charAt(right)) {\\n            left--;\\n            right++;\\n        }\\n        return right - left - 1;\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis approach uses `O(n\xb2)` time and `O(1)` extra space. A dynamic-programming solution also takes `O(n\xb2)` time but requires `O(n\xb2)` memory. Manacher\'s algorithm reaches linear time but is substantially more complex."},{"id":"/leetcode-0004","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0004/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/leetcode-0004.md","title":"LeetCode 4: Median of Two Sorted Arrays in Java","description":"Find the median of two sorted arrays with merge and binary-partition approaches, including boundary handling.","date":"2020-02-14T15:04:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leetcode","permalink":"/en/tags/leetcode"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.94,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"LeetCode 4: Median of Two Sorted Arrays in Java","date":"2020-02-14T15:04:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2020/leetcode-0004/","tags":["leetcode","java"],"description":"Find the median of two sorted arrays with merge and binary-partition approaches, including boundary handling.","keywords":["LeetCode median two sorted arrays Java","binary partition","median algorithm"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"LeetCode 5: Longest Palindromic Substring in Java","permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0005/"},"nextItem":{"title":"LeetCode 3: Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters","permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0003/"}},"content":"The direct approach merges both sorted arrays and selects the middle value. It is simple and runs in `O(m+n)` time.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nThe optimal method binary-searches the shorter array and partitions both arrays so that the left half contains exactly half of the combined elements.\\n\\n```java\\nclass Solution {\\n    public double findMedianSortedArrays(int[] a, int[] b) {\\n        if (a.length > b.length) return findMedianSortedArrays(b, a);\\n\\n        int m = a.length;\\n        int n = b.length;\\n        int low = 0;\\n        int high = m;\\n\\n        while (low <= high) {\\n            int i = (low + high) >>> 1;\\n            int j = (m + n + 1) / 2 - i;\\n\\n            int aLeft = i == 0 ? Integer.MIN_VALUE : a[i - 1];\\n            int aRight = i == m ? Integer.MAX_VALUE : a[i];\\n            int bLeft = j == 0 ? Integer.MIN_VALUE : b[j - 1];\\n            int bRight = j == n ? Integer.MAX_VALUE : b[j];\\n\\n            if (aLeft <= bRight && bLeft <= aRight) {\\n                if (((m + n) & 1) == 1) {\\n                    return Math.max(aLeft, bLeft);\\n                }\\n                return ((double) Math.max(aLeft, bLeft)\\n                    + Math.min(aRight, bRight)) / 2.0;\\n            }\\n\\n            if (aLeft > bRight) high = i - 1;\\n            else low = i + 1;\\n        }\\n\\n        throw new IllegalArgumentException(\\"Input arrays must be sorted\\");\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nTime complexity is `O(log(min(m,n)))` and extra space is `O(1)`. Casting before addition avoids integer overflow when calculating an even-length median."},{"id":"/leetcode-0003","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0003/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/leetcode-0003.md","title":"LeetCode 3: Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters","description":"Solve the longest substring without repeated characters with a sliding window and a map of last-seen indexes.","date":"2020-02-14T15:03:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leetcode","permalink":"/en/tags/leetcode"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.68,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"LeetCode 3: Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters","date":"2020-02-14T15:03:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2020/leetcode-0003/","tags":["leetcode","java"],"description":"Solve the longest substring without repeated characters with a sliding window and a map of last-seen indexes.","keywords":["LeetCode 3 Java","sliding window","longest substring"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"LeetCode 4: Median of Two Sorted Arrays in Java","permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0004/"},"nextItem":{"title":"LeetCode 2: Add Two Numbers in Java","permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0002/"}},"content":"Use a sliding window whose left boundary always remains after the previous occurrence of the current character.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```java\\nimport java.util.HashMap;\\nimport java.util.Map;\\n\\nclass Solution {\\n    public int lengthOfLongestSubstring(String s) {\\n        Map<Character, Integer> lastIndex = new HashMap<>();\\n        int left = 0;\\n        int best = 0;\\n\\n        for (int right = 0; right < s.length(); right++) {\\n            char ch = s.charAt(right);\\n            Integer previous = lastIndex.get(ch);\\n            if (previous != null && previous >= left) {\\n                left = previous + 1;\\n            }\\n            lastIndex.put(ch, right);\\n            best = Math.max(best, right - left + 1);\\n        }\\n\\n        return best;\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nFor `abcabcbb`, the longest valid window has length three. Updating `left` with `max`-equivalent logic prevents the window from moving backward.\\n\\nTime complexity is `O(n)` and extra space is `O(k)`, where `k` is the number of distinct characters tracked. For full Unicode code points rather than UTF-16 code units, iterate with `codePoints()` or explicit code-point indexes."},{"id":"/leetcode-0002","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0002/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/leetcode-0002.md","title":"LeetCode 2: Add Two Numbers in Java","description":"Add two numbers stored in reverse-order linked lists, handling carry values, unequal lengths, and a final carry.","date":"2020-02-14T15:02:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leetcode","permalink":"/en/tags/leetcode"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.72,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"LeetCode 2: Add Two Numbers in Java","date":"2020-02-14T15:02:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2020/leetcode-0002/","tags":["leetcode","java"],"description":"Add two numbers stored in reverse-order linked lists, handling carry values, unequal lengths, and a final carry.","keywords":["LeetCode Add Two Numbers Java","linked list addition","carry algorithm"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"LeetCode 3: Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters","permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0003/"},"nextItem":{"title":"LeetCode 1: Two Sum in Java","permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0001/"}},"content":"Each linked list stores a non-negative integer in reverse digit order. Add corresponding nodes and return the sum in the same representation.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```java\\nclass Solution {\\n    public ListNode addTwoNumbers(ListNode l1, ListNode l2) {\\n        ListNode dummy = new ListNode(0);\\n        ListNode tail = dummy;\\n        int carry = 0;\\n\\n        while (l1 != null || l2 != null || carry != 0) {\\n            int x = l1 == null ? 0 : l1.val;\\n            int y = l2 == null ? 0 : l2.val;\\n            int sum = x + y + carry;\\n\\n            carry = sum / 10;\\n            tail.next = new ListNode(sum % 10);\\n            tail = tail.next;\\n\\n            if (l1 != null) l1 = l1.next;\\n            if (l2 != null) l2 = l2.next;\\n        }\\n\\n        return dummy.next;\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe loop continues while either list has nodes or a carry remains. Missing digits are treated as zero. For `2 -> 4 -> 3` plus `5 -> 6 -> 4`, the result is `7 -> 0 -> 8`.\\n\\nTime complexity is `O(max(m, n))`; the returned list uses the same order of space."},{"id":"/leetcode-0001","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0001/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/leetcode-0001.md","title":"LeetCode 1: Two Sum in Java","description":"Solve LeetCode Two Sum with brute force and a one-pass HashMap, including complexity analysis and duplicate handling.","date":"2020-02-14T15:01:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"leetcode","permalink":"/en/tags/leetcode"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.89,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"LeetCode 1: Two Sum in Java","date":"2020-02-14T15:01:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2020/leetcode-0001/","tags":["leetcode","java"],"description":"Solve LeetCode Two Sum with brute force and a one-pass HashMap, including complexity analysis and duplicate handling.","keywords":["LeetCode Two Sum Java","HashMap algorithm","two sum solution"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"LeetCode 2: Add Two Numbers in Java","permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0002/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Windows Process Extension Experiments for an Authorized Test Application","permalink":"/en/2020/pcwechat_helper/"}},"content":"Given an integer array `nums` and an integer `target`, return the indexes of two distinct elements whose sum equals the target.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Brute force\\n\\n```java\\nclass Solution {\\n    public int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {\\n        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {\\n            for (int j = i + 1; j < nums.length; j++) {\\n                if (nums[i] + nums[j] == target) {\\n                    return new int[]{i, j};\\n                }\\n            }\\n        }\\n        throw new IllegalArgumentException(\\"No solution\\");\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nTime complexity is `O(n\xb2)` and extra space is `O(1)`.\\n\\n## One-pass HashMap\\n\\nFor each value, calculate the required complement and check whether it has already been seen:\\n\\n```java\\nimport java.util.HashMap;\\nimport java.util.Map;\\n\\nclass Solution {\\n    public int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {\\n        Map<Integer, Integer> indexByValue = new HashMap<>();\\n\\n        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {\\n            int complement = target - nums[i];\\n            if (indexByValue.containsKey(complement)) {\\n                return new int[]{indexByValue.get(complement), i};\\n            }\\n            indexByValue.put(nums[i], i);\\n        }\\n\\n        throw new IllegalArgumentException(\\"No solution\\");\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nAverage time complexity is `O(n)` and space complexity is `O(n)`. Checking before inserting prevents the current element from matching itself and correctly handles inputs such as `[3, 3]` with target `6`."},{"id":"/pcwechat_helper","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2020/pcwechat_helper/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/pcwechat_helper.md","title":"Windows Process Extension Experiments for an Authorized Test Application","description":"Study Windows process creation, module loading, IPC, version compatibility, and safe boundaries in an authorized helper-application lab.","date":"2020-02-10T22:38:21.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"c-cpp","permalink":"/en/tags/c-cpp"},{"inline":true,"label":"windows","permalink":"/en/tags/windows"}],"readingTime":0.81,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Windows Process Extension Experiments for an Authorized Test Application","date":"2020-02-10T22:38:21.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2020/pcwechat_helper/","tags":["c-cpp","windows"],"description":"Study Windows process creation, module loading, IPC, version compatibility, and safe boundaries in an authorized helper-application lab.","keywords":["Windows process extension","DLL loading lab","authorized reverse engineering"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"LeetCode 1: Two Sum in Java","permalink":"/en/2020/leetcode-0001/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Seata 0.8.1\u20131.0.0 Client Bootstrap Source Analysis","permalink":"/en/2019/seata-client-bootstrap/"}},"content":"This article records experiments in extending a Windows desktop application through a helper process and loaded module. Use these techniques only with software you own or have explicit permission to test.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nA robust lab begins with a small application built specifically for instrumentation. Record architecture, binary hashes, module bases, exported functions, process integrity level, and the exact Windows version.\\n\\nPrefer documented extension points, plugins, accessibility APIs, local RPC, or debugging interfaces over process injection. When a controlled module-loading experiment is necessary, minimize privileges, authenticate IPC, validate message lengths, and ensure the helper can shut down without leaving the target unstable.\\n\\nAbsolute addresses and internal structures change between builds because of ASLR, compiler changes, and application updates. Resolve symbols or module-relative offsets for the exact version and fail closed when validation does not match.\\n\\nNever use the helper to bypass access controls, collect other users\' data, or automate prohibited behavior. Keep test data synthetic and isolate crashes from production profiles."},{"id":"/seata-client-bootstrap","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2019/seata-client-bootstrap/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/seata-client-bootstrap.md","title":"Seata 0.8.1\u20131.0.0 Client Bootstrap Source Analysis","description":"Trace Seata client auto-configuration, transaction and resource manager initialization, registry lookup, and server registration.","date":"2019-11-07T13:56:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"seata","permalink":"/en/tags/seata"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.81,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Seata 0.8.1\u20131.0.0 Client Bootstrap Source Analysis","date":"2019-11-07T13:56:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2019/seata-client-bootstrap/","tags":["seata","java"],"description":"Trace Seata client auto-configuration, transaction and resource manager initialization, registry lookup, and server registration.","keywords":["Seata client bootstrap","TransactionManager ResourceManager","Seata source"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Windows Process Extension Experiments for an Authorized Test Application","permalink":"/en/2020/pcwechat_helper/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Understanding the Java Virtual Machine","permalink":"/en/2019/\u6df1\u5165\u7406\u89e3JVM/"}},"content":"Seata client startup wires application configuration to the transaction coordinator and prepares resource interception.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nSpring auto-configuration reads the application ID, transaction-service group, registry, configuration center, data-source settings, and enablement flags. It creates scanner or post-processor components that identify transactional beans and install proxies for global-transaction interception.\\n\\nThe client initializes a `TransactionManager` channel for global transaction begin, commit, and rollback operations. It also initializes one or more `ResourceManager` implementations, such as the AT resource manager that registers branch transactions and manages undo information.\\n\\nRegistry and configuration components resolve the transaction coordinator cluster from the service group mapping. The client establishes Netty channels and registers its application and transaction-service group with the server.\\n\\nVersions between 0.8.1 and 1.0.0 changed package names, configuration keys, and bootstrap classes, so trace the exact release tag rather than mixing source from different versions. Startup diagnostics should include effective configuration, resolved server addresses, registration results, proxy creation, and data-source wrapping."},{"id":"/\u6df1\u5165\u7406\u89e3JVM","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2019/\u6df1\u5165\u7406\u89e3JVM/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/\u6df1\u5165\u7406\u89e3JVM.md","title":"Understanding the Java Virtual Machine","description":"Understand JVM runtime memory, class loading, bytecode execution, garbage collection, JIT compilation, diagnostics, and performance troubleshooting.","date":"2019-06-30T14:40:52.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"jvm","permalink":"/en/tags/jvm"}],"readingTime":4.79,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Understanding the Java Virtual Machine","date":"2019-06-30T14:40:52.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2019/\u6df1\u5165\u7406\u89e3JVM/","tags":["java","jvm"],"description":"Understand JVM runtime memory, class loading, bytecode execution, garbage collection, JIT compilation, diagnostics, and performance troubleshooting.","keywords":["JVM internals","Java runtime data areas","class loading garbage collection"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Seata 0.8.1\u20131.0.0 Client Bootstrap Source Analysis","permalink":"/en/2019/seata-client-bootstrap/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Java List Interface and Implementations: Source-Level Overview","permalink":"/en/2019/list-source/"}},"content":"The Java Virtual Machine provides a managed execution environment for bytecode. Understanding its memory model, class lifecycle, execution engine, and diagnostics makes Java failures easier to explain and tune.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Runtime data areas\\n\\nThe JVM specification describes several logical runtime areas:\\n\\n- **Heap:** shared storage for objects and arrays, managed by the garbage collector.\\n- **Java stacks:** one stack per platform thread, containing frames for active method calls.\\n- **Program counter:** the current bytecode position for each executing thread.\\n- **Native method stack:** implementation support for native execution.\\n- **Method area:** class metadata, runtime constant pools, methods, and static information. HotSpot stores much of this in Metaspace.\\n\\nA stack frame contains local variables, an operand stack, dynamic-linking information, and return state. `StackOverflowError` commonly indicates excessive call depth, while native-thread creation and direct buffers can exhaust memory outside the Java heap.\\n\\n## Object allocation\\n\\nMost ordinary objects are allocated quickly from thread-local allocation buffers or a shared allocation region. Allocation advances a pointer when the target space is contiguous.\\n\\nObject layout usually includes a header, class metadata reference, fields, and alignment padding. Exact layout depends on JVM options, compressed references, architecture, and the selected collector.\\n\\nEscape analysis may allow scalar replacement or eliminate some allocations after JIT compilation, but developers should verify effects with profiling rather than assuming an object was optimized away.\\n\\n## Class loading lifecycle\\n\\nA class normally passes through:\\n\\n```text\\nloading \u2192 verification \u2192 preparation \u2192 resolution \u2192 initialization\\n```\\n\\nClass loaders follow a delegation model that helps preserve platform-class identity and avoid duplicate definitions. Bootstrap, platform, application, framework, module, plugin, and custom loaders may all participate.\\n\\nInitialization runs static field initializers and static blocks in source order. It occurs on first active use, subject to JVM rules. Circular initialization, duplicate classes, and incompatible loader boundaries can cause failures that resemble ordinary dependency problems.\\n\\n## Bytecode execution\\n\\nJava source is compiled to class files containing bytecode, constant-pool entries, method descriptors, attributes, and verification metadata. The interpreter can begin executing methods immediately.\\n\\nThe just-in-time compiler identifies hot methods and loops, then compiles them to optimized native code. Optimizations may include inlining, devirtualization, loop transformations, escape analysis, and dead-code elimination. If an assumption becomes invalid, the JVM can deoptimize and return execution to a less optimized form.\\n\\nWarm-up, profiling data, tiered compilation, and code-cache capacity all influence benchmark and production behavior. Microbenchmarks should use a harness such as JMH rather than manual timing loops.\\n\\n## Garbage collection\\n\\nCollectors determine object reachability from GC roots, reclaim unreachable objects, and sometimes compact or relocate surviving objects.\\n\\nGenerational collectors separate young and old objects because most allocations die quickly. A young collection usually reclaims newly allocated objects; mixed or old collections process longer-lived regions according to the collector\'s policy.\\n\\nCollector selection is a trade-off among throughput, pause time, CPU overhead, memory overhead, and heap size. G1 targets predictable pauses with regions and concurrent marking. ZGC and Shenandoah perform more relocation work concurrently to reduce pauses. Parallel GC favors throughput.\\n\\nDo not diagnose a memory problem from heap size alone. Inspect allocation rate, live-set growth, promotion, pause causes, reference processing, native memory, direct buffers, class metadata, thread stacks, and container limits.\\n\\n## Memory visibility and synchronization\\n\\nThe Java Memory Model defines when writes by one thread become visible to another and what reorderings are permitted.\\n\\n- `synchronized` provides mutual exclusion and establishes happens-before relationships.\\n- `volatile` provides visibility and ordering for a variable but does not make compound operations atomic.\\n- Atomic classes use compare-and-set and other primitives for lock-free or low-lock updates.\\n- Final-field rules provide additional initialization guarantees when objects are safely published.\\n\\nCorrect concurrent code should be reasoned about through happens-before relationships, not through assumptions about CPU speed or how often a test appears to pass.\\n\\n## Exceptions and common failures\\n\\nTypical JVM-related failures include:\\n\\n- `OutOfMemoryError: Java heap space`: allocation cannot be satisfied after collection.\\n- `OutOfMemoryError: Metaspace`: class metadata has exhausted its configured or available native memory.\\n- `OutOfMemoryError: unable to create native thread`: process, memory, or operating-system thread limits were reached.\\n- `StackOverflowError`: call depth exceeded the thread stack.\\n- `ClassNotFoundException`: explicit loading could not find a class.\\n- `NoClassDefFoundError`: a class expected at runtime could not be defined or initialized.\\n- `UnsupportedClassVersionError`: bytecode was compiled for a newer Java release.\\n\\nThe exception text is a starting point, not the complete diagnosis.\\n\\n## Diagnostic workflow\\n\\nStart with evidence:\\n\\n```bash\\njava -version\\njcmd <pid> VM.flags\\njcmd <pid> VM.system_properties\\njcmd <pid> GC.heap_info\\njcmd <pid> Thread.print\\njcmd <pid> VM.native_memory summary\\n```\\n\\nEnable useful JVM logs before an incident. On modern Java releases, unified logging can capture GC, safepoints, class loading, and related events.\\n\\nFor memory growth, compare heap histograms or heap dumps over time and identify retained paths. For high CPU, combine thread dumps with operating-system thread statistics and profiling. For latency, correlate request traces with GC pauses, safepoints, lock contention, I/O, and downstream dependencies.\\n\\nA single thread dump or heap histogram is rarely sufficient. Capture several samples and preserve the exact JVM version, command line, container limits, host state, and workload.\\n\\n## Performance principles\\n\\nMeasure an application-level objective before tuning. Throughput, tail latency, startup time, memory footprint, and cost may require different choices.\\n\\nPrefer these steps:\\n\\n1. Reproduce the issue with representative load.\\n2. Identify whether the bottleneck is CPU, allocation, locks, I/O, database, network, or an external service.\\n3. Change the application or data flow before adding obscure JVM flags.\\n4. Test one change at a time.\\n5. Compare distributions and tail latency, not only averages.\\n6. Keep a rollback path and record the complete runtime configuration.\\n\\nThe JVM adapts dynamically, so production behavior depends on warm-up, traffic shape, heap occupancy, code paths, and host contention. Reliable tuning is evidence-driven rather than a fixed collection of recommended flags."},{"id":"/list-source","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2019/list-source/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/list-source.md","title":"Java List Interface and Implementations: Source-Level Overview","description":"Compare the Java List contract and the internal structures, complexity, iteration behavior, and use cases of ArrayList, LinkedList, and Vector.","date":"2019-04-14T15:47:46.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.85,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Java List Interface and Implementations: Source-Level Overview","date":"2019-04-14T15:47:46.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2019/list-source/","tags":["java"],"description":"Compare the Java List contract and the internal structures, complexity, iteration behavior, and use cases of ArrayList, LinkedList, and Vector.","keywords":["Java List source analysis","ArrayList LinkedList Vector","Java collections"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Understanding the Java Virtual Machine","permalink":"/en/2019/\u6df1\u5165\u7406\u89e3JVM/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Install a Nacos Cluster","permalink":"/en/2019/nacos-cluster-install-md/"}},"content":"`List` defines an ordered collection that permits positional access and usually allows duplicate elements. Implementations differ substantially in storage layout and performance.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n`ArrayList` stores elements in a resizable array. Indexed reads are `O(1)`, append is amortized `O(1)`, and insertion or removal in the middle requires shifting elements. It is usually the default choice for general-purpose lists.\\n\\n`LinkedList` stores nodes linked in both directions. Adding or removing through a known iterator position is constant time, but locating an index is `O(n)` and each element carries node overhead. It also implements `Deque`.\\n\\n`Vector` is an older synchronized dynamic array. Its method-level synchronization rarely provides the compound-operation semantics an application needs. Prefer `ArrayList` with external synchronization or a purpose-built concurrent collection.\\n\\nIterators are generally fail-fast on structural modification, but this is a debugging aid rather than a concurrency guarantee. Choose an implementation according to measured access patterns, memory cost, concurrency model, and API semantics\u2014not by assuming linked lists are automatically faster for insertion."},{"id":"/nacos-cluster-install-md","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2019/nacos-cluster-install-md/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/nacos-cluster-install-md.md","title":"Install a Nacos Cluster","description":"Deploy a Nacos cluster with multiple nodes, external database storage, ports, reverse proxying, and health checks.","date":"2019-03-28T20:27:07.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"nacos","permalink":"/en/tags/nacos"}],"readingTime":0.75,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Install a Nacos Cluster","date":"2019-03-28T20:27:07.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2019/nacos-cluster-install-md/","tags":["java","nacos"],"description":"Deploy a Nacos cluster with multiple nodes, external database storage, ports, reverse proxying, and health checks.","keywords":["Nacos cluster install","Nacos MySQL","Nacos deployment"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Java List Interface and Implementations: Source-Level Overview","permalink":"/en/2019/list-source/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Decision Trees: Entropy, Gini Impurity, Pruning, and Ensembles","permalink":"/en/2019/decision_tree/"}},"content":"A production Nacos deployment should use multiple nodes and an external supported database rather than embedded standalone storage.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nList every node in `cluster.conf` using addresses reachable from all peers. Configure identical database connection settings and application properties on each node, then start the nodes one at a time and inspect their logs.\\n\\nPlace a load balancer or reverse proxy in front of client-facing endpoints, but preserve the ports and protocols required by the selected Nacos release. Nacos 2.x introduced additional gRPC ports relative to the main server port, so firewall rules must match the actual version.\\n\\nVerify cluster membership, namespace and configuration replication, service registration, and client reconnection when one node stops. Protect the console with strong authentication and network restrictions. Back up the external database, monitor heap, thread pools, request latency, database connectivity, and disk logs, and test rolling upgrades before applying them to production."},{"id":"/decision_tree","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2019/decision_tree/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/decision_tree.md","title":"Decision Trees: Entropy, Gini Impurity, Pruning, and Ensembles","description":"Understand decision-tree splits with entropy, information gain, gain ratio, Gini impurity, pruning, random forests, and gradient boosting.","date":"2019-02-14T20:27:07.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"machine-learning","permalink":"/en/tags/machine-learning"},{"inline":true,"label":"decision-tree","permalink":"/en/tags/decision-tree"},{"inline":true,"label":"xgboost","permalink":"/en/tags/xgboost"}],"readingTime":0.86,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Decision Trees: Entropy, Gini Impurity, Pruning, and Ensembles","date":"2019-02-14T20:27:07.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2019/decision_tree/","tags":["machine-learning","decision-tree","xgboost"],"description":"Understand decision-tree splits with entropy, information gain, gain ratio, Gini impurity, pruning, random forests, and gradient boosting.","keywords":["decision tree entropy","Gini impurity","ID3 C4.5 CART"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Install a Nacos Cluster","permalink":"/en/2019/nacos-cluster-install-md/"},"nextItem":{"title":"ServiceComb Saga Omega Source Analysis","permalink":"/en/2018/servicecomb-saga-1/"}},"content":"A decision tree recursively divides a dataset into regions that are increasingly pure with respect to the target variable.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nFor classification, common split criteria include entropy and Gini impurity:\\n\\n```text\\nEntropy: H(S) = -\u03a3 p\u1d62 log\u2082 p\u1d62\\nGini:    G(S) = 1 - \u03a3 p\u1d62\xb2\\n```\\n\\nID3 selects features by information gain. C4.5 uses gain ratio to reduce the bias toward high-cardinality attributes. CART commonly uses Gini impurity for classification and squared error for regression, producing binary splits.\\n\\nA fully grown tree can memorize noise. Pre-pruning limits depth, minimum samples, or minimum improvement. Post-pruning removes branches after growth according to validation performance or a complexity penalty.\\n\\nRandom forests train many decorrelated trees on bootstrap samples and random feature subsets, then aggregate their predictions. Gradient-boosted trees build trees sequentially to correct previous residuals. XGBoost adds regularization, optimized split search, and efficient handling of sparse data.\\n\\nEvaluate trees with a validation strategy appropriate to the data, inspect class imbalance and leakage, and tune complexity rather than relying only on training accuracy."},{"id":"/servicecomb-saga-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2018/servicecomb-saga-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/servicecomb-saga-1.md","title":"ServiceComb Saga Omega Source Analysis","description":"Understand ServiceComb Saga Omega interception, transaction events, compensation methods, exception handling, and Alpha coordination.","date":"2018-11-16T22:39:11.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"saga","permalink":"/en/tags/saga"},{"inline":true,"label":"distributed-transaction","permalink":"/en/tags/distributed-transaction"}],"readingTime":0.82,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"ServiceComb Saga Omega Source Analysis","date":"2018-11-16T22:39:11.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2018/servicecomb-saga-1/","tags":["saga","distributed-transaction"],"description":"Understand ServiceComb Saga Omega interception, transaction events, compensation methods, exception handling, and Alpha coordination.","keywords":["ServiceComb Saga Omega","compensation transaction","distributed saga"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Decision Trees: Entropy, Gini Impurity, Pruning, and Ensembles","permalink":"/en/2019/decision_tree/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Canal Quick Start for MySQL Binlog Subscription","permalink":"/en/2018/canal-quickstart/"}},"content":"ServiceComb Saga uses compensating actions rather than a global ACID transaction across services. Omega runs inside each service, while Alpha coordinates saga events and recovery.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nOmega intercepts methods marked as saga transactions or compensable operations. It creates transaction identifiers, reports start and completion events, and associates a forward operation with its compensation method.\\n\\nWhen a later step fails, Alpha determines which completed operations require compensation and sends commands back to the relevant services. Compensation methods must be idempotent because retries, duplicate commands, and partial failures are expected.\\n\\nA compensation is a business reversal, not a database rollback. It may need to issue a refund, restore inventory, or mark a record as canceled while preserving audit history. Some effects cannot be perfectly reversed and require manual reconciliation.\\n\\nRecord saga IDs in logs and business tables, protect event ordering assumptions, define timeouts and retry limits, and monitor stuck or repeatedly failing compensations. Test process crashes between local commit and event reporting, not only normal exceptions."},{"id":"/canal-quickstart","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2018/canal-quickstart/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/canal-quickstart.md","title":"Canal Quick Start for MySQL Binlog Subscription","description":"Configure MySQL binlog, start Canal Server, subscribe with a Java client, and troubleshoot replication permissions and positions.","date":"2018-07-06T14:27:21.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"canal","permalink":"/en/tags/canal"}],"readingTime":0.84,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Canal Quick Start for MySQL Binlog Subscription","date":"2018-07-06T14:27:21.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2018/canal-quickstart/","tags":["java","canal"],"description":"Configure MySQL binlog, start Canal Server, subscribe with a Java client, and troubleshoot replication permissions and positions.","keywords":["Alibaba Canal quick start","MySQL binlog subscription","Canal Java client"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"ServiceComb Saga Omega Source Analysis","permalink":"/en/2018/servicecomb-saga-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Troubleshoot Lombok Compilation Problems","permalink":"/en/2018/lombok-quesion-1/"}},"content":"Canal reads MySQL binary logs and exposes row-level change events to downstream consumers. It is commonly used for cache synchronization, search indexing, auditing, and data pipelines.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nEnable row-based binary logging and assign a unique server ID:\\n\\n```ini\\n[mysqld]\\nserver-id=1\\nlog-bin=mysql-bin\\nbinlog-format=ROW\\nbinlog-row-image=FULL\\n```\\n\\nCreate a dedicated replication account with only the required privileges, then configure the Canal instance with the MySQL address, credentials, destination, and starting position. Start Canal Server and inspect its instance logs before connecting a client.\\n\\nA client subscribes to a destination, fetches message batches, processes row events, and acknowledges only after downstream work succeeds. Roll back or leave the batch unacknowledged when processing fails.\\n\\nIf no events arrive, verify binlog is enabled, the account can read it, the position still exists, filters match the database and table, clocks are correct, and the client is connected to the expected destination. Consumers must be idempotent because reconnects and retries can produce duplicate processing."},{"id":"/lombok-quesion-1","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2018/lombok-quesion-1/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/lombok-quesion-1.md","title":"Troubleshoot Lombok Compilation Problems","description":"Diagnose Lombok failures involving annotation processing, IDE plugins, Java and compiler versions, build tools, and generated code.","date":"2018-04-04T21:32:38.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"lombok","permalink":"/en/tags/lombok"}],"readingTime":0.76,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Troubleshoot Lombok Compilation Problems","date":"2018-04-04T21:32:38.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2018/lombok-quesion-1/","tags":["java","lombok"],"description":"Diagnose Lombok failures involving annotation processing, IDE plugins, Java and compiler versions, build tools, and generated code.","keywords":["Lombok compilation error","annotation processing","Lombok IDE plugin"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Canal Quick Start for MySQL Binlog Subscription","permalink":"/en/2018/canal-quickstart/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Build a Java Agent with Instrumentation","permalink":"/en/2018/java-agent-01/"}},"content":"Lombok modifies compilation through annotation processing. A project may build in Maven while the IDE reports errors, or work in the IDE while CI fails, when those environments use different processors or Java versions.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nConfirm the Lombok dependency version and inspect the effective Maven or Gradle configuration. Enable annotation processing in the IDE and install the matching plugin when the IDE requires one.\\n\\nRun a clean command-line build with the same JDK used by CI:\\n\\n```bash\\nmvn clean test\\n# or\\ngradle clean test\\n```\\n\\nCheck whether generated methods appear in compiled bytecode or delomboked source. Ensure the compiler plugin, `source`/`target` or `release`, Lombok, JDK, and framework versions are compatible.\\n\\nDo not rely on stale IDE caches as the first explanation. Capture the actual compiler error and processor path. For public APIs and long-lived domain models, weigh Lombok\'s convenience against hidden generated behavior, constructor changes, equality semantics, and toolchain coupling."},{"id":"/java-agent-01","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2018/java-agent-01/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/java-agent-01.md","title":"Build a Java Agent with Instrumentation","description":"Build Java agents with premain, agentmain, Instrumentation, class transformers, retransformation, and manifest attributes.","date":"2018-03-22T21:28:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.8,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Build a Java Agent with Instrumentation","date":"2018-03-22T21:28:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2018/java-agent-01/","tags":["java"],"description":"Build Java agents with premain, agentmain, Instrumentation, class transformers, retransformation, and manifest attributes.","keywords":["Java agent","Instrumentation API","ClassFileTransformer"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Troubleshoot Lombok Compilation Problems","permalink":"/en/2018/lombok-quesion-1/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Schedule Tasks with Spring","permalink":"/en/2018/spring-scheduling-tasks/"}},"content":"A Java agent can observe or transform classes as the JVM loads them. Startup agents enter through `premain`; agents attached to a running JVM enter through `agentmain`.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```java\\npublic final class Agent {\\n    public static void premain(String args, Instrumentation inst) {\\n        inst.addTransformer(new LoggingTransformer(), true);\\n    }\\n\\n    public static void agentmain(String args, Instrumentation inst) {\\n        inst.addTransformer(new LoggingTransformer(), true);\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe agent JAR manifest must declare the appropriate entry point:\\n\\n```text\\nPremain-Class: example.Agent\\nAgent-Class: example.Agent\\nCan-Redefine-Classes: true\\nCan-Retransform-Classes: true\\n```\\n\\nA `ClassFileTransformer` receives raw class bytes and may return modified bytes. Do not instrument the agent itself or core classes unintentionally, and keep transformation code deterministic and fast.\\n\\nBytecode changes must preserve verifier rules, stack maps, method semantics, and compatibility with the target Java version. Libraries such as Byte Buddy or ASM are safer than editing class bytes manually. Agents run with powerful in-process access, so protect attach permissions and treat agent code as production-critical infrastructure."},{"id":"/spring-scheduling-tasks","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2018/spring-scheduling-tasks/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/spring-scheduling-tasks.md","title":"Schedule Tasks with Spring","description":"Configure Spring @Scheduled tasks with fixed delays, rates, cron expressions, thread pools, and distributed execution safeguards.","date":"2018-01-03T22:54:21.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"spring","permalink":"/en/tags/spring"},{"inline":true,"label":"spring-boot","permalink":"/en/tags/spring-boot"}],"readingTime":0.56,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Schedule Tasks with Spring","date":"2018-01-03T22:54:21.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2018/spring-scheduling-tasks/","tags":["java","spring","spring-boot"],"description":"Configure Spring @Scheduled tasks with fixed delays, rates, cron expressions, thread pools, and distributed execution safeguards.","keywords":["Spring scheduled task","@Scheduled cron","Spring task scheduler"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Build a Java Agent with Instrumentation","permalink":"/en/2018/java-agent-01/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Build a RocketMQ Cluster","permalink":"/en/2017/rocketmq-02/"}},"content":"Enable scheduling with `@EnableScheduling`, then annotate managed bean methods with `@Scheduled`.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```java\\n@Component\\npublic class CleanupJob {\\n    @Scheduled(cron = \\"0 0 2 * * *\\", zone = \\"UTC\\")\\n    public void cleanExpiredData() {\\n        // idempotent cleanup\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\n`fixedRate` measures from the previous start, while `fixedDelay` measures from the previous completion:\\n\\n```java\\n@Scheduled(fixedDelayString = \\"${jobs.delay-ms:60000}\\")\\n```\\n\\nThe default scheduler may execute tasks on one thread. Configure a `ThreadPoolTaskScheduler` when independent jobs should run concurrently, and define error handling so exceptions are observable.\\n\\nIn a multi-instance deployment, every instance normally runs the same scheduled method. Use a distributed lock, leader election, or an external scheduler to prevent duplicate work. Jobs should be idempotent, bounded by timeouts, monitored, and safe to retry."},{"id":"/rocketmq-02","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2017/rocketmq-02/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/rocketmq-02.md","title":"Build a RocketMQ Cluster","description":"Deploy a RocketMQ cluster with multiple NameServers, broker groups, primary and replica roles, ports, and failure verification.","date":"2017-11-19T15:44:28.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"rocketmq","permalink":"/en/tags/rocketmq"}],"readingTime":0.84,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Build a RocketMQ Cluster","date":"2017-11-19T15:44:28.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2017/rocketmq-02/","tags":["java","rocketmq"],"description":"Deploy a RocketMQ cluster with multiple NameServers, broker groups, primary and replica roles, ports, and failure verification.","keywords":["RocketMQ cluster setup","RocketMQ broker replica","NameServer cluster"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Schedule Tasks with Spring","permalink":"/en/2018/spring-scheduling-tasks/"},"nextItem":{"title":"RocketMQ Quick Start","permalink":"/en/2017/rocketmq-01/"}},"content":"A RocketMQ cluster normally uses multiple independent NameServers and one or more broker groups. Each broker group has a stable `brokerName`; broker ID `0` is the primary and nonzero IDs are replicas in older master/slave terminology.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nConfigure each broker with a unique listening port, storage path, role, flush mode, and the complete NameServer address list. Ensure every node resolves advertised hostnames consistently and that firewalls permit the required broker, HA, and management ports.\\n\\nStart NameServers first, then brokers. Verify registration with the administrative tools and create a test topic. Send messages, consume them, and inspect queue distribution.\\n\\nA cluster is not validated until failure behavior is tested. Stop a NameServer and confirm routing still works. Stop a broker and observe producer retries, replica availability, consumer lag, and recovery. Replication mode affects durability and write latency, while automatic failover capabilities vary by RocketMQ architecture and release.\\n\\nSeparate storage failure domains, monitor commit-log disk usage, synchronize clocks, protect administrative endpoints, and rehearse replacement and restore procedures."},{"id":"/rocketmq-01","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2017/rocketmq-01/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/rocketmq-01.md","title":"RocketMQ Quick Start","description":"Understand RocketMQ NameServer, brokers, producers, consumers, topics, queues, and the basic message flow.","date":"2017-11-03T23:08:22.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"rocketmq","permalink":"/en/tags/rocketmq"}],"readingTime":0.67,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"RocketMQ Quick Start","date":"2017-11-03T23:08:22.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2017/rocketmq-01/","tags":["java","rocketmq"],"description":"Understand RocketMQ NameServer, brokers, producers, consumers, topics, queues, and the basic message flow.","keywords":["RocketMQ quick start","NameServer broker","RocketMQ producer consumer"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Build a RocketMQ Cluster","permalink":"/en/2017/rocketmq-02/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Read Ten Million Database Rows Efficiently with Java","permalink":"/en/2017/how-to-fetch-1000w-from-db/"}},"content":"RocketMQ is a distributed messaging platform built around NameServer discovery, brokers that store messages, producers, consumers, topics, and message queues.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nStart a NameServer, then start a broker configured to register with it. Producers query NameServer for topic routing, select a queue, and send the message to a broker. Consumers discover the same routing information and pull or receive messages according to their consumer group.\\n\\nA topic is a logical message category; queues within the topic provide parallelism and ordering boundaries. Ordering is guaranteed only within the same queue, not across an entire topic.\\n\\nBefore production use, configure persistent storage, replication, retention, disk thresholds, ACLs, TLS where required, retry and dead-letter behavior, and monitoring. Producers should define send timeouts and retry policy. Consumers should be idempotent because redelivery can occur after failures."},{"id":"/how-to-fetch-1000w-from-db","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2017/how-to-fetch-1000w-from-db/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/how-to-fetch-1000w-from-db.md","title":"Read Ten Million Database Rows Efficiently with Java","description":"Process tens of millions of database rows with streaming cursors, keyset pagination, fetch sizes, bounded memory, and Spring Batch.","date":"2017-10-13T23:26:58.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"jdbc","permalink":"/en/tags/jdbc"},{"inline":true,"label":"cursor","permalink":"/en/tags/cursor"}],"readingTime":1.09,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Read Ten Million Database Rows Efficiently with Java","date":"2017-10-13T23:26:58.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2017/how-to-fetch-1000w-from-db/","tags":["java","jdbc","cursor"],"description":"Process tens of millions of database rows with streaming cursors, keyset pagination, fetch sizes, bounded memory, and Spring Batch.","keywords":["JDBC streaming large result set","MySQL cursor fetch","Java large data export"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"RocketMQ Quick Start","permalink":"/en/2017/rocketmq-01/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Build a Simple Web Crawler with Python","permalink":"/en/2017/python-simple-spider/"}},"content":"Loading ten million rows into a Java `List` is rarely safe. It can create a long transaction, exhaust heap memory, and overload the database. First decide whether the job is an online query, offline export, or migration, then choose streaming or partitioned processing.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Avoid deep OFFSET pagination\\n\\n`LIMIT offset, size` becomes expensive when the offset is large because the database still scans or sorts skipped rows. Prefer keyset pagination based on a stable indexed column:\\n\\n```sql\\nSELECT *\\nFROM source_table\\nWHERE id > ?\\nORDER BY id\\nLIMIT 1000;\\n```\\n\\nStore the last processed `id` and use it for the next batch.\\n\\n## Stream rows with a JDBC cursor\\n\\nFor MySQL Connector/J, enable cursor fetching and set a bounded fetch size:\\n\\n```properties\\njdbc:mysql://host:3306/test?useUnicode=true&characterEncoding=UTF-8&useCursorFetch=true&defaultFetchSize=1000\\n```\\n\\n- `useCursorFetch=true` enables cursor-based retrieval.\\n- `defaultFetchSize=1000` controls the number of rows fetched per round trip.\\n\\nKeep autocommit and transaction settings compatible with the driver version. Process each row immediately instead of accumulating the complete result in memory.\\n\\n## Spring Batch\\n\\nWhen using `JdbcCursorItemReader`, some drivers do not report cursor positions as Spring Batch expects. In that case:\\n\\n```java\\nreader.setVerifyCursorPosition(false);\\n```\\n\\nUse chunk-oriented writes, checkpoints, idempotent consumers, and retry rules. Monitor database load, Redis throughput, failed records, and restart behavior before running the full migration."},{"id":"/python-simple-spider","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2017/python-simple-spider/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/python-simple-spider.md","title":"Build a Simple Web Crawler with Python","description":"Build a small Python crawler with HTTP requests, HTML parsing, encoding handling, retries, rate limits, and structured data storage.","date":"2017-09-23T08:21:32.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"python","permalink":"/en/tags/python"},{"inline":true,"label":"spider","permalink":"/en/tags/spider"}],"readingTime":0.66,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Build a Simple Web Crawler with Python","date":"2017-09-23T08:21:32.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2017/python-simple-spider/","tags":["python","spider"],"description":"Build a small Python crawler with HTTP requests, HTML parsing, encoding handling, retries, rate limits, and structured data storage.","keywords":["Python web crawler","requests BeautifulSoup","scraping tutorial"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Read Ten Million Database Rows Efficiently with Java","permalink":"/en/2017/how-to-fetch-1000w-from-db/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Install Redis 3.2.10 as a Standalone Service","permalink":"/en/2017/redis-single-install/"}},"content":"A basic crawler downloads a page, verifies the response, parses the HTML, extracts required fields, and stores normalized results.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```python\\nimport requests\\nfrom bs4 import BeautifulSoup\\n\\nresponse = requests.get(\\n    \\"https://example.com/\\",\\n    timeout=10,\\n    headers={\\"User-Agent\\": \\"ExampleResearchBot/1.0\\"},\\n)\\nresponse.raise_for_status()\\n\\nsoup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, \\"html.parser\\")\\nfor link in soup.select(\\"a[href]\\"):\\n    print(link.get_text(strip=True), link.get(\\"href\\"))\\n```\\n\\nSet connection and read timeouts, retry only transient failures with backoff, and limit concurrency. Respect robots directives, site terms, copyright, privacy, and access controls. Do not bypass authentication, anti-bot controls, or rate limits.\\n\\nResolve relative URLs, deduplicate requests, validate content types, and handle the declared or detected encoding. Store source URL, retrieval time, and parsing version so data can be audited. A production crawler also needs scheduling, persistent queues, observability, and a clear deletion policy."},{"id":"/redis-single-install","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2017/redis-single-install/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/redis-single-install.md","title":"Install Redis 3.2.10 as a Standalone Service","description":"Compile and configure Redis 3.2.10, start it as a service, enable persistence and authentication, and verify connectivity.","date":"2017-09-19T22:59:25.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"redis","permalink":"/en/tags/redis"}],"readingTime":0.61,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Install Redis 3.2.10 as a Standalone Service","date":"2017-09-19T22:59:25.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2017/redis-single-install/","tags":["redis"],"description":"Compile and configure Redis 3.2.10, start it as a service, enable persistence and authentication, and verify connectivity.","keywords":["Redis 3.2 install","Redis standalone","redis.conf"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Build a Simple Web Crawler with Python","permalink":"/en/2017/python-simple-spider/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Manage Cookies with Apache HttpClient","permalink":"/en/2017/httpclient-cookie/"}},"content":"Redis 3.2.10 is a historical release. Use it only for legacy compatibility and isolate it from untrusted networks.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nTypical source installation steps are:\\n\\n```bash\\ntar -xzf redis-3.2.10.tar.gz\\ncd redis-3.2.10\\nmake\\nmake test\\nsudo make install\\n```\\n\\nCopy `redis.conf` to a managed configuration directory and set the bind address, protected mode, data directory, log file, and persistence policy. Start Redis through a system service rather than an unmanaged shell session.\\n\\nVerify locally:\\n\\n```bash\\nredis-cli ping\\n# PONG\\n```\\n\\nConfigure authentication, but do not rely on a password as the only protection. Restrict port `6379` with a firewall, bind only trusted interfaces, disable dangerous commands when appropriate, monitor memory and eviction, and back up RDB/AOF data according to recovery requirements."},{"id":"/httpclient-cookie","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2017/httpclient-cookie/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/httpclient-cookie.md","title":"Manage Cookies with Apache HttpClient","description":"Use CookieStore and HttpClientContext to preserve HTTP sessions, inspect cookies, and persist them carefully.","date":"2017-09-15T01:30:18.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"httpclient","permalink":"/en/tags/httpclient"},{"inline":true,"label":"cookie","permalink":"/en/tags/cookie"}],"readingTime":0.59,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Manage Cookies with Apache HttpClient","date":"2017-09-15T01:30:18.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2017/httpclient-cookie/","tags":["httpclient","cookie"],"description":"Use CookieStore and HttpClientContext to preserve HTTP sessions, inspect cookies, and persist them carefully.","keywords":["Apache HttpClient cookies","CookieStore","Java HTTP session"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Install Redis 3.2.10 as a Standalone Service","permalink":"/en/2017/redis-single-install/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Essential Java Startup and JVM Arguments Explained","permalink":"/en/2017/java-startup-arguments/"}},"content":"Apache HttpClient can preserve cookies between requests through a shared `CookieStore` and request context.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```java\\nCookieStore cookieStore = new BasicCookieStore();\\n\\ntry (CloseableHttpClient client = HttpClients.custom()\\n        .setDefaultCookieStore(cookieStore)\\n        .build()) {\\n\\n    HttpClientContext context = HttpClientContext.create();\\n    context.setCookieStore(cookieStore);\\n\\n    client.execute(new HttpGet(\\"https://example.com/login\\"), context).close();\\n    client.execute(new HttpGet(\\"https://example.com/account\\"), context).close();\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe store applies domain, path, expiry, secure, and policy rules. A cookie is not simply a name/value pair that should be sent to every host.\\n\\nWhen persisting cookies across process restarts, protect session and authentication values as secrets, retain all required attributes, discard expired entries, and prevent cross-user mixing. Avoid logging complete cookies. Modern sites may also require CSRF tokens, redirects, JavaScript, or additional authentication state beyond cookies."},{"id":"/java-startup-arguments","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2017/java-startup-arguments/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/java-startup-arguments.md","title":"Essential Java Startup and JVM Arguments Explained","description":"Understand common Java startup arguments including heap sizing, G1 GC, heap dumps, system properties, argument ordering, and troubleshooting practices.","date":"2017-09-06T08:30:02.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"jvm","permalink":"/en/tags/jvm"},{"inline":true,"label":"jmeter","permalink":"/en/tags/jmeter"}],"readingTime":1.49,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Essential Java Startup and JVM Arguments Explained","date":"2017-09-06T08:30:02.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2017/java-startup-arguments/","tags":["java","jvm","jmeter"],"description":"Understand common Java startup arguments including heap sizing, G1 GC, heap dumps, system properties, argument ordering, and troubleshooting practices.","keywords":["Java startup arguments","JVM options","Java G1GC options"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Manage Cookies with Apache HttpClient","permalink":"/en/2017/httpclient-cookie/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Safely Restart a Java Application on Linux","permalink":"/en/2017/linux-restart-java-application/"}},"content":"This note explains a typical Java startup command used while running load tests on Linux:\\n\\n```bash\\njava -server \\\\\\n  -XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError \\\\\\n  -Xms512m \\\\\\n  -Xmx512m \\\\\\n  -XX:+UseG1GC \\\\\\n  -XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=250 \\\\\\n  -XX:G1ReservePercent=20 \\\\\\n  -Djava.security.egd=file:/dev/urandom \\\\\\n  -jar xxxx.jar\\n```\\n\\nJVM options must appear before `-jar` or the main class. Application arguments belong after the JAR name or main class. When diagnosing startup problems, record the exact command, Java version, environment variables, operating-system limits, and container memory limits.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Option reference\\n\\n- `-server`: selects the server compiler and runtime profile. On modern 64-bit JDKs, the server VM is generally the default.\\n- `-XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError`: writes a heap dump when an `OutOfMemoryError` occurs. Also configure `-XX:HeapDumpPath` so the output location is predictable and writable.\\n- `-Xms512m`: sets the initial Java heap size to 512 MB.\\n- `-Xmx512m`: sets the maximum Java heap size to 512 MB.\\n- `-XX:+UseG1GC`: selects the G1 garbage collector. G1 is already the default on many current JDK releases.\\n- `-XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=250`: defines a soft pause-time target for G1. It is not a strict maximum.\\n- `-XX:G1ReservePercent=20`: reserves part of the heap to reduce evacuation and promotion failures. Increasing it leaves less space for ordinary allocations.\\n- `-Djava.security.egd=file:/dev/urandom`: sets a Java system property related to the entropy source. Its effect depends on the JDK and operating system, so verify whether it is still needed on your runtime.\\n\\nCheck the active runtime and resolved flags with:\\n\\n```bash\\njava -version\\njava -XX:+PrintFlagsFinal -version\\n```\\n\\nFor production services, prefer observable and version-appropriate GC logging, for example with unified logging on JDK 9 and later:\\n\\n```bash\\n-Xlog:gc*,safepoint:file=/var/log/app/gc.log:time,uptime,level,tags:filecount=10,filesize=20M\\n```\\n\\nDo not copy JVM tuning options blindly between applications. Start from measured heap usage, allocation rate, pause requirements, and the resource limits of the deployment environment."},{"id":"/linux-restart-java-application","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2017/linux-restart-java-application/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/linux-restart-java-application.md","title":"Safely Restart a Java Application on Linux","description":"Restart a Java JAR safely on Linux using systemd, graceful SIGTERM shutdown, PID tracking, health checks, logs, restart policies, and a shell-script fallback.","date":"2017-09-02T06:49:33.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"linux","permalink":"/en/tags/linux"},{"inline":true,"label":"shell","permalink":"/en/tags/shell"},{"inline":true,"label":"scripts","permalink":"/en/tags/scripts"}],"readingTime":2.17,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Safely Restart a Java Application on Linux","date":"2017-09-02T06:49:33.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2017/linux-restart-java-application/","tags":["linux","shell","scripts"],"description":"Restart a Java JAR safely on Linux using systemd, graceful SIGTERM shutdown, PID tracking, health checks, logs, restart policies, and a shell-script fallback.","keywords":["restart Java application Linux","Java systemd service","restart JAR"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Essential Java Startup and JVM Arguments Explained","permalink":"/en/2017/java-startup-arguments/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Send Text, HTML, and Attachment Emails with Spring Boot","permalink":"/en/2017/spring-boot-send-mail/"}},"content":"Production Java processes should normally be managed by systemd, a container orchestrator, or another supervisor. Searching `ps` output and killing a matched PID is fragile: it can select the grep process, match multiple applications, or start a duplicate instance.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Recommended: a systemd service\\n\\nCreate `/etc/systemd/system/myapp.service`:\\n\\n```ini\\n[Unit]\\nDescription=My Java Application\\nAfter=network-online.target\\nWants=network-online.target\\n\\n[Service]\\nType=simple\\nUser=myapp\\nGroup=myapp\\nWorkingDirectory=/opt/myapp\\nExecStart=/usr/bin/java -Xms512m -Xmx512m -jar /opt/myapp/myapp.jar\\nSuccessExitStatus=143\\nRestart=on-failure\\nRestartSec=5\\nTimeoutStopSec=45\\nKillSignal=SIGTERM\\nEnvironmentFile=-/etc/myapp/myapp.env\\n\\n[Install]\\nWantedBy=multi-user.target\\n```\\n\\nCreate a non-login service user, make application files readable but not writable by unrelated users, and keep secrets in a restricted environment file or secrets manager.\\n\\nLoad and use the service:\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo systemctl daemon-reload\\nsudo systemctl enable --now myapp\\nsudo systemctl restart myapp\\nsudo systemctl status myapp\\njournalctl -u myapp -n 100 --no-pager\\n```\\n\\nSystemd tracks the actual process, serializes lifecycle operations, captures logs, and can restart failures.\\n\\n## Graceful shutdown\\n\\nA normal `systemctl stop` sends `SIGTERM`. The application should stop accepting traffic, finish or reject in-flight work, close database connections, and exit before `TimeoutStopSec`. Spring Boot handles SIGTERM gracefully when its shutdown settings and surrounding infrastructure are configured correctly.\\n\\nDo not use `kill -9` as the first action. `SIGKILL` prevents cleanup and can leave partial work or stale locks. Reserve it for a process that does not exit after the documented grace period.\\n\\n## Health verification\\n\\nA process being alive does not mean it is ready. After restart, check a readiness endpoint:\\n\\n```bash\\nfor attempt in {1..30}; do\\n  if curl --fail --silent http://127.0.0.1:8080/actuator/health/readiness; then\\n    exit 0\\n  fi\\n  sleep 2\\ndone\\nexit 1\\n```\\n\\nLoad balancers should remove the instance before shutdown and add it back only after readiness succeeds.\\n\\n## Shell-script fallback\\n\\nIf systemd is unavailable, use a PID file created when the process starts:\\n\\n```bash\\n#!/usr/bin/env bash\\nset -euo pipefail\\n\\nAPP=/opt/myapp/myapp.jar\\nPIDFILE=/run/user/$(id -u)/myapp.pid\\nLOG=/var/log/myapp/application.log\\n\\nif [[ -f \\"$PIDFILE\\" ]] && kill -0 \\"$(<\\"$PIDFILE\\")\\" 2>/dev/null; then\\n  pid=$(<\\"$PIDFILE\\")\\n  kill -TERM \\"$pid\\"\\n  for _ in {1..30}; do\\n    kill -0 \\"$pid\\" 2>/dev/null || break\\n    sleep 1\\n  done\\n  if kill -0 \\"$pid\\" 2>/dev/null; then\\n    echo \\"Application did not stop gracefully\\" >&2\\n    exit 1\\n  fi\\nfi\\n\\nnohup java -jar \\"$APP\\" >>\\"$LOG\\" 2>&1 &\\necho $! >\\"$PIDFILE\\"\\n```\\n\\nAdd locking if concurrent executions are possible, rotate logs, and verify startup health. This fallback is still less reliable than a supervisor, so migrate to systemd or an orchestrator when possible."},{"id":"/spring-boot-send-mail","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2017/spring-boot-send-mail/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/spring-boot-send-mail.md","title":"Send Text, HTML, and Attachment Emails with Spring Boot","description":"Configure JavaMailSender and send plain text, HTML, and attachment emails securely with Spring Boot.","date":"2017-09-02T04:41:23.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"spring-boot","permalink":"/en/tags/spring-boot"},{"inline":true,"label":"spring","permalink":"/en/tags/spring"},{"inline":true,"label":"mail","permalink":"/en/tags/mail"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.6,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Send Text, HTML, and Attachment Emails with Spring Boot","date":"2017-09-02T04:41:23.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2017/spring-boot-send-mail/","tags":["spring-boot","spring","mail","java"],"description":"Configure JavaMailSender and send plain text, HTML, and attachment emails securely with Spring Boot.","keywords":["Spring Boot send email","JavaMailSender","MimeMessageHelper"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Safely Restart a Java Application on Linux","permalink":"/en/2017/linux-restart-java-application/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Install MongoDB on Linux","permalink":"/en/2017/mongodb-linux-install-tutorial/"}},"content":"Add the Spring Boot mail starter and configure the provider\'s SMTP host, port, authentication, and TLS mode. Store credentials in environment variables or a secret manager.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nPlain text:\\n\\n```java\\nSimpleMailMessage message = new SimpleMailMessage();\\nmessage.setTo(\\"receiver@example.com\\");\\nmessage.setSubject(\\"Hello\\");\\nmessage.setText(\\"Plain-text message\\");\\nmailSender.send(message);\\n```\\n\\nHTML and attachments:\\n\\n```java\\nMimeMessage mime = mailSender.createMimeMessage();\\nMimeMessageHelper helper = new MimeMessageHelper(mime, true, \\"UTF-8\\");\\nhelper.setTo(\\"receiver@example.com\\");\\nhelper.setSubject(\\"Report\\");\\nhelper.setText(\\"<h1>Report</h1>\\", true);\\nhelper.addAttachment(\\"report.pdf\\", new File(\\"/safe/path/report.pdf\\"));\\nmailSender.send(mime);\\n```\\n\\nDo not insert untrusted HTML without sanitization. Validate attachment paths and sizes, set connection and write timeouts, log provider response identifiers rather than message contents, and use asynchronous delivery or a queue when email should not delay an HTTP request."},{"id":"/mongodb-linux-install-tutorial","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2017/mongodb-linux-install-tutorial/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/mongodb-linux-install-tutorial.md","title":"Install MongoDB on Linux","description":"Install MongoDB on Linux, configure data and log directories, bind addresses, authentication, service startup, and connection verification.","date":"2017-08-18T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"mongodb","permalink":"/en/tags/mongodb"},{"inline":true,"label":"linux","permalink":"/en/tags/linux"}],"readingTime":0.58,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Install MongoDB on Linux","date":"2017-08-18T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2017/mongodb-linux-install-tutorial/","tags":["mongodb","linux"],"description":"Install MongoDB on Linux, configure data and log directories, bind addresses, authentication, service startup, and connection verification.","keywords":["MongoDB Linux install","mongod configuration","MongoDB authentication"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Send Text, HTML, and Attachment Emails with Spring Boot","permalink":"/en/2017/spring-boot-send-mail/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Delete or Update Rows Referenced by MySQL Foreign Keys","permalink":"/en/2017/mysql-delete-or-update-foreign-key-data/"}},"content":"Install MongoDB from the official repository for your distribution whenever possible. Repository packages provide service files, upgrades, and dependency management.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nAfter installation, review `/etc/mongod.conf`:\\n\\n```yaml\\nstorage:\\n  dbPath: /var/lib/mongodb\\nsystemLog:\\n  destination: file\\n  path: /var/log/mongodb/mongod.log\\n  logAppend: true\\nnet:\\n  port: 27017\\n  bindIp: 127.0.0.1\\n```\\n\\nStart and enable the service:\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo systemctl enable --now mongod\\nsudo systemctl status mongod\\n```\\n\\nConnect locally:\\n\\n```bash\\nmongosh\\n```\\n\\nCreate an administrator before enabling authorization, then set:\\n\\n```yaml\\nsecurity:\\n  authorization: enabled\\n```\\n\\nRestart MongoDB and verify authenticated access. Do not bind `0.0.0.0` or expose port `27017` publicly without authentication, firewall restrictions, TLS, backups, and monitoring. Ensure the data directory is owned by the MongoDB service account and has enough capacity."},{"id":"/mysql-delete-or-update-foreign-key-data","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2017/mysql-delete-or-update-foreign-key-data/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/mysql-delete-or-update-foreign-key-data.md","title":"Delete or Update Rows Referenced by MySQL Foreign Keys","description":"Resolve MySQL foreign-key delete and update failures with dependency ordering, cascades, and careful use of FOREIGN_KEY_CHECKS.","date":"2017-08-07T04:31:40.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"mysql","permalink":"/en/tags/mysql"},{"inline":true,"label":"foreign-key","permalink":"/en/tags/foreign-key"}],"readingTime":0.7,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Delete or Update Rows Referenced by MySQL Foreign Keys","date":"2017-08-07T04:31:40.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2017/mysql-delete-or-update-foreign-key-data/","tags":["mysql","foreign-key"],"description":"Resolve MySQL foreign-key delete and update failures with dependency ordering, cascades, and careful use of FOREIGN_KEY_CHECKS.","keywords":["MySQL foreign key delete","ON DELETE CASCADE","FOREIGN_KEY_CHECKS"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Install MongoDB on Linux","permalink":"/en/2017/mongodb-linux-install-tutorial/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Build an Executable JAR with Maven","permalink":"/en/2017/maven-package-execute-jar/"}},"content":"MySQL rejects a parent-row delete or key update when dependent child rows would violate a foreign-key constraint.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nThe safest solution is to handle dependencies explicitly:\\n\\n```sql\\nSTART TRANSACTION;\\nDELETE FROM order_items WHERE order_id = 1001;\\nDELETE FROM orders WHERE id = 1001;\\nCOMMIT;\\n```\\n\\nWhen the domain requires automatic cleanup, define the relationship with an appropriate action:\\n\\n```sql\\nFOREIGN KEY (order_id)\\nREFERENCES orders(id)\\nON DELETE CASCADE\\nON UPDATE CASCADE\\n```\\n\\nUse `CASCADE` only when deleting the parent should unquestionably delete children. `SET NULL` may be more appropriate when history must remain.\\n\\nTemporarily disabling checks is risky:\\n\\n```sql\\nSET FOREIGN_KEY_CHECKS = 0;\\n-- controlled maintenance operation\\nSET FOREIGN_KEY_CHECKS = 1;\\n```\\n\\nRe-enabling the variable does not automatically validate inconsistent rows created while checks were disabled. Use it only for reviewed imports or maintenance, in a dedicated session, with backups and post-operation integrity checks."},{"id":"/maven-package-execute-jar","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2017/maven-package-execute-jar/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/maven-package-execute-jar.md","title":"Build an Executable JAR with Maven","description":"Build executable Java JARs with Maven using Main-Class manifests, dependency classpaths, Maven Shade Plugin, reproducible builds, and runtime verification.","date":"2017-08-02T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"maven","permalink":"/en/tags/maven"},{"inline":true,"label":"packaging","permalink":"/en/tags/packaging"},{"inline":true,"label":"executable-jar","permalink":"/en/tags/executable-jar"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":1.77,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Build an Executable JAR with Maven","date":"2017-08-02T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2017/maven-package-execute-jar/","tags":["maven","packaging","executable-jar","java"],"description":"Build executable Java JARs with Maven using Main-Class manifests, dependency classpaths, Maven Shade Plugin, reproducible builds, and runtime verification.","keywords":["Maven executable JAR","Maven Shade Plugin","Java fat JAR"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Delete or Update Rows Referenced by MySQL Foreign Keys","permalink":"/en/2017/mysql-delete-or-update-foreign-key-data/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Common Spring Data Redis Problems and Solutions","permalink":"/en/2017/spring-redis-question/"}},"content":"A plain Maven JAR normally contains only your project\'s compiled classes and resources. To run it with `java -jar`, the archive needs a `Main-Class` manifest entry, and every runtime dependency must either be available on the classpath or packaged into an executable \\"fat\\" JAR.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Option 1: thin JAR with a main class\\n\\nConfigure `maven-jar-plugin`:\\n\\n```xml\\n<build>\\n  <plugins>\\n    <plugin>\\n      <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>\\n      <artifactId>maven-jar-plugin</artifactId>\\n      <version>3.4.2</version>\\n      <configuration>\\n        <archive>\\n          <manifest>\\n            <mainClass>com.example.Main</mainClass>\\n          </manifest>\\n        </archive>\\n      </configuration>\\n    </plugin>\\n  </plugins>\\n</build>\\n```\\n\\nBuild it:\\n\\n```bash\\nmvn clean verify\\njava -jar target/my-app-1.0.0.jar\\n```\\n\\nThis works only when the application has no external runtime dependencies or those dependencies are supplied separately.\\n\\n## Option 2: executable fat JAR with Shade\\n\\nThe Maven Shade Plugin combines application classes and dependencies:\\n\\n```xml\\n<build>\\n  <plugins>\\n    <plugin>\\n      <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>\\n      <artifactId>maven-shade-plugin</artifactId>\\n      <version>3.6.0</version>\\n      <executions>\\n        <execution>\\n          <phase>package</phase>\\n          <goals>\\n            <goal>shade</goal>\\n          </goals>\\n          <configuration>\\n            <createDependencyReducedPom>true</createDependencyReducedPom>\\n            <transformers>\\n              <transformer implementation=\\"org.apache.maven.plugins.shade.resource.ManifestResourceTransformer\\">\\n                <mainClass>com.example.Main</mainClass>\\n              </transformer>\\n              <transformer implementation=\\"org.apache.maven.plugins.shade.resource.ServicesResourceTransformer\\"/>\\n            </transformers>\\n          </configuration>\\n        </execution>\\n      </executions>\\n    </plugin>\\n  </plugins>\\n</build>\\n```\\n\\nThe services transformer merges `META-INF/services` entries used by Java\'s service loader. Other resource files may also require explicit merge rules.\\n\\n## Signed dependency errors\\n\\nShading signed JARs can leave signature metadata that no longer matches the merged archive. If runtime verification fails with a signature error, exclude signature files:\\n\\n```xml\\n<filters>\\n  <filter>\\n    <artifact>*:*</artifact>\\n    <excludes>\\n      <exclude>META-INF/*.SF</exclude>\\n      <exclude>META-INF/*.DSA</exclude>\\n      <exclude>META-INF/*.RSA</exclude>\\n    </excludes>\\n  </filter>\\n</filters>\\n```\\n\\nOnly do this when distributing the resulting artifact under appropriate dependency licenses and after understanding the security implications.\\n\\n## Verify the result\\n\\n```bash\\njar tf target/my-app-1.0.0.jar | head\\nunzip -p target/my-app-1.0.0.jar META-INF/MANIFEST.MF\\njava -jar target/my-app-1.0.0.jar --help\\n```\\n\\nRun integration tests against the packaged JAR, not only classes inside the Maven test process. Pin plugin versions, use a fixed Java toolchain, and avoid embedding secrets or environment-specific configuration.\\n\\nFor Spring Boot applications, prefer `spring-boot-maven-plugin`; its executable archive format and launcher handle dependencies differently from a generic shaded JAR."},{"id":"/spring-redis-question","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2017/spring-redis-question/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/spring-redis-question.md","title":"Common Spring Data Redis Problems and Solutions","description":"Troubleshoot Spring Data Redis serialization, connection pools, transactions, cache misses, and client-version compatibility.","date":"2017-07-20T21:02:14.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"spring","permalink":"/en/tags/spring"},{"inline":true,"label":"redis","permalink":"/en/tags/redis"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"spring-boot","permalink":"/en/tags/spring-boot"}],"readingTime":0.75,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Common Spring Data Redis Problems and Solutions","date":"2017-07-20T21:02:14.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2017/spring-redis-question/","tags":["spring","redis","java","spring-boot"],"description":"Troubleshoot Spring Data Redis serialization, connection pools, transactions, cache misses, and client-version compatibility.","keywords":["Spring Data Redis problems","Redis serialization","Lettuce Jedis"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Build an Executable JAR with Maven","permalink":"/en/2017/maven-package-execute-jar/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Configure HTTPS for Apache HTTP Server on CentOS 7","permalink":"/en/2016/centos7-apache2-config-https/"}},"content":"Spring Data Redis issues commonly come from mismatched serializers, connection settings, client versions, and assumptions about transactions or caching semantics.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nChoose serializers explicitly. String keys are easy to inspect, while values may use JSON with a stable schema. Java native serialization is fragile across class changes and unsafe for untrusted data.\\n\\nVerify whether the application uses Lettuce or Jedis and configure pooling only when the selected client and workload require it. Set connect, command, and shutdown timeouts; monitor exhausted pools and blocked commands.\\n\\nRedis transactions do not provide the same isolation model as relational databases. Understand `MULTI/EXEC`, connection binding, and Spring\'s transaction synchronization before combining Redis with database transactions.\\n\\nPrevent cache penetration and stampedes with input validation, short-lived negative caching, request coalescing or locks, randomized expiry, and bounded fallback load. Record Spring Boot, Spring Data Redis, Redis server, and client-library versions when diagnosing compatibility problems."},{"id":"/centos7-apache2-config-https","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2016/centos7-apache2-config-https/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/centos7-apache2-config-https.md","title":"Configure HTTPS for Apache HTTP Server on CentOS 7","description":"Configure an Apache HTTPS virtual host on CentOS 7, install certificate files, redirect HTTP, and validate the server configuration.","date":"2016-12-09T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"centos","permalink":"/en/tags/centos"},{"inline":true,"label":"apache2","permalink":"/en/tags/apache-2"},{"inline":true,"label":"https","permalink":"/en/tags/https"}],"readingTime":0.67,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Configure HTTPS for Apache HTTP Server on CentOS 7","date":"2016-12-09T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2016/centos7-apache2-config-https/","tags":["centos","apache2","https"],"description":"Configure an Apache HTTPS virtual host on CentOS 7, install certificate files, redirect HTTP, and validate the server configuration.","keywords":["CentOS 7 Apache HTTPS","SSL virtual host","httpd TLS"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Common Spring Data Redis Problems and Solutions","permalink":"/en/2017/spring-redis-question/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Install MySQL 5.7 on Linux","permalink":"/en/2016/mysql-5-7-x-install/"}},"content":"CentOS 7 is end-of-life, so use a supported operating system for new deployments. For a legacy host, install Apache and the TLS module, then configure a certificate issued for the site\'s hostname.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo yum install httpd mod_ssl\\nsudo apachectl configtest\\n```\\n\\nExample virtual host:\\n\\n```apache\\n<VirtualHost *:443>\\n    ServerName example.com\\n    DocumentRoot /var/www/example\\n\\n    SSLEngine on\\n    SSLCertificateFile /etc/pki/tls/certs/example.crt\\n    SSLCertificateKeyFile /etc/pki/tls/private/example.key\\n    SSLCertificateChainFile /etc/pki/tls/certs/example-chain.crt\\n</VirtualHost>\\n```\\n\\nRedirect HTTP to HTTPS:\\n\\n```apache\\n<VirtualHost *:80>\\n    ServerName example.com\\n    Redirect permanent / https://example.com/\\n</VirtualHost>\\n```\\n\\nValidate and reload:\\n\\n```bash\\nsudo apachectl configtest\\nsudo systemctl reload httpd\\n```\\n\\nProtect the private key, allow ports 80 and 443 through the firewall, use current protocols and ciphers, automate certificate renewal, and test the complete certificate chain from an external client."},{"id":"/mysql-5-7-x-install","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2016/mysql-5-7-x-install/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/mysql-5-7-x-install.md","title":"Install MySQL 5.7 on Linux","description":"Install and initialize MySQL 5.7, configure its data directory, service, root account, and basic security.","date":"2016-11-30T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"mysql","permalink":"/en/tags/mysql"}],"readingTime":0.67,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Install MySQL 5.7 on Linux","date":"2016-11-30T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2016/mysql-5-7-x-install/","tags":["mysql"],"description":"Install and initialize MySQL 5.7, configure its data directory, service, root account, and basic security.","keywords":["MySQL 5.7 install","mysqld initialize","MySQL Linux"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Configure HTTPS for Apache HTTP Server on CentOS 7","permalink":"/en/2016/centos7-apache2-config-https/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Build a RESTful Web Service with Spring Boot","permalink":"/en/2016/spring-boot-build-restful-web-service/"}},"content":"MySQL 5.7 is an older release and should be used only when application compatibility requires it. Prefer a supported current release for new systems.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nCreate a dedicated service account and directories, install the package or official binary distribution, then initialize the data directory:\\n\\n```bash\\nmysqld --initialize --user=mysql --basedir=/usr/local/mysql --datadir=/data/mysql\\n```\\n\\nRecord the temporary root password from the error log. Configure `my.cnf` with the correct `basedir`, `datadir`, socket, port, character set, and log paths. Start the service and change the root password immediately:\\n\\n```sql\\nALTER USER \'root\'@\'localhost\' IDENTIFIED BY \'a-long-random-password\';\\n```\\n\\nDo not expose port 3306 publicly. Restrict accounts by host, remove anonymous users and test databases, enable backups, monitor disk usage, and verify the upgrade path because MySQL 5.7 has reached end of life."},{"id":"/spring-boot-build-restful-web-service","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2016/spring-boot-build-restful-web-service/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/spring-boot-build-restful-web-service.md","title":"Build a RESTful Web Service with Spring Boot","description":"Build Spring Boot REST endpoints with controllers, request mapping, JSON DTOs, validation, status codes, and exception responses.","date":"2016-11-24T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"spring-boot","permalink":"/en/tags/spring-boot"},{"inline":true,"label":"spring","permalink":"/en/tags/spring"},{"inline":true,"label":"restful","permalink":"/en/tags/restful"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.59,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Build a RESTful Web Service with Spring Boot","date":"2016-11-24T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2016/spring-boot-build-restful-web-service/","tags":["spring-boot","spring","restful","java"],"description":"Build Spring Boot REST endpoints with controllers, request mapping, JSON DTOs, validation, status codes, and exception responses.","keywords":["Spring Boot REST API","RestController","Java web service"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Install MySQL 5.7 on Linux","permalink":"/en/2016/mysql-5-7-x-install/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Configure Maven Repositories and Mirrors","permalink":"/en/2016/maven-repository/"}},"content":"Spring Boot can expose JSON APIs with `@RestController` and request-mapping annotations.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```java\\n@RestController\\n@RequestMapping(\\"/api/users\\")\\nclass UserController {\\n    @GetMapping(\\"/{id}\\")\\n    ResponseEntity<UserDto> find(@PathVariable long id) {\\n        return ResponseEntity.ok(service.find(id));\\n    }\\n\\n    @PostMapping\\n    ResponseEntity<UserDto> create(@Valid @RequestBody CreateUserRequest request) {\\n        UserDto created = service.create(request);\\n        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.CREATED).body(created);\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nUse DTOs rather than exposing persistence entities directly. Apply Bean Validation to input and return accurate status codes such as `201`, `400`, `404`, and `409`.\\n\\nCentralize errors with `@RestControllerAdvice`:\\n\\n```java\\n@ExceptionHandler(UserNotFoundException.class)\\nResponseEntity<ProblemDetail> handleNotFound(UserNotFoundException ex) {\\n    return ResponseEntity.of(ProblemDetail.forStatusAndDetail(\\n        HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND, ex.getMessage())).build();\\n}\\n```\\n\\nVersion public contracts deliberately, document them with OpenAPI, authenticate sensitive operations, limit request sizes, and test serialization and failure responses as carefully as the success path."},{"id":"/maven-repository","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2016/maven-repository/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/maven-repository.md","title":"Configure Maven Repositories and Mirrors","description":"Configure Maven mirrors, repositories, credentials, and private artifact servers in settings.xml and project POM files.","date":"2016-11-23T22:58:32.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"maven","permalink":"/en/tags/maven"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.65,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Configure Maven Repositories and Mirrors","date":"2016-11-23T22:58:32.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2016/maven-repository/","tags":["maven","java"],"description":"Configure Maven mirrors, repositories, credentials, and private artifact servers in settings.xml and project POM files.","keywords":["Maven mirror settings","Maven repository","settings.xml"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Build a RESTful Web Service with Spring Boot","permalink":"/en/2016/spring-boot-build-restful-web-service/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Get JavaScript Function Names, Parameters, and Object Property Names","permalink":"/en/2016/js-get-function-name/"}},"content":"Maven resolves dependencies from repositories. A mirror in `settings.xml` can redirect requests to a faster or internally controlled repository manager.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```xml\\n<settings>\\n  <mirrors>\\n    <mirror>\\n      <id>company-mirror</id>\\n      <name>Company Maven Mirror</name>\\n      <url>https://repo.example.com/repository/maven-public/</url>\\n      <mirrorOf>*</mirrorOf>\\n    </mirror>\\n  </mirrors>\\n</settings>\\n```\\n\\n`mirrorOf=*` routes all repository requests through the mirror. In an enterprise environment, this supports caching, license review, malware scanning, and reproducible builds.\\n\\nCredentials belong in `settings.xml`, not in a committed `pom.xml`:\\n\\n```xml\\n<servers>\\n  <server>\\n    <id>company-mirror</id>\\n    <username>${env.MAVEN_REPO_USER}</username>\\n    <password>${env.MAVEN_REPO_PASSWORD}</password>\\n  </server>\\n</servers>\\n```\\n\\nWhen downloads fail, run Maven with `-X`, inspect the effective settings, verify proxy and TLS configuration, confirm that the artifact coordinates exist, and remove only the affected corrupted cache directory rather than deleting the entire local repository."},{"id":"/js-get-function-name","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2016/js-get-function-name/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/js-get-function-name.md","title":"Get JavaScript Function Names, Parameters, and Object Property Names","description":"Inspect JavaScript function names and object properties while understanding the limits of parameter parsing, minification, and closures.","date":"2016-01-24T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"javascript","permalink":"/en/tags/javascript"},{"inline":true,"label":"reflection","permalink":"/en/tags/reflection"}],"readingTime":0.62,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Get JavaScript Function Names, Parameters, and Object Property Names","date":"2016-01-24T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2016/js-get-function-name/","tags":["javascript","reflection"],"description":"Inspect JavaScript function names and object properties while understanding the limits of parameter parsing, minification, and closures.","keywords":["JavaScript function name","inspect function parameters","Object keys"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Configure Maven Repositories and Mirrors","permalink":"/en/2016/maven-repository/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Detect JavaScript Types with Object.prototype.toString.call","permalink":"/en/2015/js-class/"}},"content":"Modern functions expose a `name` property:\\n\\n```javascript\\nfunction calculateTotal(price, quantity) {}\\nconsole.log(calculateTotal.name); // calculateTotal\\n```\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nObject property names are available through standard reflection APIs:\\n\\n```javascript\\nconst value = {name: \\"Tom\\", age: 18};\\nconsole.log(Object.keys(value));\\nconsole.log(Object.getOwnPropertyNames(value));\\nconsole.log(Reflect.ownKeys(value));\\n```\\n\\nJavaScript has no reliable standard API that returns a function\'s declared parameter names. Parsing `Function.prototype.toString()` breaks on default values, destructuring, comments, transpilation, native functions, and minification. Use explicit metadata when parameter names are part of an application protocol.\\n\\nFunction names can also change or disappear after bundling and minification, so do not use them as stable identifiers. Closures hide lexical variables by design; they cannot be enumerated through normal reflection. For dependency injection, serialization, or routing, prefer explicit keys, decorators, schemas, or configuration."},{"id":"/js-class","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2015/js-class/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/js-class.md","title":"Detect JavaScript Types with Object.prototype.toString.call","description":"Compare typeof, Array.isArray, instanceof, and Object.prototype.toString.call for JavaScript type detection.","date":"2015-12-27T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"javascript","permalink":"/en/tags/javascript"},{"inline":true,"label":"prototype","permalink":"/en/tags/prototype"}],"readingTime":0.64,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Detect JavaScript Types with Object.prototype.toString.call","date":"2015-12-27T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2015/js-class/","tags":["javascript","prototype"],"description":"Compare typeof, Array.isArray, instanceof, and Object.prototype.toString.call for JavaScript type detection.","keywords":["JavaScript type detection","Object prototype toString","typeof"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Get JavaScript Function Names, Parameters, and Object Property Names","permalink":"/en/2016/js-get-function-name/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Implement Image Uploads for UEditor 1.3.6","permalink":"/en/2015/ueditor1-3-6-pic-upload/"}},"content":"`typeof` works well for primitives, but arrays, plain objects, and `null` require more specific checks. `Object.prototype.toString.call` exposes a useful built-in type tag.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```javascript\\nconst objectToString = Object.prototype.toString;\\n\\nobjectToString.call([123]);        // [object Array]\\nobjectToString.call(\\"123\\");        // [object String]\\nobjectToString.call({a: 1});       // [object Object]\\nobjectToString.call(/123/);        // [object RegExp]\\nobjectToString.call(123);          // [object Number]\\nobjectToString.call(undefined);    // [object Undefined]\\nobjectToString.call(null);         // [object Null]\\n```\\n\\nA reusable helper:\\n\\n```javascript\\nfunction getType(value) {\\n  return Object.prototype.toString.call(value).slice(8, -1).toLowerCase();\\n}\\n```\\n\\nUse `typeof` for strings, numbers, booleans, symbols, bigints, undefined, and functions. Use `Array.isArray(value)` when only arrays matter. `instanceof` is useful for custom classes but can fail across iframe or realm boundaries.\\n\\nObjects may customize their tag with `Symbol.toStringTag`, so this technique is not a security boundary. Validate required properties and data provenance when processing untrusted input."},{"id":"/ueditor1-3-6-pic-upload","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2015/ueditor1-3-6-pic-upload/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/ueditor1-3-6-pic-upload.md","title":"Implement Image Uploads for UEditor 1.3.6","description":"Implement UEditor 1.3.6 image uploads with compatible request parameters, storage paths, JSON responses, and server-side validation.","date":"2015-12-24T12:49:10.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"ueditor","permalink":"/en/tags/ueditor"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.78,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Implement Image Uploads for UEditor 1.3.6","date":"2015-12-24T12:49:10.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2015/ueditor1-3-6-pic-upload/","tags":["ueditor","java"],"description":"Implement UEditor 1.3.6 image uploads with compatible request parameters, storage paths, JSON responses, and server-side validation.","keywords":["UEditor 1.3.6 image upload","UEditor Java backend","upload response"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Detect JavaScript Types with Object.prototype.toString.call","permalink":"/en/2015/js-class/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Truncate Text with CSS Ellipsis","permalink":"/en/2015/css-limit-hidden/"}},"content":"UEditor\'s upload dialog sends a multipart request and expects a response in the editor\'s documented JSON format. The backend must match the field name and action used by the selected UEditor version.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nA successful response commonly contains fields such as:\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\"state\\": \\"SUCCESS\\",\\n  \\"url\\": \\"/uploads/2026/07/image.png\\",\\n  \\"title\\": \\"image.png\\",\\n  \\"original\\": \\"original.png\\",\\n  \\"type\\": \\".png\\",\\n  \\"size\\": 12345\\n}\\n```\\n\\nGenerate the stored filename on the server instead of trusting the submitted name. Normalize and validate paths, restrict file size and count, inspect actual content, and store uploads outside executable application directories.\\n\\nThe public URL and filesystem path are different concepts; map them explicitly. Return UTF-8 JSON with the expected content type and inspect the browser network panel when the editor reports a generic upload failure.\\n\\nUEditor 1.3.6 is old software. Before exposing it publicly, review known security issues, authentication, CSRF protection, upload authorization, image re-encoding, and whether migration to a maintained editor is more appropriate."},{"id":"/css-limit-hidden","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2015/css-limit-hidden/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/css-limit-hidden.md","title":"Truncate Text with CSS Ellipsis","description":"Truncate single-line and multi-line text with CSS ellipsis, including flexbox and table-layout fixes.","date":"2015-12-24T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"css","permalink":"/en/tags/css"},{"inline":true,"label":"overflow","permalink":"/en/tags/overflow"},{"inline":true,"label":"hidden","permalink":"/en/tags/hidden"}],"readingTime":0.91,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Truncate Text with CSS Ellipsis","date":"2015-12-24T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2015/css-limit-hidden/","tags":["css","overflow","hidden"],"description":"Truncate single-line and multi-line text with CSS ellipsis, including flexbox and table-layout fixes.","keywords":["CSS text ellipsis","line clamp","text overflow"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Implement Image Uploads for UEditor 1.3.6","permalink":"/en/2015/ueditor1-3-6-pic-upload/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Encode and Decode Unicode Escapes in JavaScript","permalink":"/en/2015/js-unicode-hex/"}},"content":"CSS cannot truncate text by an exact number of Chinese characters, but it can hide content according to an element\'s width or number of lines.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Single-line ellipsis\\n\\n```css\\n.text-ellipsis {\\n  width: 180px;\\n  overflow: hidden;\\n  white-space: nowrap;\\n  text-overflow: ellipsis;\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe element must have a constrained width. All three overflow-related properties are required.\\n\\n## Multi-line ellipsis\\n\\n```css\\n.text-ellipsis-2 {\\n  display: -webkit-box;\\n  overflow: hidden;\\n  line-clamp: 2;\\n  -webkit-line-clamp: 2;\\n  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;\\n}\\n```\\n\\nChange the clamp value to control the maximum number of visible lines.\\n\\n## Flexbox layouts\\n\\nA flex child may refuse to shrink because its default minimum width is based on its content. Add `min-width: 0`:\\n\\n```css\\n.item { display: flex; }\\n.item__content { min-width: 0; flex: 1; }\\n.item__title {\\n  overflow: hidden;\\n  white-space: nowrap;\\n  text-overflow: ellipsis;\\n}\\n```\\n\\n## Table cells\\n\\n```css\\n.data-table {\\n  width: 100%;\\n  table-layout: fixed;\\n}\\n.data-table td {\\n  overflow: hidden;\\n  white-space: nowrap;\\n  text-overflow: ellipsis;\\n}\\n```\\n\\nEllipsis changes only the visual presentation; the complete value remains in the DOM. For important information, provide an expand action, details page, or accessible full-text alternative."},{"id":"/js-unicode-hex","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2015/js-unicode-hex/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/js-unicode-hex.md","title":"Encode and Decode Unicode Escapes in JavaScript","description":"Encode and decode JavaScript Unicode escapes while handling UTF-16 code units, code points, surrogate pairs, and emoji.","date":"2015-12-10T14:20:13.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"javascript","permalink":"/en/tags/javascript"},{"inline":true,"label":"unicode","permalink":"/en/tags/unicode"},{"inline":true,"label":"encoding","permalink":"/en/tags/encoding"}],"readingTime":0.6,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Encode and Decode Unicode Escapes in JavaScript","date":"2015-12-10T14:20:13.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2015/js-unicode-hex/","tags":["javascript","unicode","encoding"],"description":"Encode and decode JavaScript Unicode escapes while handling UTF-16 code units, code points, surrogate pairs, and emoji.","keywords":["JavaScript Unicode escape","codePointAt","fromCodePoint"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Truncate Text with CSS Ellipsis","permalink":"/en/2015/css-limit-hidden/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Arbitrary-Precision Decimal Arithmetic in JavaScript","permalink":"/en/2015/js-bigdecimal/"}},"content":"JavaScript strings use UTF-16 code units. Characters in the Basic Multilingual Plane fit in one unit, while supplementary characters such as many emoji use a surrogate pair.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```javascript\\n\\"A\\".charCodeAt(0).toString(16); // 41\\n\\"\ud83d\ude00\\".codePointAt(0).toString(16); // 1f600\\nString.fromCodePoint(0x1f600); // \ud83d\ude00\\n```\\n\\nIterate by code point with `for...of`:\\n\\n```javascript\\nfunction toUnicodeEscapes(text) {\\n  return [...text].map(char => {\\n    const cp = char.codePointAt(0);\\n    return cp <= 0xffff\\n      ? `\\\\\\\\u${cp.toString(16).padStart(4, \\"0\\")}`\\n      : `\\\\\\\\u{${cp.toString(16)}}`;\\n  }).join(\\"\\");\\n}\\n```\\n\\nDo not confuse Unicode escapes with URL encoding, HTML entities, UTF-8 bytes, or Base64; they solve different representation problems. Avoid using `eval` to decode external escape sequences. Parse the expected syntax explicitly and reject malformed surrogate pairs or out-of-range code points."},{"id":"/js-bigdecimal","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2015/js-bigdecimal/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/js-bigdecimal.md","title":"Arbitrary-Precision Decimal Arithmetic in JavaScript","description":"Understand arbitrary-precision decimal arithmetic in JavaScript for money and measurement, including scale, rounding, parsing, comparison, and safe API design.","date":"2015-12-08T16:44:07.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"javascript","permalink":"/en/tags/javascript"},{"inline":true,"label":"bigdecimal","permalink":"/en/tags/bigdecimal"}],"readingTime":2.22,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Arbitrary-Precision Decimal Arithmetic in JavaScript","date":"2015-12-08T16:44:07.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2015/js-bigdecimal/","tags":["javascript","bigdecimal"],"description":"Understand arbitrary-precision decimal arithmetic in JavaScript for money and measurement, including scale, rounding, parsing, comparison, and safe API design.","keywords":["JavaScript BigDecimal","decimal arithmetic","avoid floating point errors"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Encode and Decode Unicode Escapes in JavaScript","permalink":"/en/2015/js-unicode-hex/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Test Spring MVC Controllers with MockMvc","permalink":"/en/2015/spring-mvc-test-by-mock/"}},"content":"Binary floating-point values cannot represent many decimal fractions exactly. This is why expressions such as `0.1 + 0.2` do not produce an exact decimal `0.3`. Financial, accounting, tax, pricing, and measurement code often needs decimal arithmetic with explicit precision and rounding.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Decimal representation\\n\\nA decimal implementation normally stores:\\n\\n```text\\nvalue = unscaledInteger \xd7 10^(-scale)\\n```\\n\\nFor example, `123.45` can be represented as an unscaled integer `12345` with scale `2`. Modern implementations may use `BigInt`, arrays of base-10 or base-1eN digits, or another arbitrary-precision integer representation.\\n\\n## Parse strings, not floating-point values\\n\\nConstruct decimal values from strings whenever exact decimal input matters:\\n\\n```javascript\\nconst price = new Decimal(\\"19.99\\");\\nconst quantity = new Decimal(\\"3\\");\\nconst total = price.times(quantity);\\n```\\n\\nPassing an already rounded JavaScript `number` cannot recover precision that was previously lost.\\n\\n## Core operations\\n\\nA useful decimal API should support:\\n\\n- addition and subtraction;\\n- multiplication and division;\\n- comparison and equality;\\n- scale changes and quantization;\\n- absolute value and negation;\\n- conversion to plain or scientific notation;\\n- configurable precision and rounding modes.\\n\\nDivision needs an explicit result scale or precision because many decimal divisions do not terminate:\\n\\n```javascript\\nconst result = new Decimal(\\"1\\")\\n  .div(new Decimal(\\"3\\"))\\n  .toDecimalPlaces(2, Decimal.ROUND_HALF_UP);\\n// 0.33\\n```\\n\\n## Rounding\\n\\nCommon modes include toward zero, away from zero, floor, ceiling, half-up, half-down, and half-even. The correct mode is a business rule, not merely a technical preference. Banker\'s rounding (`half-even`) reduces aggregate bias in some workloads, while tax regulations may require another method.\\n\\nAlways define where rounding occurs. Rounding each line item and then summing can differ from summing exact values and rounding only the final total.\\n\\n## Comparison\\n\\nDo not compare formatted strings or convert back to `number`:\\n\\n```javascript\\namount.comparedTo(limit) < 0\\namount.equals(other)\\n```\\n\\nDecide whether equality treats `1.0` and `1.00` as numerically equal or also considers scale. Both semantics are useful in different domains.\\n\\n## Money model\\n\\nFor a single currency with a fixed minor unit, storing integer cents is often simpler:\\n\\n```javascript\\nconst unitPriceCents = 1999n;\\nconst quantity = 3n;\\nconst totalCents = unitPriceCents * quantity;\\n```\\n\\nUse arbitrary-precision decimals when rates, percentages, multiple scales, currency conversion, or regulated rounding rules make integer minor units insufficient.\\n\\n## Serialization\\n\\nSerialize exact decimal values as strings unless both sides have a documented decimal-capable format:\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\"amount\\": \\"1234567890.123456\\"\\n}\\n```\\n\\nJSON numbers are usually parsed into binary floating-point values and may lose precision.\\n\\n## Production checklist\\n\\nUse a maintained decimal library rather than a copied historical implementation. Pin the version, test negative values and zero, define maximum precision, reject malformed or unbounded inputs, document rounding rules, and verify results against authoritative examples. Keep formatting separate from arithmetic so locale-specific commas, currency symbols, and display rounding do not affect stored values."},{"id":"/spring-mvc-test-by-mock","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2015/spring-mvc-test-by-mock/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/spring-mvc-test-by-mock.md","title":"Test Spring MVC Controllers with MockMvc","description":"Test Spring MVC endpoints with MockMvc, request builders, status and JSON assertions, security, and focused application contexts.","date":"2015-12-03T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"spring-mvc","permalink":"/en/tags/spring-mvc"},{"inline":true,"label":"spring","permalink":"/en/tags/spring"},{"inline":true,"label":"test","permalink":"/en/tags/test"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.56,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Test Spring MVC Controllers with MockMvc","date":"2015-12-03T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2015/spring-mvc-test-by-mock/","tags":["spring-mvc","spring","test","java"],"description":"Test Spring MVC endpoints with MockMvc, request builders, status and JSON assertions, security, and focused application contexts.","keywords":["Spring MockMvc test","controller unit test","Spring MVC testing"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Arbitrary-Precision Decimal Arithmetic in JavaScript","permalink":"/en/2015/js-bigdecimal/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Preview a Selected Image with JavaScript","permalink":"/en/2015/js-pic-preview/"}},"content":"`MockMvc` exercises Spring MVC request handling without starting a real HTTP server.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```java\\n@WebMvcTest(UserController.class)\\nclass UserControllerTest {\\n    @Autowired MockMvc mockMvc;\\n\\n    @MockBean UserService userService;\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void returnsUser() throws Exception {\\n        given(userService.findById(1L))\\n            .willReturn(new UserDto(1L, \\"Tom\\"));\\n\\n        mockMvc.perform(get(\\"/users/{id}\\", 1))\\n            .andExpect(status().isOk())\\n            .andExpect(content().contentTypeCompatibleWith(\\"application/json\\"))\\n            .andExpect(jsonPath(\\"$.id\\").value(1))\\n            .andExpect(jsonPath(\\"$.name\\").value(\\"Tom\\"));\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nUse `@WebMvcTest` for a focused controller slice and mock service dependencies. Use `@SpringBootTest` with `@AutoConfigureMockMvc` when filters, serialization, validation, security, and broader configuration must be integrated.\\n\\nAssert both success and failure contracts: invalid input, missing resources, authorization, content type, and exception-handler responses. Avoid assertions that depend on irrelevant JSON field order."},{"id":"/js-pic-preview","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2015/js-pic-preview/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/js-pic-preview.md","title":"Preview a Selected Image with JavaScript","description":"Preview a local image selected through a file input with the File API, object URLs, validation, and proper URL cleanup.","date":"2015-03-05T15:30:51.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"javascript","permalink":"/en/tags/javascript"},{"inline":true,"label":"image-preview","permalink":"/en/tags/image-preview"}],"readingTime":0.73,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Preview a Selected Image with JavaScript","date":"2015-03-05T15:30:51.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2015/js-pic-preview/","tags":["javascript","image-preview"],"description":"Preview a local image selected through a file input with the File API, object URLs, validation, and proper URL cleanup.","keywords":["JavaScript image preview","URL.createObjectURL","file input preview"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Test Spring MVC Controllers with MockMvc","permalink":"/en/2015/spring-mvc-test-by-mock/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Java Regular Expressions with Pattern and Matcher","permalink":"/en/2014/java-regex-class/"}},"content":"A browser can preview a file explicitly selected by the user without uploading it first. Validate the MIME type, size, and number of files before rendering the preview.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```html\\n<input id=\\"imageInput\\" type=\\"file\\" accept=\\"image/*\\">\\n<img id=\\"preview\\" alt=\\"Selected image preview\\" width=\\"200\\" height=\\"200\\">\\n\\n<script>\\nconst input = document.getElementById(\\"imageInput\\");\\nconst preview = document.getElementById(\\"preview\\");\\nlet currentUrl;\\n\\ninput.addEventListener(\\"change\\", () => {\\n  const file = input.files?.[0];\\n  if (!file) return;\\n\\n  if (!file.type.startsWith(\\"image/\\")) {\\n    input.value = \\"\\";\\n    throw new Error(\\"Please select an image file\\");\\n  }\\n\\n  if (currentUrl) URL.revokeObjectURL(currentUrl);\\n  currentUrl = URL.createObjectURL(file);\\n  preview.src = currentUrl;\\n});\\n\\nwindow.addEventListener(\\"beforeunload\\", () => {\\n  if (currentUrl) URL.revokeObjectURL(currentUrl);\\n});\\n<\/script>\\n```\\n\\n`URL.createObjectURL` avoids converting the complete file to Base64, making it efficient for previews. Revoke old URLs when they are replaced or no longer needed.\\n\\nClient-side validation improves usability but does not make an upload safe. The server must independently validate file size, content, extension, storage path, and authorization."},{"id":"/java-regex-class","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2014/java-regex-class/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/java-regex-class.md","title":"Java Regular Expressions with Pattern and Matcher","description":"Use Java Pattern and Matcher for full matches, searches, groups, replacement, escaping, flags, and performance-safe regex design.","date":"2014-12-22T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"regex","permalink":"/en/tags/regex"}],"readingTime":0.64,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Java Regular Expressions with Pattern and Matcher","date":"2014-12-22T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2014/java-regex-class/","tags":["java","regex"],"description":"Use Java Pattern and Matcher for full matches, searches, groups, replacement, escaping, flags, and performance-safe regex design.","keywords":["Java Pattern Matcher","Java regex groups","regular expression performance"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Preview a Selected Image with JavaScript","permalink":"/en/2015/js-pic-preview/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Design a Comment and Reply Data Model","permalink":"/en/2014/qqzone-comment-reply/"}},"content":"Java regular expressions are compiled into a `Pattern` and applied through a `Matcher`.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```java\\nPattern pattern = Pattern.compile(\\"(\\\\\\\\d{4})-(\\\\\\\\d{2})-(\\\\\\\\d{2})\\");\\nMatcher matcher = pattern.matcher(\\"date=2026-07-16\\");\\n\\nif (matcher.find()) {\\n    System.out.println(matcher.group(0));\\n    System.out.println(matcher.group(1));\\n}\\n```\\n\\nUse `matches()` when the complete input must match, `find()` to locate subsequences, and `lookingAt()` to match from the beginning. Named groups improve readability:\\n\\n```java\\nPattern.compile(\\"(?<year>\\\\\\\\d{4})-(?<month>\\\\\\\\d{2})-(?<day>\\\\\\\\d{2})\\");\\n```\\n\\nJava string literals require their own escaping, so a regex backslash is usually written as `\\\\\\\\`. Use `Pattern.quote` for literal input and `Matcher.quoteReplacement` for literal replacement values.\\n\\nCompile frequently reused patterns once. Avoid nested ambiguous quantifiers that can cause catastrophic backtracking on adversarial input. Apply input-size limits and prefer explicit parsers for complex structured formats."},{"id":"/qqzone-comment-reply","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2014/qqzone-comment-reply/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/qqzone-comment-reply.md","title":"Design a Comment and Reply Data Model","description":"Design comments and nested replies with parent relationships, reply targets, pagination, indexes, moderation, and efficient queries.","date":"2014-12-18T22:48:24.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"design","permalink":"/en/tags/design"},{"inline":true,"label":"sql","permalink":"/en/tags/sql"}],"readingTime":0.76,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Design a Comment and Reply Data Model","date":"2014-12-18T22:48:24.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2014/qqzone-comment-reply/","tags":["java","design","sql"],"description":"Design comments and nested replies with parent relationships, reply targets, pagination, indexes, moderation, and efficient queries.","keywords":["comment reply database design","nested comments SQL","threaded discussion"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Java Regular Expressions with Pattern and Matcher","permalink":"/en/2014/java-regex-class/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Read a Text File Line by Line in Java","permalink":"/en/2014/java-readline/"}},"content":"A discussion system usually needs to represent a top-level comment, its replies, and the user being replied to.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nA practical table can include:\\n\\n```text\\nid\\ncontent_id       -- post, article, or status being discussed\\nroot_id          -- top-level comment ID\\nparent_id        -- direct parent reply\\nauthor_id\\nreply_to_user_id\\nbody\\nstatus\\ncreated_at\\n```\\n\\nTop-level comments may use `root_id = id` after insertion and a null `parent_id`. Replies share the same `root_id`, which makes it efficient to fetch one thread while preserving the direct parent relationship.\\n\\nIndex `(content_id, status, created_at, id)` for top-level pagination and `(root_id, status, created_at, id)` for replies. Prefer cursor pagination to deep offsets on active content.\\n\\nDo not trust cached reply counts as the only source of truth. Update counters transactionally or reconcile them. Store moderation status rather than deleting immediately when auditability matters. Escape output, limit body size, rate-limit posting, enforce authorization, and avoid unbounded recursive queries or UI nesting."},{"id":"/java-readline","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2014/java-readline/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/java-readline.md","title":"Read a Text File Line by Line in Java","description":"Read large text files line by line with BufferedReader or Files.lines while handling character sets, malformed rows, and resource cleanup.","date":"2014-12-18T15:33:38.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.85,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Read a Text File Line by Line in Java","date":"2014-12-18T15:33:38.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2014/java-readline/","tags":["java"],"description":"Read large text files line by line with BufferedReader or Files.lines while handling character sets, malformed rows, and resource cleanup.","keywords":["Java read file line by line","BufferedReader","Files.lines"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Design a Comment and Reply Data Model","permalink":"/en/2014/qqzone-comment-reply/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Detect Client Device and Browser Information in Java","permalink":"/en/2014/java-get-device-name/"}},"content":"Reading a file line by line is appropriate for logs and other large text files because it avoids loading the complete file into memory. Always specify the character set and close streams reliably.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## BufferedReader example\\n\\n```java\\nimport com.google.gson.JsonObject;\\nimport java.io.BufferedReader;\\nimport java.io.BufferedWriter;\\nimport java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;\\nimport java.nio.file.Files;\\nimport java.nio.file.Path;\\n\\npublic class ConvertFile {\\n    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {\\n        Path input = Path.of(\\"c:/error.txt\\");\\n        Path output = Path.of(\\"c:/errorJson.txt\\");\\n        JsonObject json = new JsonObject();\\n\\n        try (BufferedReader reader = Files.newBufferedReader(\\n                input, StandardCharsets.UTF_8)) {\\n            String line;\\n            while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {\\n                String[] parts = line.split(\\"-\\", 2);\\n                if (parts.length == 2) {\\n                    json.addProperty(parts[0], parts[1]);\\n                }\\n            }\\n        }\\n\\n        try (BufferedWriter writer = Files.newBufferedWriter(\\n                output, StandardCharsets.UTF_8)) {\\n            writer.write(json.toString());\\n        }\\n    }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nUsing `split(\\"-\\", 2)` prevents later hyphens in the value from creating extra array elements. Decide how malformed rows should be logged or rejected instead of silently assuming every line has the expected format.\\n\\n## Files.lines\\n\\n```java\\ntry (var lines = Files.lines(input, StandardCharsets.UTF_8)) {\\n    lines.forEach(System.out::println);\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe returned `Stream` owns an open file handle and must be closed, so keep it inside try-with-resources."},{"id":"/java-get-device-name","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2014/java-get-device-name/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/java-get-device-name.md","title":"Detect Client Device and Browser Information in Java","description":"Parse HTTP User-Agent data in Java, handle proxy headers, and understand the limits of browser and device detection.","date":"2014-12-10T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"device","permalink":"/en/tags/device"},{"inline":true,"label":"regex","permalink":"/en/tags/regex"}],"readingTime":0.68,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Detect Client Device and Browser Information in Java","date":"2014-12-10T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2014/java-get-device-name/","tags":["java","device","regex"],"description":"Parse HTTP User-Agent data in Java, handle proxy headers, and understand the limits of browser and device detection.","keywords":["Java User-Agent parsing","detect browser Java","client device information"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Read a Text File Line by Line in Java","permalink":"/en/2014/java-readline/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Stream Audio to an HTML5 Audio Element","permalink":"/en/2014/html5-audio-file-stream-play/"}},"content":"A Java web server can inspect HTTP headers such as `User-Agent` to estimate the browser, operating system, and device category. The result is heuristic, not a trustworthy device identity.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```java\\nString userAgent = request.getHeader(\\"User-Agent\\");\\nString forwardedFor = request.getHeader(\\"X-Forwarded-For\\");\\n```\\n\\nWhen the application is behind a trusted reverse proxy, configure the framework to process forwarded headers correctly. Never trust arbitrary `X-Forwarded-For` values from direct clients.\\n\\nPrefer a maintained User-Agent parser over an expanding set of regular expressions. User-Agent reduction, browser privacy features, bots, embedded WebViews, and spoofing all limit accuracy.\\n\\nUse feature detection in the browser when behavior depends on capabilities. Do not use User-Agent parsing for authentication, licensing, fraud decisions, or a stable device identifier. Record only the minimum data needed and consider privacy and retention requirements."},{"id":"/html5-audio-file-stream-play","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2014/html5-audio-file-stream-play/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/html5-audio-file-stream-play.md","title":"Stream Audio to an HTML5 Audio Element","description":"Serve audio for HTML5 playback with correct content types, byte-range requests, content length, caching, and browser compatibility.","date":"2014-11-20T14:21:37.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"html5","permalink":"/en/tags/html-5"},{"inline":true,"label":"audio","permalink":"/en/tags/audio"}],"readingTime":0.76,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Stream Audio to an HTML5 Audio Element","date":"2014-11-20T14:21:37.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2014/html5-audio-file-stream-play/","tags":["java","html5","audio"],"description":"Serve audio for HTML5 playback with correct content types, byte-range requests, content length, caching, and browser compatibility.","keywords":["HTML5 audio streaming","HTTP Range audio","Java audio response"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Detect Client Device and Browser Information in Java","permalink":"/en/2014/java-get-device-name/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Generate CAPTCHA Images with Java","permalink":"/en/2014/java-checkcode/"}},"content":"An `<audio>` element can play a normal HTTP resource, but seeking and reliable playback depend on correct response headers and byte-range support.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```html\\n<audio controls preload=\\"metadata\\" src=\\"/media/song.mp3\\"></audio>\\n```\\n\\nThe server should send the real media type, such as `audio/mpeg`, and a correct `Content-Length`. When the request contains `Range: bytes=start-end`, validate the range and return:\\n\\n```text\\nHTTP/1.1 206 Partial Content\\nAccept-Ranges: bytes\\nContent-Range: bytes start-end/total\\nContent-Length: selected-length\\nContent-Type: audio/mpeg\\n```\\n\\nStream only the requested bytes instead of loading the complete file into memory. Reject invalid or unsatisfiable ranges with `416 Range Not Satisfiable`.\\n\\nSupport `HEAD`, conditional requests, and appropriate cache headers when needed. Keep path resolution inside an authorized media directory and enforce access control before opening a file. Browser codec support varies, so provide formats supported by the target platforms or use a transcoding pipeline."},{"id":"/java-checkcode","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2014/java-checkcode/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/java-checkcode.md","title":"Generate CAPTCHA Images with Java","description":"Generate a Java image CAPTCHA with random characters, drawing, noise, HTTP output, expiration, and server-side verification.","date":"2014-11-18T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"captcha","permalink":"/en/tags/captcha"}],"readingTime":0.75,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Generate CAPTCHA Images with Java","date":"2014-11-18T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2014/java-checkcode/","tags":["java","captcha"],"description":"Generate a Java image CAPTCHA with random characters, drawing, noise, HTTP output, expiration, and server-side verification.","keywords":["Java CAPTCHA generator","BufferedImage captcha","servlet verification code"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Stream Audio to an HTML5 Audio Element","permalink":"/en/2014/html5-audio-file-stream-play/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Use and Configure UEditor with a Java Backend","permalink":"/en/2014/ueditor-use-and-config/"}},"content":"A basic image CAPTCHA generates a random challenge, stores its expected value on the server, draws the characters into an image, and returns the image with no-cache headers.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nUse `SecureRandom` rather than predictable `Random` for challenge generation. Render with `BufferedImage` and `Graphics2D`, add moderate distortion or noise, and write the response with `ImageIO`.\\n\\nThe expected answer should be stored in a short-lived server-side session or challenge record, never trusted from a hidden form field. Compare answers in constant, normalized form where practical, expire them quickly, invalidate after success, and rate-limit attempts.\\n\\n```java\\nresponse.setContentType(\\"image/png\\");\\nresponse.setHeader(\\"Cache-Control\\", \\"no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate\\");\\nImageIO.write(image, \\"png\\", response.getOutputStream());\\n```\\n\\nA homemade visual CAPTCHA is not a strong bot defense by itself and may create accessibility problems. For higher-risk systems, combine rate limits, abuse detection, device and session signals, accessible alternatives, and a maintained challenge service."},{"id":"/ueditor-use-and-config","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2014/ueditor-use-and-config/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/ueditor-use-and-config.md","title":"Use and Configure UEditor with a Java Backend","description":"Initialize UEditor, configure toolbar and server endpoints, implement upload actions, map public URLs, and secure editor content.","date":"2014-10-25T19:26:27.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"ueditor","permalink":"/en/tags/ueditor"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":0.8,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Use and Configure UEditor with a Java Backend","date":"2014-10-25T19:26:27.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2014/ueditor-use-and-config/","tags":["ueditor","java"],"description":"Initialize UEditor, configure toolbar and server endpoints, implement upload actions, map public URLs, and secure editor content.","keywords":["UEditor configuration","UEditor Java backend","rich text editor upload"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Generate CAPTCHA Images with Java","permalink":"/en/2014/java-checkcode/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Read Values from JSON and JavaScript Objects","permalink":"/en/2014/json-get-value-method/"}},"content":"UEditor consists of a browser editor and a server-side action endpoint used for configuration, uploads, image listing, and related operations.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nInitialize the editor with a stable element ID and explicit options:\\n\\n```html\\n<script id=\\"editor\\" type=\\"text/plain\\"><\/script>\\n<script>\\nconst editor = UE.getEditor(\\"editor\\", {\\n  initialFrameHeight: 420,\\n  autoHeightEnabled: false,\\n  serverUrl: \\"/ueditor/controller\\"\\n});\\n<\/script>\\n```\\n\\nThe backend should return the configuration and action-specific JSON schema expected by the installed UEditor release. Keep filesystem paths separate from public URLs, generate filenames server-side, and return normalized UTF-8 responses.\\n\\nRestrict toolbar features to those the product actually needs. Validate upload size, type, content, count, and authorization on the server. Store files outside executable directories and prevent path traversal.\\n\\nRich-text HTML is untrusted input. Sanitize it with an allowlist before storage or rendering, enforce CSRF protection, and apply a content security policy. UEditor is legacy software, so review known vulnerabilities and consider a maintained editor before deploying a new public system."},{"id":"/json-get-value-method","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2014/json-get-value-method/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/json-get-value-method.md","title":"Read Values from JSON and JavaScript Objects","description":"Parse JSON strings and read fixed, dynamic, special, and nested properties with dot notation, brackets, iteration, and optional chaining.","date":"2014-08-20T15:27:56.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"javascript","permalink":"/en/tags/javascript"},{"inline":true,"label":"json","permalink":"/en/tags/json"}],"readingTime":0.72,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Read Values from JSON and JavaScript Objects","date":"2014-08-20T15:27:56.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2014/json-get-value-method/","tags":["javascript","json"],"description":"Parse JSON strings and read fixed, dynamic, special, and nested properties with dot notation, brackets, iteration, and optional chaining.","keywords":["JavaScript JSON access","dynamic object property","optional chaining"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Use and Configure UEditor with a Java Backend","permalink":"/en/2014/ueditor-use-and-config/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Submit a Dynamically Generated Form with jQuery","permalink":"/en/2014/jquery-build-form/"}},"content":"\u201cReading a JSON value\u201d usually involves two operations: parse a JSON string into a JavaScript object, then access properties on that object.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```javascript\\nconst text = \'{\\"name\\":\\"Tom\\",\\"age\\":18}\';\\nconst user = JSON.parse(text);\\n\\nconsole.log(user.name);\\nconsole.log(user[\\"age\\"]);\\n```\\n\\nUse dot notation for fixed identifier-like names. Use brackets for dynamic or special names:\\n\\n```javascript\\nconst key = \\"name\\";\\nconsole.log(user[key]);\\n\\nconst config = {\\n  \\"user-name\\": \\"Tom\\",\\n  \\"display name\\": \\"Tom Cat\\"\\n};\\nconsole.log(config[\\"user-name\\"]);\\n```\\n\\nDynamic keys can be assembled normally:\\n\\n```javascript\\nfor (let i = 1; i <= 3; i++) {\\n  console.log(data[`r${i}`]);\\n}\\n```\\n\\nIterate with `Object.keys`, `Object.values`, or `Object.entries`:\\n\\n```javascript\\nfor (const [key, value] of Object.entries(data)) {\\n  console.log(key, value);\\n}\\n```\\n\\nUse optional chaining when intermediate properties may be absent:\\n\\n```javascript\\nconst name = result.user?.profile?.name ?? \\"Not set\\";\\n```\\n\\nOnly strings need `JSON.parse`. Many HTTP libraries already return parsed objects, and parsing them again causes an error."},{"id":"/jquery-build-form","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2014/jquery-build-form/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/jquery-build-form.md","title":"Submit a Dynamically Generated Form with jQuery","description":"Build and submit a temporary HTML form with jQuery for POST navigation or file downloads, while avoiding browser compatibility and injection problems.","date":"2014-08-20T15:11:19.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"javascript","permalink":"/en/tags/javascript"},{"inline":true,"label":"jquery","permalink":"/en/tags/jquery"},{"inline":true,"label":"form","permalink":"/en/tags/form"}],"readingTime":1.12,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Submit a Dynamically Generated Form with jQuery","date":"2014-08-20T15:11:19.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2014/jquery-build-form/","tags":["javascript","jquery","form"],"description":"Build and submit a temporary HTML form with jQuery for POST navigation or file downloads, while avoiding browser compatibility and injection problems.","keywords":["jQuery dynamic form submit","JavaScript POST redirect","temporary HTML form"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Read Values from JSON and JavaScript Objects","permalink":"/en/2014/json-get-value-method/"},"nextItem":{"title":"A Dangerous C Disk-Write Example and How to Study It Safely","permalink":"/en/2013/first-virus/"}},"content":"A dynamically generated form is useful when a page must perform a normal browser navigation with a `POST` request, such as exporting a file with parameters. This avoids keeping a hidden form in the page markup.\\n\\nUse DOM APIs to assign field values. Do not concatenate untrusted data into HTML strings, because that can break the markup or introduce an injection vulnerability.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nThe following legacy example creates a form, appends it to the document, submits it, and then removes it:\\n\\n```javascript\\nvar result = $(\\"#printDIV\\").html();\\nvar xlsName = \\"excel-file\\";\\nvar url = \\"exportExcel/export\\";\\n\\nvar form = $(\\"<form></form>\\");\\nform.attr(\\"action\\", url);\\nform.attr(\\"method\\", \\"post\\");\\n\\nform.append($(\\"<textarea></textarea>\\").attr(\\"name\\", \\"result\\").val(result));\\nform.append($(\\"<textarea></textarea>\\").attr(\\"name\\", \\"xlsName\\").val(xlsName));\\n\\nform.appendTo(\\"body\\").trigger(\\"submit\\");\\nform.remove();\\n```\\n\\nAppending the form to `body` is important for compatibility with older browsers and ensures that the form participates in the document before submission.\\n\\n## Modern JavaScript version\\n\\njQuery is not required for this pattern:\\n\\n```javascript\\nfunction postNavigate(url, values) {\\n  const form = document.createElement(\\"form\\");\\n  form.method = \\"post\\";\\n  form.action = url;\\n\\n  for (const [name, value] of Object.entries(values)) {\\n    const input = document.createElement(\\"input\\");\\n    input.type = \\"hidden\\";\\n    input.name = name;\\n    input.value = String(value);\\n    form.appendChild(input);\\n  }\\n\\n  document.body.appendChild(form);\\n  form.submit();\\n  form.remove();\\n}\\n\\npostNavigate(\\"exportExcel/export\\", {\\n  result: document.querySelector(\\"#printDIV\\").innerHTML,\\n  xlsName: \\"excel-file\\"\\n});\\n```\\n\\nFor ordinary API calls that do not require a full-page navigation or native download flow, use `fetch()` instead."},{"id":"/first-virus","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2013/first-virus/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/first-virus.md","title":"A Dangerous C Disk-Write Example and How to Study It Safely","description":"Analyze an early C program that writes to a physical disk, understand why it can destroy boot data, and learn how to reproduce the concept safely with an ordinary file.","date":"2013-03-10T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"security","permalink":"/en/tags/security"},{"inline":true,"label":"c","permalink":"/en/tags/c"}],"readingTime":1.35,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"A Dangerous C Disk-Write Example and How to Study It Safely","date":"2013-03-10T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2013/first-virus/","tags":["security","c"],"description":"Analyze an early C program that writes to a physical disk, understand why it can destroy boot data, and learn how to reproduce the concept safely with an ordinary file.","keywords":["C physical disk write","destructive code analysis","safe malware lab"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Submit a Dynamically Generated Form with jQuery","permalink":"/en/2014/jquery-build-form/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Convert Numbers Between Bases in Java","permalink":"/en/2013/java-any-hex-convert/"}},"content":"This early C exercise demonstrates how a program can open a Windows physical drive and overwrite its first sector.\\n\\n**Warning:** the original code can corrupt critical disk structures, make the operating system unbootable, and cause permanent data loss. Do not run it on a real machine or any disk containing valuable data. It is retained here only as a security-education example. A safe exercise should replace the physical-drive path with an ordinary test file inside an isolated virtual machine.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n```c\\n#include <stdio.h>\\n#include <stdlib.h>\\n\\nint main()\\n{\\n    char buffer[512] = \\"0\\";\\n    FILE *fd = fopen(\\"\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\.\\\\\\\\PHYSICALDRIVE0\\", \\"rb+\\");\\n    if (fd == NULL)\\n        return 0;\\n\\n    fseek(fd, 0, SEEK_SET);\\n    fwrite(buffer, 512, 1, fd);\\n    printf(\\"hello, your disk has been modified!\\\\n\\");\\n    fclose(fd);\\n    return 0;\\n}\\n```\\n\\n## Why the code is dangerous\\n\\n`\\\\\\\\.\\\\PHYSICALDRIVE0` refers to the first physical disk on Windows rather than to a normal file. The program requests read/write access, seeks to byte zero, and writes 512 bytes. Depending on the disk layout, that area may contain a master boot record, partition metadata, or other structures needed to locate data.\\n\\nModern Windows versions normally require elevated privileges for raw-disk access, but permission checks are not a safety mechanism for experimental code. Running the program as an administrator can still cause immediate damage.\\n\\n## A safe replacement\\n\\nTo study file positioning and binary writes, change the target to a disposable file:\\n\\n```c\\nFILE *fd = fopen(\\"disk-image.bin\\", \\"wb+\\");\\n```\\n\\nCreate the file in a temporary directory, write known bytes, and inspect it with a hex editor. This preserves the learning objective\u2014understanding `fopen`, `fseek`, and `fwrite`\u2014without touching a physical device."},{"id":"/java-any-hex-convert","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2013/java-any-hex-convert/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/java-any-hex-convert.md","title":"Convert Numbers Between Bases in Java","description":"Convert integers and arbitrary-size values between bases 2 and 36 with Integer and BigInteger, including validation and negative values.","date":"2013-03-10T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"},{"inline":true,"label":"radix","permalink":"/en/tags/radix"}],"readingTime":0.85,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Convert Numbers Between Bases in Java","date":"2013-03-10T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2013/java-any-hex-convert/","tags":["java","radix"],"description":"Convert integers and arbitrary-size values between bases 2 and 36 with Integer and BigInteger, including validation and negative values.","keywords":["Java radix conversion","BigInteger base conversion","decimal to hexadecimal"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"A Dangerous C Disk-Write Example and How to Study It Safely","permalink":"/en/2013/first-virus/"},"nextItem":{"title":"Generate a 9\xd79 Multiplication Table with JavaScript","permalink":"/en/2013/javascript-jiujiuchengfabiao/"}},"content":"Java\'s standard library supports conversions between bases 2 and 36. Digits `0`\u2013`9` represent values zero through nine, while letters `a`\u2013`z` represent values ten through thirty-five.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Convert decimal integers\\n\\n```java\\nint value = 255;\\nSystem.out.println(Integer.toString(value, 2));  // 11111111\\nSystem.out.println(Integer.toString(value, 8));  // 377\\nSystem.out.println(Integer.toString(value, 16)); // ff\\nSystem.out.println(Integer.toString(value, 36)); // 73\\n```\\n\\nConvenience methods are also available:\\n\\n```java\\nInteger.toBinaryString(255);\\nInteger.toOctalString(255);\\nInteger.toHexString(255);\\n```\\n\\n## Convert arbitrary-size values\\n\\n```java\\nimport java.math.BigInteger;\\n\\nstatic String convert(String value, int sourceRadix, int targetRadix) {\\n    if (sourceRadix < Character.MIN_RADIX || sourceRadix > Character.MAX_RADIX ||\\n        targetRadix < Character.MIN_RADIX || targetRadix > Character.MAX_RADIX) {\\n        throw new IllegalArgumentException(\\"radix must be between 2 and 36\\");\\n    }\\n\\n    return new BigInteger(value, sourceRadix).toString(targetRadix);\\n}\\n\\nSystem.out.println(convert(\\"ff\\", 16, 2)); // 11111111\\n```\\n\\n`BigInteger` preserves values that exceed `long`. Negative values are supported, and output letters are lowercase by default. Use `toUpperCase()` when uppercase hexadecimal output is required.\\n\\nInvalid characters or unsupported radices cause `NumberFormatException` or `IllegalArgumentException`. Do not parse a large value as `int` or `long` before creating the `BigInteger`, because overflow may already have occurred."},{"id":"/javascript-jiujiuchengfabiao","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2013/javascript-jiujiuchengfabiao/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/javascript-jiujiuchengfabiao.md","title":"Generate a 9\xd79 Multiplication Table with JavaScript","description":"Generate a triangular multiplication table with nested loops and render it in the console or as an HTML table.","date":"2013-03-10T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"javascript","permalink":"/en/tags/javascript"}],"readingTime":0.47,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Generate a 9\xd79 Multiplication Table with JavaScript","date":"2013-03-10T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2013/javascript-jiujiuchengfabiao/","tags":["javascript"],"description":"Generate a triangular multiplication table with nested loops and render it in the console or as an HTML table.","keywords":["JavaScript multiplication table","nested loops","DOM table"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Convert Numbers Between Bases in Java","permalink":"/en/2013/java-any-hex-convert/"},"nextItem":{"title":"2012 Lanqiao Cup Java Vocational Problems: Analysis and Techniques","permalink":"/en/2013/2012-lqb-java/"}},"content":"A multiplication table is a simple exercise for understanding nested loops.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\nConsole output:\\n\\n```javascript\\nfor (let row = 1; row <= 9; row++) {\\n  const cells = [];\\n  for (let column = 1; column <= row; column++) {\\n    cells.push(`${column} \xd7 ${row} = ${column * row}`);\\n  }\\n  console.log(cells.join(\\"\\\\t\\"));\\n}\\n```\\n\\nDOM rendering:\\n\\n```javascript\\nconst table = document.createElement(\\"table\\");\\n\\nfor (let row = 1; row <= 9; row++) {\\n  const tr = document.createElement(\\"tr\\");\\n  for (let column = 1; column <= row; column++) {\\n    const td = document.createElement(\\"td\\");\\n    td.textContent = `${column} \xd7 ${row} = ${column * row}`;\\n    tr.appendChild(td);\\n  }\\n  table.appendChild(tr);\\n}\\n\\ndocument.body.appendChild(table);\\n```\\n\\nUsing `textContent` avoids HTML injection and makes the generated structure easy to style with CSS."},{"id":"/2012-lqb-java","metadata":{"permalink":"/en/2013/2012-lqb-java/","source":"@site/i18n/en/docusaurus-plugin-content-blog/2012-lqb-java.md","title":"2012 Lanqiao Cup Java Vocational Problems: Analysis and Techniques","description":"Analyze the 2012 Lanqiao Cup Java vocational problems with algorithm selection, input and output handling, complexity, and contest implementation advice.","date":"2013-01-27T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"lanqiao-cup","permalink":"/en/tags/lanqiao-cup"},{"inline":true,"label":"java","permalink":"/en/tags/java"}],"readingTime":1.29,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Apache Wangye","title":"Software developer and technical writer","url":"https://github.com/jsbxyyx","imageURL":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/avatar.jpg"}],"frontMatter":{"title":"2012 Lanqiao Cup Java Vocational Problems: Analysis and Techniques","date":"2013-01-27T00:00:00.000Z","lang":"en","translation_of":"/2013/2012-lqb-java/","tags":["lanqiao-cup","java"],"description":"Analyze the 2012 Lanqiao Cup Java vocational problems with algorithm selection, input and output handling, complexity, and contest implementation advice.","keywords":["2012 Lanqiao Cup Java","programming contest problems","Java algorithms"],"image":"https://xxzkid.github.io/img/top2.jpg"},"unlisted":false,"lastUpdatedAt":1784343104000,"prevItem":{"title":"Generate a 9\xd79 Multiplication Table with JavaScript","permalink":"/en/2013/javascript-jiujiuchengfabiao/"}},"content":"This article reviews the 2012 Lanqiao Cup Java vocational-group problems and the programming techniques commonly required to solve them.\\n\\n\x3c!-- more --\x3e\\n\\n## Read the problem as a specification\\n\\nIdentify the exact input range, required output format, edge cases, and whether the task asks for a value, count, arrangement, or proof. Small input bounds may permit enumeration; larger bounds usually require dynamic programming, graph algorithms, number theory, or an optimized data structure.\\n\\n## Build the simplest correct model\\n\\nTypical contest patterns include:\\n\\n- nested loops and simulation;\\n- string and digit processing;\\n- recursion, permutations, and backtracking;\\n- greatest common divisor and modular arithmetic;\\n- sorting, binary search, and prefix sums;\\n- dynamic programming for repeated subproblems.\\n\\nBefore coding, estimate time and memory complexity. An `O(n\xb2)` solution may be acceptable for a few thousand elements but not for millions.\\n\\n## Java implementation details\\n\\nUse buffered input and output when the data set is large. Prefer `long` when intermediate arithmetic can exceed the `int` range. Keep indexing conventions consistent and test minimum, maximum, duplicate, empty, and boundary cases.\\n\\n```java\\nBufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(\\n    new InputStreamReader(System.in));\\nStringBuilder output = new StringBuilder();\\n```\\n\\n## Contest workflow\\n\\nFirst implement a clear baseline solution and verify it against hand-calculated examples. Optimize only after identifying the actual bottleneck. During the contest, preserve working versions, avoid unnecessary framework code, and compare the final output exactly with the required format.\\n\\nThe original article contains the individual problem attempts and code. Their lasting value is the reasoning process: translate the statement into a precise model, select an algorithm supported by the constraints, and validate every boundary condition."}]}}')}}]);